<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-117  NEW PROTEIN TECHNOLOGIES: OUTLOOK FOR MANUFACTURING TECHNOLOGIES & MATERIALS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-117  NEW PROTEIN TECHNOLOGIES: OUTLOOK FOR MANUFACTURING TECHNOLOGIES & MATERIALS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>GOALS AND OBJECTIVES OF STUDY</B><P>

The goals of this study are to quantify materials used for the
manufacture of proteins and peptides, and to forecast changes to
l995. The objective is to elucidate the impact of biotechnology,
and other important influences, on the supply of materials.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR STUDY</B><P>

The first phase of the biotechnology revolution focuses on the
manipulation of genes, the second on the manufacture of proteins
and peptides. As the biotechnology revolution progresses, an
increasing number of proteins and peptides will be produced, and
the ways of manufacture will also shift. These changes bring with
them new, and different, demands for manufacturing materials.
Proteins and peptides already are big business, even without
biotechnology, and the ways even they are manufactured are being
touched.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF STUDY</B><P>

Most studies of this type focus on new proteins and peptides coming
out of the biotechnology revolution, but ignore all the other
proteins and peptides already on the market. They also tend to
ignore the implications of new developments on post-genetic aspects
and the materials of manufacture. This study, on the other hand,
takes an integrated approach, and examines the entire field of
proteins and peptides, with emphasis on their methods of
manufacture and their materials requirements.<P>

<B>AUDIENCE FOR REPORT</B><P>

Readers of this report are expected to have interests in business
aspects of science and technology. They may have titles such as
product managers, sales managers, marketing managers, strategic
planners, business development  managers, financial investors, and
the like. Scientific and technological developments are interpreted
for their significance to business interests. The report serves
both protein/peptide manufacturers and materials suppliers.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The report divides into cohesive units for ready access. After the
INTRODUCTION and SUMMARY, the report opens with an OVERVIEW OF
PROTEINS AND THEIR  MANUFACTURE  & SUPPLY to place the topic into
context. Next, the section on PROTEIN/PEPTIDE MANUFACTURING
TECHNOLOGIES goes into depth regarding process descriptions,
applications of the technologies, materials requirements and major
materials suppliers in each manufacturing category. The third
section presents the MATERIALS INDUSTRY STRUCTURE, explaining the
organizational supply of materials for proteins and peptides. A
special addendum is a discussion of important strategies for
staying competitive in the 1990s. Section four analyzes MARKETS FOR
MANUFACTURING MATERIALS BY MATERIALS TYPES, and section five
analyzes MARKETS FOR MANUFACTURING MATERIALS BY PROTEIN
APPLICATIONS. These two sections break down materials consumption
comprehensively. The next three sections provide information on
GOVERNMENT REGULATION, INTERNATIONAL ASPECTS and a selection of
COMPANY PROFILES. The report ends with six APPENDICES, including a
DIRECTORY of MATERIALS SUPPLIERS.<P>

Since this report's emphasis is on manufacture and materials, this
study has only brief discussions of the end markets and sales of
proteins and peptides.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

For accounting purposes, this report uses the biochemical
definition of proteins and peptides, which is in conformance with
the definition used by the Protein Data Bank. We exclude polyamides
in the plastics sense and we exclude penicillins. Proteins and
peptides generally refer to refined, or semi-refined, identifiable
substances; we exclude whole cells and complex mixtures such as
muscle, and we exclude "active principles" recognizable merely as
chromatogram spots. This study pays most attention to the initial
generation of proteins and peptides in the raw, bulk production
sense. Post-production operations are accounted for separately.<P>

This study uses a harmonized system of accounting. Materials for
proteins that may fit more than one protein category are accounted
for in one place only; thus, for example, a protein or peptide that
could fit the blood protein or peptide hormone category is
accounted for only once. This system ensures the avoidance of
double-counting errors. Readers, for their own particular
interests, may wish to assemble and tailor data from this report
to suit their own needs.<P>

Materials consumption is presented in terms of combined sales and
captive use. Quantities are expressed in pounds (lbs.) and
kilograms (kg), and liquid materials are converted to a weight
basis through density considerations. Values are in U.S. currency,
expressed in millions of dollars, where $1 million equals $1 MM
equals $1 x 106. A billion is 109.<P>

All analyses are made independently and objectively, without any
biases of vested interest. Mention of companies and products are
not endorsements; omissions if any are not intentional.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Direct sources of information came from telephone interviews with
over forty individuals representing protein manufacturers and
materials suppliers. We also obtained copious company and product
literature, from both here and abroad. In addition, we examined the
scientific and patent literature. In some instances data were
obtained from those we interviewed. In other instances we made
informed estimates. Where we made calculations, we explain what  we
did and give our assumptions.<P>

<B>CREDENTIALS AND RELATED WORK</B><P>

The analyst for this study is a biochemist, formally educated in
protein chemistry, having both academic and industrial experience
in the field. He also holds an MBA in marketing and has been
writing studies for BCC for many years. Among the published studies
the analyst has written are C-065: Bioengineered Medical Proteins,
C-057: The Vaccine Industry, C-088: Polyclonal and Monoclonal
Antibodies, and C-105: Specialty Enzymes.<P>

BCC studies related to the present topic but done by others
include:
<PRE>
    C-012R   Water-Soluble Polymers
    C-056R   The Amino Acid Business
    C-071R   The Blood Industry
    C-073    High-Tech Separations For Biotechnology
    C-083    Media & Sera For Cell Culture
    C-096    Feedstocks For Fermentation
    GA-043R  Processed Protein Foods<P>
</PRE>

