<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-121  FOOD TESTING REAGENTS: IMPACT OF NEW REGULATIONS AND
BIOTECHNOLOGY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-121  FOOD TESTING REAGENTS: IMPACT OF NEW REGULATIONS AND
BIOTECHNOLOGY
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS OF STUDY
</B><P>
The objectives of this study are to:  (1) Relate how foods are
analyzed for  components and  contaminants; (2)  Elucidate the
forces for  change in  food testing  and  the  application  of
reagents; (3)  Estimate current  U.S. sales  of  food  testing
reagents and  forecast their  sales to 1997.  The goals are to
provide meaningful  information, data, and analysis to help in
strategic, marketing, and product planning.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTION</B><P>

Recent proposed  changes in  food labeling regulations promise
to reshape  food testing  and influence  reagent sales.   Even
without  their   implementation,  however,   food  testing  is
undergoing  significant   changes  as   a  result   of   other
regulations, consumer pressures for increased food safety, and
new testing  technologies.   Although the  overall market  for
food testing reagents will likely grow in the near future, the
shares held  by the  various types  of  testing  reagents  are
likely to change and shift, dramatically in some instances.<P>

As a  consequence of  the changing  scene,  it  is  critically
important to  grasp the  ramifications of  the complex market,
regulatory, and  technological forces  on the  sales  of  food
testing reagents.  BCC's contribution is to shed light on this
topic and  quantify the  changes  with  independent,  unbiased
analysis.<P>


<B>AUDIENCE</B><P>

This study  is written  expressly for  business  managers  and
executives, both in testing product supply and testing product
use.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT OF STUDY</B><P>

See Table  of Contents.   This  study is about analytical food
testing, which  concerns the  detection,  identification,  and
quantification of  substances in  foods.   Emphasis is  on the
applications and sales of reagents for food testing.<P>

This study  is not  about analytical  reagents or  reagents in
general.   This  study  also  excludes  reagents  for  on-farm
agricultural testing  or environmental  analysis.   This study
excludes analytical  instrumentation except to a minor extent,
and then  only qualitatively  for the impact on reagent sales.<P>

This study  is not  about food  toxicology, food  manufacture,
food markets,  or the  remediation of  food  safety  problems.
Also excluded  are human health and medical aspects, except in
relation to food testing concerns.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This study  defines foods  as products for nutritive ingestion
by eating and drinking, and conceptually includes products for
both  humans   and  animals.    Food  testing  is  defined  as
analytical tests  for food  components and  food contaminants,
and analytical reagents for food testing as chemistry-based or
biology-based products  for the detection, identification, and
quantitation of substances in foods.<P>

Excluded from this study are pharmaceutical nutriments such as
parenteral vitamins  and  amino  acids,  vitamin  and  mineral
pills, and  drinking water  from tap.    The  emphasis  is  on
processed and  "manufactured" foods and beverages, but certain
aspects of  on-the-farm  agricultural  testing  are  included.
This study  also excludes  food toxicology  testing, taste and
consumer preference  testing, and  physical properties testing
such as texture, mouthfeel, and other such testing.<P>

Primary  sources   of  information  and  data  were  telephone
interviews with representatives of testing reagent, suppliers,
testing reagent  users, and others expert and knowledgeable in
the field  of food  testing.  Secondary sources of information
and data included company product literature, general business
literature,  scientific  literature,  government  studies  and
reports,  various   reference  texts,   and   numerous   trade
publications.<P>

All discussion  and analysis refers to the U.S. only,
unless specifically  indicated otherwise.  We estimate current
sales for  1992, and  forecast sales  to 1997 in constant 1992
dollars to  reflect  real  changes  without  inflation.  Sales
figures are  in millions  of dollars,  where  $1  MM  is  $One
million, which is $106.  The average annual growth rate, AAGR,
is derived  by the compounding method using standard tables of
net present  value.   Sales are  estimated for the supplier to
user transaction, and may not necessarily reflect manufacturer
level.<P>

All information,  analysis, and  assessment are  gathered  and
made independently,  and  without  bias  or  vested  interest.
Omissions of  companies or  products are  not intentional, and
mentions are not endorsements.<P>


<B>CREDENTIALS, RELATED STUDIES</B><P>

The analyst  for this  study is a chemist and biochemist, also
having an  MBA degree  in marketing.  He has had many years
of experience  in the  food industry.    BCC  studies  he  has
written  include   ones  on   clinical  diagnostic   reagents,
biohazard testing  (toxicology), cancer  diagnostics,  medical
diagnostic kits, and many others.<P>

Published BCC  studies relating to the present subject include
the following:<P>

