<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-126  BIOHAZARD TESTING
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> C-126  BIOHAZARD TESTING</H2>

<HR><P>



<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>



<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVE AND PURPOSE OF REPORT</B><P>

Human toxicity testing and environmental effects testing, the two
components of biohazard testing, play pivotal roles in industry and
commerce, since they contribute to and often initiate standards,
regulations, market approvals, remediations, controls and materials
substitutions. Calling a chemical toxic has major implications and
consequences, and a lot of decisions from various quarters hinge on
whether biohazard tests are done, and the way they are conducted.<P>

Obviously, if it kills, it's toxic.  But the tests today are more
complicated and are becoming increasingly more subtle.  Tests for
lethality, in fact, are no longer the way to judge most forms of
toxicity.  Moreover, new types of toxicity have become recognized
and added to the battery of tests that must now be considered.<P>

Biohazard testing has become a hot-button, emotional issue as a
result of antichemical attitudes, animal rights activism and
environmental protectionism.  The field is undergoing a period of
change and transition, making its future perhaps difficult to grasp
in all its various dimensions.  Yet, the demands for biohazard
testing increase, even while voices, sometimes strident, call for
radical changes in the way they are carried out.<P>

An unfortunate outcome of the controversies now aroused by
biohazard testing is that a cloud of secrecy is descending on the
subject, making it difficult to discuss it objectively from a
business standpoint.  But this is precisely what the subject needs,
so that executive managers and others in authority can effectively
deal with events and implement the future.  The objective of this
report, therefore, is to shed light on the changing dimensions of
biohazard testing from a technical-business standpoint and examine
its evolving roles.  The purpose is to help readers with business
concerns understand developments from their perspective so they can
manage more effectively.<P>

This report raises the following questions about biohazard testing,
and then seeks answers to them:<P>

     What types of tests are involved in biohazard testing?  How
are they done?<P>

    Who does biohazard testing?  Where are they done, in-house or
by outside contracting?<P>

    How big is the field of biohazard testing, in terms of animal
supply?  What are the markets for animal alternatives?<P>

    What are the newly emerging in vitro testing products?  Where
are their niche opportunities even as the validation process
proceeds?  Who is entering this field?<P>

    What is the business status of envirotoxicity testing?  Who is
in it?  What are the fauna and flora requirements for this kind of
testing?<P>

<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT</B><P>

This study addresses the business of toxicology, covering health
effects on humans and the effects of chemicals on the fauna and
flora of the environment.  It includes discussion and accounting of
conventional animal tests, in vitro tests and envirotoxicity tests.<P>

Readers of this report are expected to be business managers and
those with business interests.  Though the report takes up
toxicological science, the writing is geared to be readable by
those having a nontechnical background, while maintaining
scientific soundness for those who do have a science background.<P>

Topics not taken up in this report are:  The use of laboratory
animals in nontoxicological applications; the chemical or
microbiological analysis, diagnosis or monitoring of substances
already known to be toxic; remediation and control of toxic or
hazardous materials; and chemical hazards unrelated to toxicity,
i.e. flammability, explosiveness, causticity and corrosiveness.
Also, this is not a science textbook on toxicology, but a business
analysis of the subject.<P>

Section I provides an overview of the NATURE OF BIOHAZARD.  It
defines biohazard, and places biohazard in the context of other
types of hazard and in the context of fields related to and
differentiated from biohazard testing.  Newcomers to the subject
will find this basic grounding useful, and those already acquainted
may find fresh insights.<P>

Section II is on the BUSINESS, MARKETS AND DYNAMICS of biohazard
testing.  This section gives insight as to how biohazard testing
"works" from the business standpoint.  It includes a brief history
to explain why biohazard testing has come to play a pivotal role,
illuminates the forces influencing biohazard testing including the
subtle interplays, and extensively discusses regulations as the key
driver of biohazard testing.  The lengthy discussion on the
business climate for biohazard testing illuminates the major forces
shaping the future development of this field.  Then, this section
analyzes the market for biohazard testing, examining it in many
ways to bring out various features.  Finally, this section
discusses BCC's forecasting scenario, the analysis and thinking
that went into our projections.  This piece gives our critical
assumptions and the reasoning behind them, as devoid of biases as
any independent observer with no vested interests can be.<P>

Section III presents the INDUSTRY STRUCTURE.  It describes the
elementary components of the biohazard testing industry and makes
clear their roles and interactions.  Included are chemical
manufacturers and suppliers, testing product suppliers, testing
service providers, and research centers including universities and
government laboratories.  Our profiles of selected establishments
were selected as leading examples of their types of organizations.<P>

Section IV covers APPLICATIONS OF BIOHAZARD TESTING.  Testing
requirements, needs and desires are described, volumes of testing
are analyzed and major trends and directions affecting testing are
discussed.  Emphasized are pharmaceuticals, foods, cosmetics and
toiletries, and pesticides.  Also covered are medical device
materials, biocompatible plastics, organic solvents, smoke and
biotechnology.<P>

Section V extensively discusses CONVENTIONAL ANIMAL TESTING,
emphasizing the business aspects rather than the science of
toxicology.  BCC discusses laboratory animals and derives estimates
for the number and value of mammalian animals used in biohazard
testing and associated research.  Then we describe the various
types of toxicology tests and discuss the changes and developments
taking place regarding their use.<P>

Section VI is about IN VITRO TESTING.  Often touted as substitutes
or alternatives to tests with live animals, in vitro testing
products actually are finding various other applications as well,
which this study sheds light on.<P>

Section VII is on ENVIROTOXICITY TESTING, emphasizing toxicity
tests for the effects of chemicals on the fauna and flora of the
environment.  A number of companies are positioning themselves to
take advantage of what many see as a major growth area in the
1990s.<P>

This report has SEVEN APPENDICES:  Literature references and
sources of information for this study, separate directories of
mammalian animal suppliers, nonmammalian animal suppliers and
independent testing laboratories, additional government
laboratories not described in the main text that are investigating
toxic substances of various kinds, a brief synopsis on the care of
laboratory animals, and a listing of special terminology,
abbreviations and symbols used in biohazard testing.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

This study is the result of three man-months of concentrated
research, analysis and writing.  Primary sources of information
were telephone interviews with 40 individuals representing animal
and in vitro product suppliers, testing service providers,
user-customers and various trade associations.  Information
obtained from these sources went beyond the ordinary and commonly
available, and concerned such matters as the kinds and percentages
of lab animals actually used for toxicology and toxicity testing,
weighted average prices of animals representing the various species
as a national whole, the volume shares of short-term vs. long-term
tests, in-house testing vs. outside contracting, and many other
details not easily obtained or widely known.<P>

Secondary sources of information were extensive amounts of
historical and current published technical and business literature,
as well as product and price catalog literature, annual reports
where available, government documents including the OTA's and NIH's
reports on the subject, and several toxicology textbooks.  This
report documents all sources of information, and an Appendix lists
our major ones.<P>

In various instances, computations had to be made.  We show our
work and our rationale.  Where assumptions had to be made, we state
what they are and the reasons for making them.<P>

Sales figures are expressed in U.S. millions of dollars ($1 MM =
$1,000,000).  Projections of future testing and of future testing
product sales are based on reasoned scenarios fully explained in
the text.  Forecasted sales for 1995 are expressed in constant 1990
dollars to reflect real changes without inflation, and assume
constant prices.  The five-year average annual growth rate
presented in tables, the AAGR, is derived by the compounding method
using standard tables of net present value.<P>

BCC and the analyst have no vested interest in any company or
product mentioned in this report.  All analyses and forecasts are
made independently, without biases.  Omissions of company names, if
any, are not intentional except when anonymity was specifically
requested because of sensitivity regarding certain subject matter.<P>

<B>CREDENTIALS AND RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

The writer of this report is a seasoned chemist-biochemist also
having an MBA.  He has had industry experience at senior levels,
first as a laboratory scientist and research supervisor, then as an
internal science-business advisor to executive management.  Since
coming to BCC as Director of Biotechnology & Healthcare, he has
authored numerous studies, including Cancer Diagnostic & Treatment
Products, Vaccines & Alternatives, Inert Ingredients For Drugs,
Stereoselective Chemical Technology, Monoclonal & Polyclonal
Antibody Business, Medical Anti-Infective Agents, Plant-Derived
Chemicals, The Changing Sterilization Picture, The Pet Food &
Health Industry, and many others.  He has laboratory experience in
the handling of animals.<P>

BCC itself is a multidisciplinary market research and consulting
firm, which has been serving industry for many years.  Besides
biotechnology and healthcare, the firm also has expertise in
petrochemicals, plastics, metals, ceramics, advanced composite
materials, electronics, packaging, foods and other fields.  BCC has
a reputation for honesty and accuracy.<P>

BCC reports related to this report's topic include the following:<P>

C-006:    Chlorofluorocarbons:  Markets & Alternatives
C-038R:   The Huge Conventional Waste Management Business
C-059:    Technologies For Managing Hazardous Waste
C-110:    Environmental Management Through Biotechnology
E-051:    Indoor Air Pollution
E-052:    Environmental Services For Indoor Air Pollution
GB-042:   Air Pollution Monitoring & Abatement Equipment
GB-043:   Water Pollution Monitoring & Abatement Equipment
GB-127:   The Solid Waste Recycling Business<P>


