<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-142: INVESTMENT OPPORTUNITIES IN CHINA:
EMPHASIZING BIOTECHNOLOGY, DRUGS, AGRICULTRE, 
FOOD AND CHEMICALS 
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-142: INVESTMENT OPPORTUNITIES IN CHINA:
EMPHASIZING BIOTECHNOLOGY, DRUGS, AGRICULTRE, 
FOOD AND CHEMICALS 
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Philip Rotheim
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR STUDY
</B><P>

The economic transformation of China into a free market economy,
along with its opening to foreign investment and joint ventures,
provides an enormous market opportunity.  At the same time, the
economic development of China positions the country to become a
significant competitive player on the world stage.<P>    

This study therefore offers insight into China's capabilities and
activities and offers a road map and guide to doing business with
China.<P>  

<b>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS OF STUDY</B><P>
One objective of this study is to elucidate mainland China's
capabilities and activities in biotechnology, drugs and other
medical products, agriculture and food, chemicals, and
biochemicals.  Another objective is to identify governmental,
academic, professional, trade, and manufacturing organizations with
whom foreign companies can make contact.  The third objective is to
shed light on the maze of regulations and other intricacies for
doing business with Chinese companies.<P>  

The goal of this study is to provide information and insight that
will  help "Western" companies access this enormous market.<P>

<b>AUDIENCE FOR REPORT</B><P>
Readers of this report are expected to be executives and scientists
in biotechnology, drug, medical device, agricultural, food,
chemical, enzyme and biochemical companies interested in, or
considering doing business with, China.<P>  

<b>SCOPE AND CONTENT</B><P>
This report's Overview provides a capsule view of China, including
its history, culture, people, natural resources and infrastructural
resources.  This chapter also provides a summary of mainland
China's economy in general and gives the names of individuals one
should contact for general information.<P> 

In China's New Direction we lay out the new policies that encourage
foreign investment and joint ventures, spell out the applicable
regulations and other requirements for doing business, include key
organizations to contact (including addresses and contact
personnel), and provide other useful information anyone
contemplating doing business with China should know. We also point
out the various obstacles to business dealings so readers can be
prepared beforehand.<P>  

The chapter called Medical Products encompasses pharmaceuticals and
medical equipment.  We sketch in the market sizes, provide
information on how foreign firms can access the markets, and
summarize recent joint venture activities.<P> 

We do the same in Agriculture and Food, outlining the relevant
market sizes, explain how to gain access to the market and
summarize recent activities.<P>

The chapter on Chemicals outlines the overall chemicals market in
China, offers a guide to gaining entry to the Chinese market, and
describes some of the key manufacturers.  This chapter encompasses
synthetic chemicals, plant-derived chemicals and fermentation-based
chemicals, the latter including fermentation solvents, biochemicals
and enzymes.<P>   

Hong Kong and Taiwan are discussed in a separate chapter.  We
discuss the status and future of these entities, outline the
commercial activities emphasizing medical products, and list key
contact organizations.  Because Hong Kong and Taiwan are not a part
of the People's Republic of China, this study excludes a forecast
of biotechnology-based product sales concerning these two entities.<P> 


Appendix I on Biomedical Research Institutions and Drug
Manufacturers in China lists (complete with addresses and contact
personnel) biological, medical and drug research institutions; drug
manufacturers ("drug factories"); and veterinary pharmaceutical
factories.  Appendix II on Agricultural Research Institutions and
Food Manufacturers lists agricultural and plant research
institutions; animal and veterinary research institutions; fish and
aquaculture institutions; and food and beverage factories. 
Appendix III on Chemical and Fermentation Research Institutions and
Manufacturers lists chemical research institutions; environmental
research institutions; microbial and fermentation research
institutions; agrichemical producers; fermentation solvent
companies; and biochemical and enzyme producers.  Appendix IV
provides a List of Acronyms used in this study.  Appendix V is a
list of Information Sources used for this study and which readers
can refer to independently.<P>  

<b>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>
Data and information for this study comes from  the recent
technical and business press, reports issued by the American
Embassy in Beijing, the Foreign Commercial Service in various
locations inside China, the International Trade Administration, the
Chinese State Statistical Bureau, standard texts on China, and
original BCC research by telephone interviews with executives in
selected companies already doing business with China.  We also had
personal communications with knowledgeable individuals inside
China.<P>

A paucity of "hard" statistics coming out of China relevant to
commercial interests hampers the kind of detailed economic analysis
we are accustomed to in the West. Nevertheless, this study has
developed models  for possible scenarios representing future
biotechnology developments.<P>

Except where noted, all economic values are stated in U.S. dollars.
In some instances, we present figures in China's currency and the
section on Hong Kong uses some figures in Hong Kong dollars. 
Currency exchange rates are provided.<P> 

<b>CREDENTIALS</B><P>
BCC is well-known for its biotechnology studies. The writer of this
study is a biochemist who also holds an MBA degree and who has
had international experience, professionally.  At BCC, he has
written numerous studies on all aspects of biotechnology, including
pharmaceuticals, food, diagnostics, environmental science, and
chemicals. He is also editor of Applied Genetics News and
Stereochemical Technology News.<P>

<b>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>
No other published BCC report relates precisely to this one. 
However, in the general field of biotechnology relevant reports
include:<P>

<UL>DBP91--Worldwide Directory of Protein and Peptide Producers<BR>
     C-065--Bioengineered Protein Drugs<BR>
     C-088R--The Dynamic Antibody Industry<BR>
     C-143--Biotechnology in the '90s<BR>
     C-147R--The Enzyme Outlook</UL><P>


