<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-143  BIOTECHNOLOGY IN THE 1990S: TAKING STOCK
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-143  BIOTECHNOLOGY IN THE 1990S: TAKING STOCK</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>CORT WROTNOWSKI</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The basic goal of this study is to present the most complete analysis possible of the
biotechnology industry.  This study comes at a very important time in the
development of the industry.  Just as new product introductions and sales are
beginning to increase, and the range of industries affected by biotechnology grows,
there is also heightened investor interest that has been absent for the last several
years.<P>

The study answers the question:  Where has the biotechnology industry been, and
where is it going?  Also, just what is the reasonable size to expect these markets to
become?  Is this the time to invest, reinvest, increase investments, or even divest?<P>

Leading technological and commercial developments are discussed at length.
Historical perspective of the last ten years is included as well.<P>

The study addresses the basic concerns about the status of biotechnology and where
it is likely to go over the next ten years.  This includes considerations of changes in
technologies, in research direction, in product development and marketing strategies.
The shifting picture of regulatory reform at the FDA and other federal agencies is
presented, as well as the growing role of state regulation.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The biotechnology industry has grown significantly in the last ten years, well beyond
the expectations of most observers and participants.  In the course of growing, it has
gone into a number of areas where special skills are required.  At the same time, the
development of new disciplines and new combinations of technologies are creating a
growing number of cross-impacts from which new opportunities are quickly emerging.
This applies to all the major market segments.<P>

However, there has been no systematic effort to collect together in one place the
different activities of biotechnology in and around these market segments.  This study
was designed to look at all these different areas and to get a sense of how they are
progressing and what kinds of impacts they can be expected to make in the next
decade.<P>

Also, a number of entirely new analytical instruments and enhanced capabilities have
been introduced, especially over the last five years, which have set the stage for
working into entirely new areas of research.  Capillary electrophoresis,
multidirectional electrophoresis, and supercritical extraction are a few common
examples.<P>

The net effect is that, were one to make these measures, one would find that research
productivity has gone up significantly.  The rate at which a compound can be isolated
and analyzed has increased very significantly.  If one compares what tools were
available in 1981 with those available in 1991, it is fair to say that the difference is
dramatic.<P>

The range of DNA products, the sequencing technologies, the nuclease enzymes, and
other products introduced in the last ten years make researchers' work much easier.
Along with this, the growing use of such things as complementary DNA libraries and
the expanding range of PCR techniques have changed the way researchers get results.<P>

What all this progress means is the following:  Product development times will be
shorter, the costs will be less, and the number and types of markets and products that
can benefit from biotech-nological methods will only grow.  Thus, areas that were not
considered opportunities several years ago, will become very definite opportunities in
the next several years.  So, for example, as researchers continue to extend the range
of genetic engineering capabilities in biomaterials, new market opportunities for
advanced materials having medical and industrial applications will come into focus.
Advances in supporting technologies will only further accelerate the pace of this work.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study provides a perspective on the growth of a new industry that is not to be
found anywhere else.  The information reflects a time when there were high
expectations as well as considerable disappointment, when the efforts of individual
companies unfolded, or unraveled, as the case may be.<P>

This study provides data and other information not found anywhere else on the
technology, the markets, the products, and other areas.  The information presented
here will help in planning and investigating the many promising aspects of
biotechnology.<P>

In this respect, the study pulls together a broad array of data on finance, investment,
sales, markets, and other areas.  Taken together, this provides a frame of reference
for analyzing the biotechnology industry.<P>

The audience for this report is intended to include strategic planners, market
managers, and others involved in managing different biotechnology projects both
within their own company and in conjunction with other companies. The study is also
for those concerned with the state of the biotechnology industry and how it is
changing.  This study is unique in the extensive collection of information on
biotechnology.  It is the most complete and up-to-date report on the whole
biotechnology industry.  The report is also useful since it includes perspectives of the
dozen plus current BCC Reports on biotechnology that specialize in selected market
areas.<P>

This document should prove to be a useful source of data, an important resource for
discussion, and an aid in analysis of the industry as it changes over the next several
years.  It is fair to say that this is the best collection of information on biotechnology.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of the study is the whole biotechnology industry.  As such it includes work
in biotherapeutics, diagnostics, industrial biotechnology, agricultural biotechnology,
marine biotechnology, and the research market for biotechnology.<P>

The overall format is organized to look at overall issues, then the leading technologies,
then products under develoment, then products that are on the market and the
companies that are involved.<P>

There is also a section on international biotechology.  It considers the likely
competitors to the U.S. and how their positions have changed over the last several
years, as well as what they are likely to do next.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The methodology for the preparation of this study included interviews, scanning of
secondary sources, and the development of estimates and analyses in those places
where the necessary information was lacking.<P>

Market estimates are based on 1990 dollars and go through the year 2000.  Most
estimates are limited to the U.S., but, where appropriate, world market figures are
included as well.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The several dozen trade and technical publications in biotechnology and related areas
were scanned for key information on the current directions of biotechnology.  In
addition, back issues of these sources as well as computer searches were conducted in
reconstructing the recent history of biotechnology.<P>

Customers, researchers, marketing managers, and company presidents were among
those interviewed in seeking information about the different biotechnology market
segments, as well as their perspectives on the progress of biotechnology over the last
ten years.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The analyst for this study, Cort Wrotnowski, has extensive experience in market
research and analysis for biotechnology.  He has done approximately a dozen studies
over the last 8 years on behalf of BCC.  He has presented a number of conference
papers, written articles for trade publications, and consulted on a variety of special
assignments for Fortune 500 firms involving biotech-nological products and markets.
He has a BA in Biology from the State University of New York at Purchase.<P>

Related BCC Studies are listed in the back of this report.<P>


