<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-144  REAGENTS FOR BIOTECHNOLOGY: NEW TRENDS, NEW NEEDS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-144  REAGENTS FOR BIOTECHNOLOGY: NEW TRENDS, NEW NEEDS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>CORT WROTNOWSKI</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The basic goal of this study is to present the most complete
analysis possible of the bioreagent business.  The kinds of
products being developed and used in this area are critical to the
future progress of biotechnology.  The accelerating pace of
molecular biology is putting increasing pressure on suppliers to
develop products that save time and money, while also helping to
improve the performance of researchers.<P>

This study comes at a very important time in the development of
biotechnology. While there is increasingly visible interest in and
discussion about innovation in biotechnology, at the same time new
and novel products are being introduced at a faster pace.  Some are
simple, others are sophisticated. Taken together, they represent a
growing tool-box of increasing versatility in research and product
development.  Moreover, this applies to all the areas of product
development, including but not limited to biotherapeutics,
diagnostics, industrial applications and environmental
applications.<P>

The study answers the questions: Where has the bioreagent business
been, and where is it going?  Just what is the reasonable size
these markets will become?  What are the important new product
trends, and how will changing directions in research affect reagent
demand?<P>

Leading technological and commercial developments are discussed in
the report.  Also, important regulatory and financial issues are
covered.<P>

The study addresses the many different issues, general and
specific, that are expected to shape the bioreagent business over
the rest of the decade. This includes considerations of changes in
technologies, in research direction, in product development and
marketing strategies.  The shifting picture of regulatory reform at
the FDA and other federal agencies is presented, as well as the
growing role of international competition and cooperation.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The biotechnology industry has grown significantly in the last 10
years,  well beyond the expectations of most observers and
participants.  In the course of growing, it has gone into a number
of areas where special skills are required.  At the same time, the
development of new disciplines, and new combinations of
technologies are creating a growing number of cross-impacts from
which new opportunities are quickly emerging.  This applies to all
the major market segments.<P>

Not only has this pattern of development had an impact on the much-
watched commercial opportunities in biotherapeutics, it has also
affected the supporting technologies.  In particular, the various
compounds, reagent systems, kits, and other products used to
control and study biological reactions have undergone a number of
changes.  The net effect has been to reduce the amount of time a
researcher needs to carry out routine research tasks.  Further,
there is an ongoing effort to reduce the time and cost associated
with the many techniques of molecular biology.  This is a quiet
revolution, the impact of which is still only beginning to be felt.<P>

This study was designed to look at the many different kinds of
products and market segments.  The purpose was to get a sense of
how they are changing and how they will likely change in the next
decade.<P>

The basic assertion is that improved reagents improve research
results.  The net effect is that were one to make these measures,
one would find that research productivity has gone up
significantly. The rate at which a compound can be isolated and
analyzed has increased very significantly.  If one compares what
tools were available in 1981, as compared with 1991, it is fair to
say that the difference is dramatic.<P>

An unanswered question, though, is the relative contribution of new
reagents as compared with the contribution of new analytical
equipment (and computers).  The most likely answer is that they are
inextricably linked.  Advances in one are dependent on and
influenced by advances in the other.<P>

The range of DNA products, sequencing technologies, endonuclease
enzymes, and other products introduced in the last ten years, make
researchers' work much easier.  Along with this, the growing use of
gene libraries, and the expanding range of PCR techniques have
changed the way researchers get results.<P>

What all this progress means is the following:  Product development
times will be shorter, the costs will be less, and the number and
types of markets and products that can benefit from
biotechnological methods will only grow.  Thus, areas that were not
considered opportunities several years ago, will become very
definite opportunities in the next several years.  So, for example,
as researchers continue to extend the range of genetic engineering
capabilities in biomaterials, new market opportunities for advanced
materials having medical and industrial applications will come into
focus.  Advances in supporting technologies will only further
accelerate the pace of this work.<P>

Thus, an important part of the study is to look at new reagents
being introduced and to ask questions about the kinds that are
needed for the future.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study provides a perspective on the growth of an important and
complex business. It provides data and other information not found
anywhere else on the technology, markets, products and other areas.
The information presented here will help in assessment and
evaluation of the many promising features of the bioreagent
business.<P>

In this respect, the study pulls together a broad array of data on
finance, investment, sales, markets and other areas.  Taken
together, this provides a frame of reference for analyzing the
bioreagent business.<P>

The audience for this report is intended to include strategic
planners, market managers, and others involved in managing
different projects both within their own company and in conjunction
with other companies. The study is also for those interested in
gaining important information about the bioreagent marketplace in
the US and how it is changing.  This study is unique in the
extensive collection of information on bioreagents.  It is the most
complete and up-to-date report on the bioreagent marketplace.  The
report is also useful since it includes perspectives from the dozen
or more current BCC reports on biotechnology industry.<P>

This document should prove to be a useful source of data, and an
important resource for discussion, and an aid in analysis of the
industry as it changes over the next several years.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

It is fair to say that this is the best collection of information
on biotechnology. The scope of the study is the bioreagent
industry.  This is a complex and multifaceted business.  There are
many tens of thousands, if not hundreds of thousands, of individual
products that are used in highly specialized, and not-so-
specialized applications in biotherapeutics, diagnostics,
industrial biotechnology, agricultural biotechnology, marine
biotechnology, and analytical biotechnology.  Among the research
areas considered are molecular biology, cell biology, immunology,
AIDS research, the genome project, virology, and PCR-related work.<P>

The format is organized to look at overall issues, the leading
technologies, products under development, products that are on the
market and the companies that are involved.<P>

There is also a section on international biotechology.  It
considers the leading suppliers competing with US bioreagent
suppliers, and how their positions have changed over the last
several years, as well as what they are likely to do next.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The methodology for the preparation of this study included
interviews, scanning of secondary sources, and the development of
estimates and analyses in those places where the necessary
information was lacking.<P>

Market estimates are based on current U.S. dollars and project
through the year 2000.  Most estimates are limited to the US, but,
where appropriate, world market figures are included as well.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The several dozen trade and technical publications in biotechnology
and related areas were perused for key information on the current
directions of biotechnology.  In addition, back issues of these
sources, as well as computer searches, were conducted in
reconstructing the recent history of biotechnology.  Key trade
shows were attended and important individuals interviewed.<P>

Company presidents, researchers, purchasing agents, marketing
managers and company presidents were among those interviewed in
seeking information about the different bioreagent market segments,
as well as their perspectives on the outlook for bioreagents in the
coming years.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The analyst for this study, Cort Wrotnowski, has extensive
experience in market research and analysis for biotechnology.  He
has written approximately a dozen studies over the last eight years
on behalf of BCC.  He has presented a number of conference papers,
written articles for trade publications, and consulted on a variety
of special assignments involving biotechnological products and
markets for Fortune 500 firms.  He has a BA in Biology from the
State University of New York at Purchase.<P>

Related BCC Studies are listed in the back of the report.<P>


<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
