<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-147RB THE ENZYME INDUSTRY: SPECIALTY AND MEDICAL APPLICATIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-147RB THE ENZYME INDUSTRY: SPECIALTY AND MEDICAL
APPLICATIONS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
Sr. MARKET ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>
                                  
                                  
<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS OF STUDY</B><P>

The  objectives  of  this  study are to comprehensively  analyze  the
entire enzyme industry, to identify actual and potential applications
of  enzymes, to quantify the sales value of enzyme products,  and  to
assess  the  impact  of new technologies that may either  improve  or
retard  the  prospects  for commercial enzymes.   The  goals  are  to
provide meaningful data and unbiased analysis and assessment  of  the
roles  enzymes  play now and the roles they could have in the future.
This study also updates a previously published comprehensive analysis
of the enzyme industry.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF STUDY</B><P>

All  categories  of  enzymes are covered in this  study:  hydrolases;
oxidoreductases;  isomerases;  transferases;  ligases;  and  ligases.
Within  the hydrolases we include proteases, carbohydrases,  lipases,
nucleases amidases, and phosphatases.<P>

All  applications  of enzymes are covered: C-147A  covers  industrial
(food,  detergents, textiles, leather, paper), chemicals  manufacture
applications.  C-147B  covers  specialty (analytical,  biotechnology,
research) and medical applications. C-147C is an Enzyme Directory.

Absolutely  nothing  has been intentionally  left  out.   This  study
quantifies sales and consumption for the major enzymes of commerce in
the  respective  fields  of application, but  in  some  instances  we
provide  aggregative  estimates.  We do not comprehensively  quantify
sales and consumption for each and every enzyme known to  exist.<P>


<B>AUDIENCE FOR REPORT</B><P>

This  report  is  intended  for  business  executives  interested  in
enzymes,  including  enzyme  suppliers,  enzyme  users,  and   enzyme
investors.   Scientists  interested in the  business  perspective  of
enzymes will find this study informative.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This  study results from three man-months of effort. Primary  sources
of  information  were  direct telephone  interviews  with  sales  and
technical  staffs  among  enzyme  suppliers  and  with  knowledgeable
technical and business people among enzyme users. We also interviewed
appropriate  industry associations for industry-wide  practices  with
regard  to enzyme usages.  Secondary sources of information  included
product  literature  from  enzyme suppliers and  numerous  scientific
references.  We also made use of in-house computerized literature and
patent  searching capabilities.  BCC's Applied Genetics  News  proved
invaluable.<P>

Sales  (and captive values) for enzymes are expressed in millions  of
dollars  ($1 MM = 106).  Forecasts of enzyme sales and value  are  in
constant  1993  dollars.  The average annual growth  rate  (AAGR)  is
derived  by  the  compounding method.  Quantities of  enzyme  protein
consumption  are  expressed in kilograms. All sales  and  consumption
figures  refer  to  the United States, unless otherwise  specifically
indicated. Brand names are in capital letters.  Mentions of  products
are  not  endorsements, and omissions, if any, are  not  intentional.
Analyses   are  made  independently,  without  the  bias  of   vested
interests.<P>


<B>ANALYST CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The  research writer of this study is an enzymologist with an  M.B.A.
After working at the Albert Einstein College of Medicine, he moved on
to  industry, where he worked for many years in microbial  enzymology
and  obtained several patents.  He spent time as a reviewer  for  the
National  Science  Foundation  in  connection  with  enzyme  research
proposals  submitted for funding.  He has work experience also  in  a
pharmaceutical  company.   At BCC, this analyst  has  researched  and
written  many  studies  in the biotechnology field,  including  three
others  specifically on enzymes.  At BCC he has also provided  custom
consulting service.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

Published BCC studies that relate to this one, done by the writer  or
by others, include the following:<P>

