<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-147RC THE ENZYME DIRECTORY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-147RC THE ENZYME DIRECTORY
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
Sr. MARKET ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>
                                                                    
This  Enzyme Directory identifies suppliers of enzymes.  The goal  is
to  provide  a  handy  reference so that the worldwide  suppliers  of
individual enzymes can be readily looked up.  We rely on company self-
reporting for these identifications and cannot confirm that companies
do in fact supply the enzymes they say they do (although most, if not
all,  do  supply the enzymes they claim).  This Directory  identifies
suppliers in the sense that they offer enzymes for sale to customers.<P>

We  have not comprehensively determined whether in fact the suppliers
produce  the enzymes they offer or merely distribute enzymes produced
by   others,  although  the  Company  Profiles  section  gives   some
indications in this regard for certain companies.  Some companies may
produce  the  enzymes  they  sell, while  other  companies  may  only
distribute enzymes without producing any of them.  Some companies may
produce only certain of the enzymes they sell, while merely acting as
distributors of other enzymes  they offer.<P>
                                  
This  Enzyme Directory uses the common names of enzymes, rather  than
the  formal  designations assigned by the Enzyme  Commission  of  the
International  Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry. Where  an  enzyme
has  more  than  one common name, we use the one we believe  is  most
frequently used and provide cross-referencing.<P>
                                  
We  do  not  differentiate enzymes on the basis of source or  origin,
even  if  subtle  differences in specificity may  exist.   Thus,  for
example,  we  do not differentiate between the DNA polymerase  of  E.
coli,  Micrococcus luteus, T4 bacteriophage and T7 bacteriophage,  or
between  bacterial and calf intestinal alkaline phosphatase. However,
where  the source of enzyme has special connotations, we do make  the
distinction, e.g., Taq DNA polymerase.  Future editions may  be  made
more detailed in this regard.  In some instances the Company Profiles
section of this directory provides more details than does the  Enzyme
Suppliers section, and readers are advised to check these details.<P>

The   Company  Profiles  section  of  this  Directory  provides   the
addresses, telephone numbers and fax numbers of companies   from  all
over  the  world  that  supply enzymes.   We  provide  brief  general
descriptions  of  the  companies,  identify  their  focus  of  market
applications, and list the enzymes they supply.<P>

Two observations about this Directory are worth noting:<P>

1) Sales of an enzyme roughly correlate with the number of suppliers.
Although  no precise mathematical formula can be set down correlating
sales  with the number of suppliers, it can be said that the  greater
the sales of an enzyme in its market, the more likely it will attract
many suppliers.<P>

2) For any particular enzyme, the list of suppliers hints at business
relationships   between  the  true  producer(s)  and   those   merely
distributing  the enzyme but not producing it.  This  Directory  does
not  pursue the delineation of these business relationships,  but  it
can serve as a useful starting point.<P>

This  Directory  does  not  provide sales estimates  or  analysis  of
applications   and  markets  for  enzymes.   Two  companion   studies
accomplish those goals:<P>

<UL>
<LI>C-147R Vol.  A:  Enzymes  for Industrial and Chemicals  Manufacturing
Applications
<LI>C-147R Vol. B: Enzymes for Specialty and Medical Applications
</UL>


                            
                                  
                                  
                          





