<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-156  LABELING AND LINKAGE AGENTS FOR INNUMOASSAYS
AND GENE PROBES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-156  LABELING AND LINKAGE AGENTS FOR INNUMOASSAYS
AND GENE PROBES</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>RICHARD ROSSITER</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The primary objective of this study is to examine the markets for
the various compounds used to tag gene probe and immunoassay
products, so that an accurate demand forecast can be developed and
the market/industry structural changes can be predicted.  In order
to complete this task, a close examination of the forces impacting
on both markets and industry dynamics are determined and evaluated.<P>


Specifically, we expect to ascertain the consequences of the
current and expected future diagnostic/test regulatory environment
on tags usage.  Regulations issued through the Food and Drug
Administration (FDA), the Dept. of Agriculture (USDA),
the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) and the Environmental
Protection Agency (EPA) are carefully assessed so that the their
impact on industry structure and demand dynamics can be accurately
forecast.<P>

Further technical developments will be assessed to determine if
there is an impact on demand for the various tagging reagents. In
the event of a major impact, we would like to understand what the
probable outcome of that development will be.  Technical advances
in both detection and diagnostics will be examined, as they both
have the potential to impact on the label and linker industry.<P>

We also examine the international markets and trade so that a
situational analysis of the U.S. label and linker industry can be
performed.  In addition to facilitating an understanding of the
U.S. market, it will also provide a basic understanding of European
and Japanese markets.<P>

Finally, we profile companies that supply the industry.  We also
briefly characterize distributors and, when possible, consuming
companies.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Our study is intended to help industry participants better
understand the complex environment where they do business. By
identifying and examining the issues associated with markets,
regulations, technology, and trade, industry players will be better
able to make decisions; managers will be able to enhance both and
company and product positioning generate increased returns.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

The contents and conclusions of the study will be valuable for a
wide variety of label and linker industry managers, including:
strategic planners, marketers, product development professionals,
purchasing agents, and sales staff.  These decision-makers will be
better able to plan production, to develop new products and to find
new customers.  Planners and marketers will gain insight for
company and product positioning.  Purchasers will locate new and
additional suppliers.<P>

Managers from several related industries will also find valuable
information in the report.  Distributors, test formulators, traders
and even test laboratory professionals can benefit from a better
understanding of the tag/linkage business and how it influences
competition in their own industries.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The focus of this study is on the U.S. market supply and demand for
compounds used in the linkage and labeling of diagnostic and test
materials.  Several industrial segments are examined, including the
human health care segment comprising clinical, hospital, doctors
office and home sectors; the dental market; the in vivo imaging
market; the forensic/paternity market; the food market; the
environmental and plant agricultural markets; and finally the
research market.  Emphasis has been put on human health care since
it is the largest sector.  In relation to the other segments, it is
at least an order of magnitude larger, and frequently more than two
orders of magnitude larger.  Thus, we feel it warrants particular
emphasis.<P>

It is important to point out that many of the numerous materials
used by diagnostic producers are not covered by this report.
First, as the title indicates, we have limited the scope to
chemicals used in tagging gene probe or immunoassay products.
Next, we do not cover some of the segments that are not related to
human health care, such as industrial and veterinary tests.  And
finally, only chemicals with sufficiently large unit volume demand
or dollar volume are examined.<P>

As might be expected, the diversity of materials used in research
applications is far greater than that of commercial areas.  This
makes forecasting for the segment particularly difficult.  However,
we have identified the larger volume items and discussed them at
length.  Market demand forecasts, both unit volume and dollar, are
developed for each of the larger volume reagents and the total
demand - the total for all sectors included in this report and not
inclusive of other outlets - is determined.
Major factors impacting on the label/linker supply and demand are
discussed.  Government regulations, technology, patents and
international trade are all examined.  European and Japanese
suppliers and markets are briefly discussed, together with trade.<P>

Finally, we arrive at conclusions to facilitate the formation of
specific plans of action by industry participants.  Although the
study is not geared toward any particular supplier, the analysis
and conclusions are detailed in a manner that each will find
valuable.<P>

The table of contents serves as an outline for the study.  Specific
sections include: Introduction, Summary, Overview, Regulatory
Environment, Tagging and Linkage Reagents, Markets for Tagging and
Linkage Reagents, Technology, Patents, Material Prices, Selected
Company Expertise, International Arena, Industry Structure and
Selected Company Profiles.  For more detail, see the Table of
Contents.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Information was gathered using both primary and secondary sources.
Background information was pieced together from a multitude of
secondary sources, and complementary and supplementary information
was developed with telephone interviews.<P>

Specific analysis includes value chain assessment, strategic
positioning maps, and life cycle evaluations of both markets and
technologies.  Technical and regulatory analysis yielded valuable
information that facilitated the understanding of the direction and
magnitude of market demand for various product segments.  The key
elements impacting on market demand were determined so that
specific demand forecasts could be developed for each product.<P>



<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Secondary data were derived from: technical books; directories;
journals;  periodicals; computerized literature searches; product
catalogs and bulletins; company newsletters and annual reports;
government reports; consultant reports and newsletters; and trade
association bulletins.<P>

Interviews were conducted with numerous knowledgeable individuals,
including employees of diagnostic/test companies from such
departments as Technical Services, Marketing, R&D, and Purchasing.
Staff were interviewed from distributing firms, primarily in the
technical service and marketing departments, and from domestic raw
material producers, mostly from marketing department.  Discussions
with  newsletter authors and other consultants provided additional
information.  Exchanges with association personnel and academics
were informative.  And finally, interviews with government
regulatory agencies contributed greatly to the value of the study.<P>



<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS, INCLUDING WORK DONE BY
OTHERS</B><P>

Recent BCC studies that are closely related to the topic at hand
include: 
<UL>C-045N: Medical Diagnostic Kits<BR> 
C-060: New Directions in Diagnostic Reagents<BR> 
C-088R: The Dynamic Antibody Industry<BR> 
C-121: Food Testing Reagents<BR> 
C-103: Expanding Horizon for Gene Probes<BR> 
C-104: Drug Monitoring and Abuse Testing<BR> 
C-084: Microorganism Testing.</UL><P>


