<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-160  HUMAN GENE THERAPY: TECHNOLOGY ANALYSIS
AND MARKET FORECAST
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-160  HUMAN GENE THERAPY: TECHNOLOGY ANALYSIS
AND MARKET FORECAST</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PAUL E. KELLY</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goal of this report is to forecast the dollar amounts of
markets worldwide for inherited disease gene pharmaceuticals.  The
forecast period covers roughly the first ten years that inherited
disease gene pharmaceuticals will be in commercialization.  Markets
are defined by specific inherited disease, by entry date, by degree
and pace of market penetration, by geography, and where warranted,
by gene pharmaceutical type.<P>

Further, gene therapies are contrasted with competing
conventional technologies for inherited disease treatment to
generate forecasts of which mode of therapy will be used in a
specific disease or within patient subsets of that disease.  The
reader is thus informed not only of the market potential of
inherited disease gene therapies but of all possible competing
conventional therapies now in use or in development.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR CONDUCTING THE STUDY</B><P>

Inherited disease gene therapy was chosen as the study topic
for several reasons: 1) human gene therapy has advanced rapidly
within the past several years, and it is now feasible to develop on
a large scale, 2) the inherited diseases where gene therapy is
technically feasible at this date may be clearly identified, 3) the
clinical parameters that gene therapy must achieve in those
inherited diseases to be both therapeutically and commercially
successful may be unambiguously defined, 4) the therapeutic and
thus commercial potential of conventional therapy competitors to
inherited disease gene therapies may be assessed with a high degree
of confidence, 5) the inherited diseases analyzed here treated by
conventional means generate pharmaceutical sales and other medical
expenditures in the billions of dollars annually, up to $5.8
billion of which inherited disease gene therapies can capture, 6)
inherited disease gene pharmaceuticals should display as a group
among the highest profit margins available today in the
pharmaceutical industry.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND INTENDED AUDIENCE</B><P>

This study defines the inherited disease gene pharmaceutical
market, projects which inherited disease pharmaceuticals now under
development will be commercially successful and which will not, and
identifies inherited diseases that may be the subject of commercial
gene pharmaceutical development in the future.  Every parameter of
inherited disease gene therapy germane to commercial success is
analyzed here in depth, including: 1) clinical efficacy potential,
2) risk potential, 3) regulatory  hurdles,  and 4) methods for
applying gene pharmaceuticals clinically and their impact on
commercial distribution channels.  For each of the inherited
diseases analyzed here, gene therapy is also contrasted with both
current and developing conventional therapies across four critical
parameters: 1) efficacy, 2) risk, 3) ease of use, and 4) price.
The analysis is used to define the market potential for gene
therapy in a specific inherited disease and also to indicate the
market potential of competing conventional therapies, even those
that are only now in development.  Actual markets for inherited
disease gene therapies are derived from this technical analysis.<P>

This study is intended for venture capitalists, investment
bankers, industry and financial analysts, business development
professionals, strategic planners, marketing groups, consultants
and independent investors - in short, anyone whose work or
investments  are in some fashion related to human pharmaceuticals.
Though some of the topics this study covers are necessarily of a
technical nature, it is written to appeal to both lay and
scientifically literate audiences.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report focuses on inherited diseases.  Those inherited
diseases for which gene therapy is now tenable are defined in
Chapter 2, "Technical Dimensions: Inherited Disease Gene Therapy."
In summary, those inherited diseases must: 1) be prevalent enough
in likely market countries to warrant commercial interest, 2) have
a well defined defect in a single gene, 3) have normal copies of
the gene available for use in gene pharmaceuticals, and 4) be
amenable to correction by the insertion of a non-defective copy of
the causative gene into appropriate cells within the patient.<P>

All inherited diseases were considered in the early phases of
this study.  Those that met the above criteria are analyzed here:
Cystic Fibrosis, the Hemoglobinopathies (b-thalassemia and Sickle
Cell Anemia), the Hemophilias (A and B), Hereditary Emphysema,
Lysosomal Storage Disorders (Fabry's Disease, Gaucher's Disease,
Hunter's Disease and Hurler's Disease), the Muscular Dystrophies
(Becher's and Duchenne's) and Phenylketonuria.  The number of
people afflicted by these diseases in likely market areas - defined
here as the United States, Australia, Canada, Europe and Japan - is
approximately 600,000.  ADA Deficiency and Hypercholesterolemia are
also discussed here in some detail due to their status as the first
inherited diseases for which gene therapy was approved in the
United States, but they are too rare to be commercially viable.<P>

The bulk of the study - Chapters 2 through 4 - is  organized
by specific inherited disease to make the analysis easy to follow.
Those chapters describe the technical requirements for inherited
disease gene therapy, analyze current and developing conventional
treatments for inherited diseases that could compete with gene
therapy, and develop discrete market forecasts across the
geographic areas identified above.  Additional chapters: 1) define
the components of inherited disease gene pharmaceuticals, their
manufacture and keys to commercial value, 2) describe government
regulatory policies that bear on inherited disease gene therapy
commercialization, and 3) describe the structure of the gene
therapy industry and the general determinants of a particular
firm's commercial potential.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Technical, scientific, market and regulatory issues were
determined as described below.  The formal market forecasts
presented here are based on technical parameters (primarily
risk/efficacy potentials of the inherited disease gene therapy and
development barriers), probable market entry dates (determined from
company literature and interviews), an analysis of market
penetration functions (degree and pace of market penetration) and
probable inherited disease gene pharmaceutical pricing (derived
from the medical costs incurred with conventional treatments and
the relative clinical efficacies of them and inherited disease gene
therapies).<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

A thorough review of all pertinent primary scientific
literature on gene therapy and the inherited diseases was first
conducted to establish key scientific, technological and initial
market parameters for inherited disease gene pharmaceuticals.
Primary gene therapy companies, regulatory agencies, secondary
literature (the popular and business press) and associations for
the inherited diseases were consulted to define fully all market
parameters and to establish the regulatory and government policy
issues that  could affect inherited disease gene therapy
commercialization.<P>

<B>PERSONNEL FOR STUDY</B><P>

The author holds a bachelor's degree in biochemistry and an
MBA in finance.  He completed two years of formal medical education
and has several years of research experience in biotechnology-
focused laboratories.  He has been the Biotechnology Office
Administrator at the University of Rochester School of Medicine for
the past nine years, where his work has focused on devising
biotechnology-related education, research-support and professional
development programs.<P>




