<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-163  BIOTECHNOLOGY FOR ENVIRONMENTAL TESTING
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-163  BIOTECHNOLOGY FOR ENVIRONMENTAL TESTING
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS</B><P>

The objectives  of this  study are  to examine biotechnology's
role in  environmental testing  and to assess, quantitatively,
its growth prospects.   The goal is to bring this little-known
application  of   biotechnology  to  the  attention  of  those
concerned with the environment.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR THE STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTION</B><P>


Environmental concerns  are on  nearly everyone's  mind today,

and now  industry must  take into  account  the  environmental

effects in all of its manufacturing and discard practices.<P>


Environmental testing  is the  means  by  which  industry  and

municipalities, as  well as  government regulators,  determine

whether pollutants  have  entered  the  environment  and  also

whether remediation and abatement methods are working.<P>


Although little  recognized, biotechnology  is offering up new

products for  carrying out  environmental  testing,  and  they

represent competitive  alternatives  to  conventional  testing

methods and products.  Moreover, the technologies and products

becoming  available   have  potentials  beyond  the  immediate

applications.   It is  worthwhile, therefore,  to examine what

biotechnology-based testing  has to  offer and  to assess  its

impact.<P>


<B>REPORT'S SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>


This  report   examines   biotechnology-based   products   for

environmental  testing,   the  latter  being  defined  as  the

analysis of  soil, water,  and air  for the presence, identity

and quantity of chemical substances.<P>


Excluded from  this study  is  the  determination  of  whether

substances are  toxic or  hazardous.   Also excluded  are  the

testing of  non-environmental samples  such  as  food,  animal

tissue, human  tissue and  plant materials  and the testing of

and for  micro-organisms.   Except for  comparative  purposes,

conventional methods  and products  for environmental  testing

are also excluded.<P>


This report  divides into  six  sections,  not  including  the

introduction and  summary, and includes two appendices.  After

the  INTRODUCTION  and  SUMMARY,  the  report  opens  with  an

OVERVIEW of  environmental testing and biotechnology's role in

it,  including   the  importance   of  environmental   testing

generally and  its impact  on industry.   We  next present the

INDUSTRY STRUCTURE  AND DYNAMICS  of environmental  testing in

general and of biotechnology-based products in particular, and

this section  includes a description of the key players in the

supply of  biotechnology-based environmental testing products.

Then we briefly review the TECHNOLOGIES of biotechnology-based

testing,  comparing  the  technologies  among  themselves  and

against conventional  environmental testing technologies.  The

next section describes and compares the various biotechnology-

based  testing   PRODUCTS.     The  final  section  describes,

discusses, and  analyzes  the  APPLICATIONS  AND  MARKETS  for

biotechnology-based  environmental   testing  products,  which

includes sales  estimates and a forecast of sales, broken down

in several  ways.   Appendix I lists the key references on the

subject, and  Appendix  II  describes  application  areas  for

biotechnology-based  testing  products  that  relate  to  (but

differ from) environmental testing.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY FOR STUDY</B><P>


All the available product and company literature was collected

and reviewed.   We  telephone  interviewed  key  participants,

including company  presidents, product  and  market  managers,

scientists,  and   government   regulators,   for   additional

information.<P>


All estimates  and forecasts  refer to the United States only.

Figures are  expressed in  millions of  dollars ($1  MM = $1 x

106).   Forecasts for  1997 and 2002 are expressed in constant

1992 dollars.   The  average annual  growth rates,  AAGR,  are

derived by the compounding method.<P>


All analyses  are made  without the  bias of vested interests.

Mentions of  companies and  products are not endorsements, and

omissions, if  any, are not intentional.  Brand names or trade

names are indicated by the use of capital letters.<P>



<B>CREDENTIALS AND RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>


The analyst  for this  study is  a chemist-biochemist who also

holds an  MBA degree  in marketing.   He  has many years of

industrial experience and many years of experience with BCC.

Published BCC  studies relating  to the  present topic include
the following:<P>

<UL>C-038R:     The   Huge,   Conventional   Waste   Management
Business<BR>

   C-059R:     Hazardous Waste Control<BR>

   C-084: Microorganism Testing<BR>

   C-110: Environmental Management Through Biotechnology<BR>

   C-121: Food  Testing  Reagents,  Including  Biotechnology's
Impact<BR>

   C-126: Biohazard (Toxicology) Testing<P></UL>

