<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-165  LIPIDS: NEW TECHNOLOGIES, APPLICATIONS AND MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-165  LIPIDS: NEW TECHNOLOGIES, APPLICATIONS AND MARKETS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR THE STUDY</B><P>

Lipids were once the primary sources of aliphatic carbon
compounds used by industry.  With the arrival of petroleum, the
consumption of lipids declined in most industrial applications,
although obviously they still retain their strong position in
foods and feeds.<P>

Today, market forces, regulations, and concerns about the
environment once again bring lipid materials to the fore, as an
alternative to petrochemicals.  At the very same time, new
technologies have come along to create new and modified lipids
and to introduce new properties and performance characteristics.
New vegetable oils are near commercial introduction.<P>

Since lipids appear to be on the verge of renaissance, it will be
critical to assess the market opportunities for the new
technologies and products and to understand the forces for change
in the years ahead.<P>


<B>OBJECTIVE AND GOALS</B><P>

This study has two primary objectives:  (1) to quantitatively
assess the impact of new lipid technologies and new types of
lipid materials; and (2) to quantitatively analyze the lipid
industry in terms of the end-use consumption and consumption
value of lipids by products, functional applications, and market
outlets.  The goals of this study are to provide information,
facts and data that would allow business managers to make
intelligent decisions and enhance their corporate positions.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTION</B><P>

Lipids comprehensively analyzed in this study are triglycerides
and their derivatives, fatty acids and their derivatives, natural
plant and animal waxes, and phospholipids.  Only briefly
mentioned are glycerol, phytosterols, tocopherols, sphingolipids,
cerebrosides, glycolipids, and other types of lipids.  For the
lipids covered, all functional applications and all markets are
discussed and thoroughly analyzed.<P>

All major conventional and new technologies bearing on lipids are
discussed:  chemical modification and derivatization processes
and the catalysts employed, enzyme technology, conventional plant
breeding, and biotechnology.<P>

The study provides independent, unbiased discussions and
assessment of new technologies and new product and market
developments.  The study provides a diligent effort to quantify
end-use consumptions and values and also includes data on the
production of key intermediates.<P>

<B>REPORT AUDIENCE</B><P>

This study will serve the interests of companies in lipid
manufacturing and lipid supply, new technology firms applying
their expertise to lipids, and those considering investments,
joint ventures, or acquisitions relating to the lipid business.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information for this study was derived from government data,
company data, published trade data, scientific literature, in-
house patent searches, and an extensive number of telephone
interviews with market managers, product managers, technical
managers, and academic scientists.<P>

Consumption data refer to end uses and include both captive and
open-market consumption.  Dollar values for the consumption use
prices appropriate for the specific applications.  In most cases
the data refer to U.S. consumption and value.  This study also
provides U.S. import and export data.<P>

Consumption is stated in millions of pounds (MM lbs.), where 1
U.S. ton = 2,000 lbs., 1 lb. = 0.45359 kilogram, and 1 metric ton
= 1,000 kilograms = 2,205 lbs.  Dollar values refer to U.S.
currency and 1997 forecasts are expressed in constant 1992
dollars to reflect real changes without inflation.<P>

In our analyses of new technologies, we do not assume that
products introduced to the marketplace with the help of new
technologies will actually sell.  This assumption is at least
subjected to questioning and examination in the belief that it
serves industry more to investigate the technical-market
interface.  If events should turn out not exactly as planned,
then by our analyses companies would be in an advance position to
deal with new realities.  Conversely, we also identify reasons
why new technologies may benefit from changes taking place in the
market.  The reasoning is given throughout, with rational
explanations and an avoidance of "bio-infatuation."<P>


<B>CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The analyst for this study is a chemist-biochemist with a
master's degree in business administration specializing in
marketing.  He has previous industrial experience in lipid
technology. At BCC, the analyst is director of biotechnology and
editor of Applied Genetics News, and has written numerous studies
relating to the present topic, as well as others.  He has
presented invited speeches at technical and business conferences
and is the primary organizer of BCC's conferences on commercial
biotechnology.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

Numerous reports previously published by BCC relate to the
present topic, either substantially or in part.  Among these are
the following:<P>

<UL>C-0101: Developing Markets for Synthetic Lubricants<BR>
    C-020AR:   Corrosion Inhibitors<BR>
    C-025:  Printing Ink Chemicals<BR>
