<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-194 CYTOKINES AND GROWTH FACTORS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC=	"bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-194 CYTOKINES AND GROWTH FACTORS</H2>

<HR><P>
<I>Philip Rotheim</I><BR>
 Project Analyst
<P>
<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


<B>REASONS FOR STUDY, ITS CONTRIBUTION</B>

<P>Cytokines and growth factors  account for perhaps 70% of the protein drug 
research activity in the biotechnology industry today, and over 50% of the 
biotechnology-based pharmaceutical product sales. Discoveries have revealed 
the existence of new cytokines and growth factors, new biological behaviors 
about cytokines and growth factors are continually being uncovered, and the 
technologies for manufacturing cytokines and growth factors, though 
stabilizing, are undergoing important changes.</P> 

<P>Now that cytokines and growth factors have entered the market, the business 
issues affecting their sales can be meaningfully considered. Market 
applications for cytokines and growth factors are in flux: some already 
maturing, others offering expansion possibilities, and a few being 
disappointments.</P> 

<P>This group of biopharmaceuticals as a whole uniquely faces two great 
challenges. First, they tend to be more expensive than conventional drugs and 
therefore require economic justification in a healthcare climate that 
emphasizes pharmacoeconomics. Second, the prospect of entirely new 
technologies, such as gene therapy, cell and device implants, and chemical 
drugs for the stimulation of endogenous proteins, offers a future competitive 
challenge to cytokines and growth factors provided as exogenously 
administered, formulated drugs.</P> 

<P>In light of new developments, this study therefore  updates two earlier 
published studies on this subject. The aim is  to elucidate the future  of 
cytokines and growth factors in therapeutic applications in view of current 
developments. The major contribution of this study is a dispassionate, 
comprehensive analysis of cytokine and growth factor drugs from the business 
standpoint.</P> 




<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS OF STUDY</B>

<P>The objectives and goals of this study are the following:</P>

      <P>Sales analysis of cytokines and growth factors currently on the market, 
      by  products,  by applications, by geographic territories, by companies, 
      and by manufacturing technologies.</P>
  
      <P>Identification of cytokines and growth factors in the pipeline and  
      projections of actual (not merely the theoretical) sales if successful 
      in clinical trial and approved for marketing.</P>
 
      <P>Identification of newly discovered cytokines and growth factors and the  
      companies developing them.</P>
   
      <P>Elucidation of business and technical issues influencing the sales and 
      prospects of cytokines and growth factors.</P>
 
       <P>Forecast of C/GF sales in the year 2000.</P>


<B>REPORT AUDIENCE</B>

<P>Focused on business concerns rather than the science, this report will serve 
the interests of senior management executives in biotechnology firms and 
pharmaceutical companies.  It will also serve the interests of investment 
firms and anyone else who cares about the future of biopharmaceuticals as a 
business enterprise.  Scientists involved in cytokines and growth factors will 
also find this study of interest for its business perspective.</P> 


<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT OF REPORT</B>

<P>This report encompasses cytokines and growth factors for therapeutic use to 
treat human diseases.  Included are formulated cytokines and growth factors as 
well as cytokines and growth factors still under development or investigation, 
for dosed, therapeutic administration.</P> 

<P>This report excludes any detailed analysis of:  cytokines and growth factors 
as conditioning and proliferating agents for cell therapy; gene therapy based 
on the delivery of genes expressing cytokines and growth factors; chemical 
drugs for the endogenous stimulation of cytokines or growth factors; cytokines 
and growth factors as cell culture supplements; cytokines and growth factors 
for research applications; receptors to cytokines and growth factors for 
therapeutic or any other application; inhibitors or antagonists of cytokines 
and growth factors for therapeutic or any other use; immunoassays for 
cytokines and growth factors.</P> 

<P>This study is not simply a review of basic cytokine and growth factor research 
that just happens to take place in company laboratories. This is a business 
analysis of products being developed or already being marketed for therapeutic 
use, and this study is about their business prospects. For reviews of basic 
research, readers should consult the scientific literature.</P> 

<B>STUDY METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>Sales data come from up-to-date company self-reporting and from BCC estimates 
based on telephone interviews with business executives and on computations 
derived from patient sizes, dosing and unit packaging prices. Product 
development information comes from company reports, medical literature, and 
patent searches.</P> 

<P>All sales data refer to formulated products at primary supplier level. 
Worldwide sales by product are presented,  then analyzed by medical 
application, geographic territory, company, and manufacturing technology. 
Figures are in millions of dollars ($MM, where one million dollars equals 
$106).  BCC also estimates by computation the minimum bulk protein 
requirements, in grams, for each cytokine and growth factor on the market, 
based on patient size and dosing for individual medical applications.  
Forecasts are in constant 1994 dollars to reflect changes without inflation. 
Sales projections incorporate a conservative model of market penetration for 
specific applications.</P> 

<P>All analyses are made independently, without the bias of vested interests. 
Mentions of products are not endorsements, and omissions, if any, are not 
intentional.  Medical judgments are left to physicians.</P> 


<B>CREDENTIALS AND RELATED REPORTS</B>

<P>The writer of this study is a biochemist, with a lengthy background in academe 
and industry.  He also has an M.B.A. degree in marketing.  At BCC he has 
written many strategic and industry business analysis studies  in the 
biotechnology and healthcare fields, including various dimensions of the 
present topic. The analyst also has organized BCC's conferences on commercial 
biotechnology and he is now the editor of Applied Genetics News, as well as 
Stereochemical Technology News.  From time to time, at BCC, the analyst has 
carried out custom consulting on behalf of biotechnology industry clients, 
providing realistic -- and, in hindsight, accurate -- assessments of 
commercial opportunities or their lack.</P> 

<P>Published BCC studies relating to the present topic, written by the analyst or 
by others, include:</P> 

