<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-199 GENETIC PLATFORM TECHNOLOGIES: MATERIALS AND
APPLICATIONS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogo.Small.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-199 GENETIC PLATFORM TECHNOLOGIES: MATERIALS AND
APPLICATIONS</H2>

<HR><P><I>Philip Rotheim</I><BR>
Sr. Market Analyst<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS OF THIS STUDY</B>

<P>The objectives of this study are to provide professional discussion, analysis 
and insight on the subject of genetic technologies and on enabling materials 
and ultimate applications.  The goals are to provide readers with an 
integration of technological and business perspectives and to provide useful 
information for the conduct of business activities.</P>  


<B>WHO BENEFITS FROM THIS STUDY</B>

<P>This report is written from the business perspective and readers will receive 
information useful for their business, product and market planning and 
development efforts.  We expect this study will be of interest both to support 
product suppliers and the practitioners of biotechnology.</P> 


<B>REASONS FOR STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTION</B>

<P>The revolution in genetic technology brought about in the 1970s with the 
invention of recombinant DNA techniques continues unabated, but already some 
platform technologies are showing signs of maturing while new ones are 
emerging.</P> 

<P>The genetic technology industry itself is undergoing significant changes, as 
financial constraints and business competition place new selective pressures 
on companies which, in effect, "choose" those firms best adapted to survive 
the changed and challenged environment.</P> 

<P>This study therefore is written to provide up-to-date information and analysis 
of interest to both the suppliers of genetic technology enabling materials and 
the practitioners of genetic technology, with emphasis on the business  
aspects since we assume readers already have familiarity with the science. A 
key feature of this study is its quantifying of enabling materials sales in 
each of the genetic technology platforms. Forecasts are rational, and 
explained.</P>  


<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT OF THIS STUDY</B>

<P>This study focuses on the enabling materials for genetic technology, 
particularly the materials directly involved in genetic manipulation. Genetic 
technologies covered in this study are evident in the table of contents.</P> 

<P>Excluded  from this study are materials for the extraction and purification of 
genetic material, materials for gel electrophoresis, media for propagation, 
materials for screening, materials for protein synthesis and sequencing, 
immunoassay reagents, and materials of a general laboratory nature. This study 
also excludes durable equipment and instruments, small supplies and consumable 
supplies.</P> 


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>Primary information on sales and other technical and business matters was 
obtained from telephone interviews with many product suppliers. We also 
interviewed practitioners of the various genetic technologies, who constitute 
customers for the materials.  Secondary sources of information included 
several science texts (see Appendix) and articles in professional journals. We 
also made use of in-house computerized literature search capability.</P> 

<P>Sales are presented in millions of dollars ($ MM), where one million = 106.  
The report generally provides worldwide sales estimates; exceptions are noted. 
Forecasts to 2000 are given in constant 1995 dollars to reflect real changes 
without inflation.  The average annual growth rate (AAGR, %) is a compounded 
figure derived from tables of net present value.</P> 

<P>All analyses are made independently, without the bias of vested interests.  
Mentions of products and companies are not endorsements and omissions, if any, 
are not intentional.</P> 


<B>ANALYST CREDENTIALS</B>

<P>The preparer of this study is a biochemist who also has an MBA degree. He has 
both academic and industry experience extending many years. At BCC, he has 
written numerous studies on biotechnology subjects. He also has provided 
confidential consulting to single clients, which has included repeat business. 
He is the editor of Applied Genetics News and Stereochemical Technology News 
and is the organizer of BCC's biotechnology conferences.</P> 


<B>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B>

<P>Published BCC studies relating to the topic of genetic technology, to  
enabling products for it, and to the products resulting from its application, 
done by the analyst of this study or by others, include the following:</P> 

<UL>
<LI>C-040R:   Needs of the Biotechnology Industry
<LI>C-065N:   Bioengineered Protein Drugs 
<LI>C-099:    Prospects for Food Biotechnology
<LI>C-103:    Expanding Horizons for Gene Probes
<LI>C-109:    Antisense Oligonucleotides
<LI>C-144:    Reagents for Biotechnology
<LI>C-147R/B: Specialty Enzymes
<LI>C-160:    Human Gene Therapy
</UL>




