<HEAD><TITLE>
C-202  NEW DEVELOPMENTS IN THERAPEUTIC ENZYME INHIBITORS AND
RECEPTOR 
BLOCKERS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMP ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-202 NEW DEVELOPMENTS IN THERAPEUTIC ENZYME
INHIBITORS 
AND RECEPTOR BLOCKERS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
SENIOR MARKET ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS OF THIS STUDY</B><P>

The principal objective of this study is to communicate facts, data and  technical information
relevant to a business understanding of enzyme inhibitors and receptor blockers, especially from
the strategic perspective. The goal of the study is to have it be a meaningful guide for companies
pursuing commercial developments in this field.<P> 


<B>REASONS FOR STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTION</B><P>

Many drugs work by exerting physiological effects, i.e. by causing events to happen. On the other
hand, a significant number of drugs work by preventing physiological effects, i.e. by causing
events not to happen.  These kinds of substances are the therapeutic enzyme 
inhibitors and receptor blockers.<P>

In the past, many of the inhibitors and blockers were developed hit or miss, and without 
necessarily knowing precisely how they worked. Now, research is providing insights as to 
how these "old" drugs in fact work, leading to potential improvements in existing drug 
categories. Furthermore, biomedical research in biotechnology companies and academia is 
revealing new biological targets for possible therapeutic intervention with entirely new 
classes of inhibitors and blockers.<P> 

Efforts commonly described as "small-molecule research" and "drug discovery research" 
generally involve the kinds of substances taken up in this study.  A large fraction of the 
biotechnology industry in fact deals with the development of therapeutic inhibitors and 
blockers.<P> 




Another new development concerns new technologies for finding and making therapeutic 
enzyme inhibitor and receptor blocker molecules. These new technologies include 
combinatorial chemistry, high-throughput screening, rational drug design, and chiral 
technology.<P>


<B>AUDIENCE FOR THIS REPORT</B><P>

This report should be of interest and value to pharmaceutical companies and biotechnology 
companies seeking to keep up with commercial developments in this field, as well as to 
combinatorial chemistry companies, chirotechnology companies and drug discovery 
companies.  We also believe that investors who may be overlooking significant but under-
publicized activities will find this report worth reading. Anyone who has invested, or is 
thinking about investing in inhibitor and blocker research and development ought to consider the
sales and potential future sales of their products, which analysis this study provides.<P> 


<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT OF STUDY</B><P>

Included in this study are enzyme inhibitors and receptor blockers already available, or 
intended for, therapeutic use. We include a world perspective on inhibitors and blockers 
curently available and those being investigated or under development for such use. <P>

Excluded from this study are discussions of the kinds of inhibitors and blockers that serve use in
basic research, i.e. those used for investigations aimed at elucidating the binding sites or
mechanistic behavior of enzymes and receptors, although an Appendix lists many of these
substances.<P> 

This study excludes discussion or sales analysis of therapeutic antibiotics and agricultural 
pesticides, even though a large percentage of them act as either inhibitors or blockers. An 
Appendix briefly mentions a few of the antibiotics.<P>

Also excluded from this study: receptor agonists, antisense molecules and therapeutic 
enzymes.<P>  

Readers should note that this study emphasizes the commercial aspects of enzyme inhibitors and
receptor blockers and their practical medical applications. Although this study discusses some of
the relevant basic research, this study does not constitute a roundup or comprehensive review of
basic scientific research merely happening to take place in company settings.<P> 

This is not a sales audit report of the kind that certain well-known pharmaceutical databases 
already provide: we are not providing explicit, comprehensive past-year brand and dosage 
form sales. This is instead a strategic level,  forward-looking "new developments" report 
particularly oriented toward forecasting.<P> 


<B>STUDY METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Primary information for this study comes from telephone interviews with business managers or
head scientists, depending on the relevancy. Secondary sources of information encompass
available company literature, scientific journals, medical literature and the trade press.<P> 

Sales are presented in millions of dollars ($ MM), where one million = 106. All figures refer to
worldwide sales unless indicated otherwise. Sales figures refer to the total for the compound or
compound category: we aggregate all dosage forms and strengths of a compound into a single
figure. Forecasts are made to the year 2000 and are expressed in constant 1995 dollars to reflect
real changes without inflation.  The average annual growth rate percentage (AAGR%) is a
compounded figure derived from tables of net present value.<P> 

All analyses are made independently, without the bias of vested interests. Mentions of 
products and companies are not endorsements, and omissions, if any, are not intentional.<P> 


<B>ANALYST CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The analyst of this study is a chemist and biochemist who also has an M.B.A. degree.  Having
both academic and industrial laboratory research experience at senior levels, he has been writing
technical-business studies at BCC for 13 years and serves as its biotechnology 
director.  He is editor of both Applied Genetics News  and Stereochemical Technology News  and
is the organizer of BCC's conferences on commercial biotechnology.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

Published BCC studies relating to the present topic, done by the analyst or by others, 
include:<P>
<UL>
