<CENTER><H2>DBE95 BATTERY & EV INDUSTRY REVIEW
</H2>

<HR><P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


<B>INDUSTRY OVERVIEW</B><P>

Electrochemical cells, generically known as batteries, are
used to save and transport electrical energy.  These
functions -- power storage and power portability -- make
batteries essential to today's industrial and consumer-
oriented society.  Although simple batteries have existed
for at least 200 years, the battery industry traces its
roots to the early 1900s.  At that time, the
commercialization of automobiles and radios created a demand
for automotive (starting, lighting, ignition and generator)
batteries and portable appliance batteries.  These markets,
characterized by primary (disposable) and secondary
(rechargeable) batteries, remain the two areas where most
batteries are consumed.  Automotive batteries are a distinct
secondary battery market subsector.<P>

As such, most of the battery industry is considered mature,
with demand closely related to the sales of either
automobiles or various consumer products.  Unlike many
mature industries, battery demand is also related to service
life, and hence, replacement sales.  Even rechargeable
secondary batteries must eventually be discarded and
replaced.  In many applications, replacement sales are the
driving force in market growth.<P>

On the other hand, there are areas where the battery
industry could experience the explosive growth usually
associated with juvenile industries.  Portable computers,
computer memory preservation, mobile telephones and portable
video cameras didn't exist as well-developed markets 15
years ago.  Now, these battery-using products are
commonplace.  Electric vehicles, utility load leveling, and
remote power storage stations represent an underdeveloped
role for batteries and potential new markets.  Advances in
battery technology promise to increase battery power
density, service and cycle life.  Lithium-containing and
nickel-hydrogen (including nickel metal-hydride) batteries
were a specialized niche 10 years ago.  Now, they are
available to the general consumer and are displacing a
number of existing battery technologies.  Further down the
road, developmental systems like conductive polymer, sodium-
sulfur, redox and others could allow unprecedented battery
configuration and performance.  These two developments, new
markets and improved performance will help batteries replace
more conventional power sources (internal combustion
engines, utility AC power, etc.).<P>

The goal of battery designers is a portable accumulator that
stores large amounts of electricity for long periods of
time, allows repeated charge-discharge cycles and is
inexpensive.  The question is no longer if these goals can
be met.  Today's research is directed towards improving
these criteria to performance levels heretofore considered
impossible.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Battery technical advances and a realignment of the battery
industry players must be matched by new marketing attitudes.
Competing manufacturers and suppliers must be identified.
Batteries must be matched with appliance requirements.  New
battery performance requires new appliance designs.
Material requirements necessary for a new generation of
batteries must be identified.  Reliable supplies of these
materials must be secured.  Competing technology, including
both non-battery systems and new battery systems, threaten
existing kinds of batteries.  Is it better to abandon
outmoded technology, replace it with new technology, or get
out of the battery business altogether?  What is the extent
of existing technology and markets?  This BCC document
addresses these problems.<P>

                       


