<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-044 NEW INDUSTRIAL DIAMOND AND CBN TECHNOLOGY AND MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-044 NEW INDUSTRIAL DIAMOND AND CBN TECHNOLOGY AND MARKETS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS ABRAHAM, D. Eng. Sci.</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Diamond possess the greatest hardness and greatest thermal
conductivity among all known materials. Combined with these important
properties, diamond has very low thermal expansion and high electrical
resistance. Because of its hardness, diamond is far more effective and
efficient than other competing materials used for abrasive, cutting,
shaping or finishing tools.<P>

Industrial diamond is either tailor-made synthetic diamond, or natural
diamond that does not meet the standards of gem diamond because of its
color, size or some other imperfection. Synthetic diamond was first
synthesized by J.B. Hannay in 1880 by heating bone oil, lithium, and
hydrocarbons in sealed iron tubes at a red heat.<P>

The diamond and  CBN material industry interfaces directly with the
heavy, automotive, construction and stone cutting industries through
the widespread use of diamond and CBN products for grinding, cutting,
polishing and finishing operations. The industry is characterized by
different production technologies, from high-temperature,
high-pressure synthesis for diamond and cubic boron nitride to plasma
CVD for diamond and CBN films and coatings. The diamond and CBN
product technologies are characterized by different forming methods
such as electroplated, resin- and metal-bonded and vitrified products.
Brazing technologies are also adopted for single crystal or
polycrystalline products.<P>

Several segments of the diamond and CBN industry are characterized by
rapid innovations and technological changes. Composed of a wide
variety of products, the industrial diamond and CBN materials and
products industry is in the midst of booming sales and growth.<P>

There has been an explosion of interest in diamond, diamond-like and
CBN films and coatings. These films are expected to be used in a
variety of applications from cutting tools to wear-resistant parts,
and from electronics to optical applications. One advantage of CVD
diamond technology over the high-pressure technology is its low cost.<P>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This BCC report has been prepared because a lot of new developments
have been taking place in the industrial diamond and CBN materials and
products. Some of the market segments are matured while others are
growing at very fast rates. Secondly, there have been new developments
in materials, processing and applications in the areas of diamond and
CBN materials and their products, including films and coatings. These
have contributed a need to make a proper analysis of the technological
and business issues, trends in manufacturing as well as foreign
competition. Thirdly, the trend toward high performance materials and
technologies necessitates high performance tools and devices in which
diamond and CBN materials play major roles.<P>

This report has been prepared with the following objectives:<P>

<LI>To provide an overview of the various industrial diamond and CBN
materials, films and products, their production technologies and
applications.<P>

<LI>To identify the technological and business issues related to the
commercial production of diamond and CBN materials, PCD and PCBN
blanks, and diamond, diamond-like and CBN films.<P>

<LI>To identify the technological and business issues related to the
commercial production of diamond, CBN, PCD and PCBN products.<P>

<LI>To understand the inter-material competition among the various
diamond, CBN, PCD, PCBN and diamond and CBN coated products.<P>

<LI>To identify the technological and business issues related to the
development and commercial production of diamond, diamond-like, and
CBN films and coated products.<P>

<LI>To analyze the domestic and foreign competition among companies within
each of the diamond and CBN materials, PCD and PCBN blanks, diamond
and diamond-like films, and their product market segments.<P>

<LI>To determine the current size and future growth of the U.S. markets
for diamond and CBN materials, films and products.<P>

<LI>To determine the current size of the world markets for diamond and CBN
materials, films and products.<P>

<LI>To identify and profile all U.S. producers, suppliers and users of
diamond, CBN, PCD, PCBN materials.<P>

<LI>To identify and profile all U.S. producers and suppliers of diamond,
CBN, PCD and PCBN products.<P>

<LI>To identify and profile all U.S. producers and those involved in the
development of diamond, diamond-like and CBN films and products.<P>

<LI>To identify the foreign companies involved in the diamond and CBN
materials, films and products.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION TO THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC's technical/economic study covers the technical and industry
overviews, materials, current and emerging production methods, new
developments in materials and processing techniques, business and
development issues, current and emerging applications and an extensive
market analysis. Current size and future growth of the U.S. markets
are estimated for 1990, 1991 and 1996. Estimation is also made on the
current world markets.<P>

<B>FORMAT AND SCOPE</B><P>

For each material segment, the report provides an analysis of material
and products, types in that category, processing technologies,
properties, applications, new developments, the U.S. markets and
patent analysis.<P>

The qualitative and quantitative judgments embodied in this report are
a valuable contribution to the current knowledge of diamond and CBN
materials and products, their manufacturing technologies, applications
and markets. Moreover, this study has been conducted at a vital stage
when diamond and CBN products are increasing their share of the
markets from competing products. However, there are domestic as well
as foreign competitions not only for the raw products but also for the
final products. With these new developments, decisions are to be made
by a number of companies as to their future strategies of involvement.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The findings of this report are based on information derived from
interviews with almost all producers, potential producers and
suppliers of diamond and CBN materials and their products. Several
industry experts were also contacted for this study. In addition, many
end-users were contacted to evaluate the current and future demands
for these materials. In all, about 300 persons from 250 companies were
contacted for this study.<P>

Secondary data were obtained from industry associations such as
Diamond Wheel Manufacturers Institute, Grinding Wheel Institute,
Society of Manufacturing Engineers, Abrasive Manufacturers Institute,
Abrasive Engineering Society, Industrial Diamond Association of
America; trade publications; technical journals; government statistics
such as from the U.S. Department of Interior (Bureau of Mines), U.S.
Dept. of Commerce (Bureau of Census); and U.S. Patent Database, NTIS
and Dialog computer searches.<P>

<B>WHO SHOULD SUBSCRIBE?</B><P>

This report is directed to the various strata of companies that are
interested in the developments in this field such as:<P>

Companies involved in the development, manufacturing and supplying of
advanced materials.<P>

<MENU>Manufacturers and suppliers of industrial diamond and CBN materials.<BR>

Manufacturers and suppliers of diamond and CBN products.<BR>

Developers and Producers of diamond, diamond-like and CBN films and
coatings.<BR>

Manufacturers and suppliers of abrasive materials.<BR>

Manufacturers and suppliers of advanced ceramic materials and
components.<BR>

Producers and suppliers of advanced electronic and opticalcomponents.<BR>

Producers and suppliers of machine tools.<BR>

Metal working companies.<BR>

Companies involved in the development and manufacture of abrasive
products.<BR>

Importers and suppliers of industrial diamond and CBN materials and
products.<BR>

Manufacturers and suppliers of grinding wheels, cutting wheels,
polishing wheels and other finishing operation devices.<BR>

Manufacturers and suppliers of saw blades, and diamond construction
and stone cutting products.<BR>

Advanced material companies interested in diversification.</MENU><P>

<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

The following is a related BCC study:<P>

<DD>1.   GB-135,  Abrasives: Materials, Processing, Applications,
Economics and Markets, published March 1991.<P>

<DD>2.   WTAP-02, "High-Performance Diamond," An Analysis of the U.S.
Patents, published March 1991.<P>

