<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-058N  U.S. ADVANCED CERAMICS INDUSTRY
Markets, Players and New Developments
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-058N  U.S. ADVANCED CERAMICS INDUSTRY
Markets, Players and New Developments</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Dr. Thomas Abraham</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Advanced materials and particularly advanced ceramics will play an important
role in the future of the U.S. economy. The development and use of advanced
ceramics are revolutionizing the field of material science and technology.
Dramatic changes are taking place in the way materials are used and made. The
result of this foment is the improved performance of existing products and the
birth of new technologies.<P>

Advanced ceramic materials constitute an emerging technology with a very broad
base of current and potential applications and an ever growing list of
material compositions. Indeed, there are several new applications for advanced
ceramics which were anticipated.<P>

Advanced ceramics encompass a variety of materials, markets, and applications.
For structural applications, materials include: Sialon, silicon carbide,
silicon nitride, zirconias, oxides and aluminas. In the broad category of
advanced ceramics, advanced structural ceramics constitute those materials
which are used for high performance applications where a combination of
properties such as wear resistance, hardness, stiffness, corrosion resistance
and low density are important. In addition to these properties, advanced
structural ceramics have relatively high mechanical strength at high
temperatures. Electronic ceramics utilize their functional characteristics and
encompass a range of materials, from simple oxides and nitrides to complex
compounds.<P>

Ceramic powder is a necessary ingredient for most of the structural ceramics,
ceramic composites, electronic ceramics and ceramic coatings. The ceramic
powders used most are oxides, carbides, nitrides and borides.  New
technologies are emerging for the production of ultra pure ceramic powders.
These new developments have helped to improve the quality of ceramic
components. The impact of these new developments will be felt as the advanced
ceramic industry scales up manufacturing processes and the powders produced by
the new processes become competitive with those produced by established
techniques.<P>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Although the advanced ceramics markets and, in particular, the structural
ceramics market had been projected to grow very rapidly in the 1980s, this
rapid growth did not occur. The "Ceramics Fever" of the early and mid-1980's
has gone and a new reality is felt by suppliers of advanced ceramic
components. Also certain defense programs which would have used advanced
ceramics have been shelved for the time being because of the massive cuts in
the military. Also certain ceramic market segments have been losing ground
because of  the emergence of newer technologies that render ceramic components
obsolete.  However, several industrial segments such as cutting tools, wear
parts, bioceramics and ceramic coatings have been growing.<P>

Electronic ceramics constitutes a mature market with some of its segments
growing while others are at a stand still. The new high temperature ceramic
superconductor offers a very good future potential market.<P>

The recession in the last three years has severely affected certain segments
of the advanced ceramics industry such as structural ceramics and, in a
limited way, the ceramics coating business. However, electronic ceramics has
not been much affected by the current recession because of the larger growth
of the electronics industry.<P>

Acquisitions and joint ventures are increasingly taking place in the advanced
ceramics industry. Japanese and European companies have also entered the U.S.
market by setting up their own subsidiaries or through acquisitions and joint
ventures.<P>

Business Communications Co., Inc. has been keeping track of all these
industry developments mentioned above. BCC had earlier published a report
"Advanced Ceramics - A Technical Economic Study," in 1985 and another report,
"A Complete Guide to U.S. Advanced Ceramics Industry," in 1990. In addition to
these, BCC had published over half a dozen reports in advanced ceramic areas,
such as advanced structural ceramics, electronic ceramics, ceramic matrix
composites, ceramic powders, high-performance ceramic coatings, ceramic wear
parts, ceramic magnets and piezoelectric ceramics. With this massive volume of
data available, we felt the need to pool all the information in advanced
ceramics we have acquired so far.<P>

Since our last study in 1990, major changes have occurred in the industry
structure of the U.S. advanced  ceramic industry, including the acquisition of
several U.S. companies by foreign companies. With all these changes, we at BCC
felt that a detailed analysis should be carried out for each segment.<P>

This report has been prepared with the following objectives:<P>

<UL>- To provide an industry overview of structural ceramics, ceramic coatings
and electronic ceramics.<P>

   - To determine the current size and future growth of the U.S. markets for
structural ceramics, ceramic composites, electronic ceramics and ceramic
coatings.<P>

   - To provide a technology overview, including material types, properties
and applications for structural  ceramics (monolithic and ceramic composites),
electronic ceramics and ceramic coatings.<P>

   - To review the technological developments, both in the U.S. and overseas,
as well as the recent patents in structural ceramics, electronic ceramics and
ceramic coatings.<P>

   - To analyze the domestic and foreign competition among companies within
each of the advanced ceramic market segments.<P>

   - To identify and profile all U.S. companies and institutions involved in
advanced ceramics.<P>

   - To analyze the acquisitions, mergers, joint ventures and licensing
agreements in the U.S.advanced ceramics industry.<P>

   - To categorize all U.S. companies according to their involvement in the
various market segments.</UL><P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION TO THE STUDY</B><P>

The new BCC study provides an in-depth analysis of the technological
advancements, new applications, economics, current markets and trends, and the
players in the advanced ceramic industry. Forecasts for each segment are
provided to the year 2000.  Profiles of all U.S. companies and institutions
involved in advanced ceramics as suppliers, users, and researchers are
presented. In depth analyses have been provided for the U.S. advanced ceramic
industry structure, providing detailed information on acquisitions, mergers,
joint ventures and licensing agreements.<P>

Through this report we hope to provide a better understanding of the U.S.
advanced ceramics industry, including current markets, market potential and
players. This study provides the most up-to-date information on U.S. companies
in advanced ceramics.<P>

<B>FORMAT AND SCOPE</B><P>

This BCC study has been conducted with a global perspective in terms of
technology development and its applications. The market projections have  been
calculated for the U.S. only. However, Japanese and European companies are
positioning themselves to take niches of the U.S. advanced ceramics market.
Therefore, we present a detailed analysis of foreign acquisitions, mergers and
licensing agreements occurring in the ceramics industry.<P>

The report provides business planners and managers with an improved
understanding of the direction and impact of advanced ceramics technology, and
how markets will be  affected and opportunities created.<P>

The comprehensive report contains:<P>

<UL>*  An overview of materials for advanced ceramics, their properties, new
         developments, and recent patents<P>

      *  Current and potential uses for advanced ceramics<P>

      *  An analysis of major advances in advanced ceramics technology<P>

      *  Sales projections for advanced ceramics in all the major applications<P>

      *  Detailed profiles of industry players as well as their product lines
         and new product developments<P>

      *  A review of the economic/market opportunities for current industry
         participants and new entrants</UL><P>

We feel, therefore, that the qualitative and quantitative judgements embodied
in this report are a valuable contribution to the current knowledge of
advanced ceramics. Moreover, we are making this contribution at a vital stage
when drastic changes are occurring in the U.S. advanced ceramics industry.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information for this report was collected through extensive industry contacts
with people active in the research, development, production and use of
advanced ceramic components, from government and academic sources active in
research and development, and by reference to the technical literature.
Several industry experts were also interviewed for this study. In addition,
many end-users were contacted to evaluate the current and future demands for
these materials.<P>

Over 300 U.S. companies assisted BCC in identifying and updating new material
developments and their applications as well as the markets. A thorough
computer patent database search was conducted in addition to consulting
several NTIS published searches to evaluate new developments. New developments
and company news appearing in the BCC newsletter, High Tech Ceramics News have
also been included in this report. All the major technical and trade
publications and conference proceedings were also used  for this study.<P>

<B>WHO SHOULD READ THIS REPORT</B><P>

This study is directed to the various strata of companies and institutions
interested in the markets and new developments in this growing field. They
are:<P>

<UL>- Companies involved in  developing, manufacturing and
       supplying advanced materials<P>

     - Companies involved in the development and manufacture of
       advanced ceramic components<P>

     - Suppliers of advanced ceramic powders and components<P>

     - Chemical companies supplying ceramic additives and processing
aids<P>

     - Suppliers of advanced ceramic processing equipment<P>

     - O.E.M. suppliers<P>

     - Government agencies involved in advanced materials<P>

     - Automotive engine manufacturers<P>

     - Producers of cutting tools and wear-resistant parts<P>

     - Producers of implants and dental materials<P>

     - Producers of heat exchangers and recuperators<P>

     - Producers of electronic insulators, capacitors, integrated circuits, and piezoelectric components<P>

     - Producers of permanent magnets and soft magnetic materials<P>

     - Companies providing ceramic coating consumables and coating
        services<P>

     - Companies involved in the development and use of aerospace and
       defense-related materials<P>

     - Venture capital companies and financial institutions interested
       in new attractive investments</UL><P>

<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

The following are related technical and economic analysis reports published by BCC:<P>

<UL>1. GB-107, "Advanced Structural Ceramics," published December 1987.<P>
2. GB-111, "Ceramic Coatings for High-Performance Applications," published
          March 1988.<P>
3. GB-102, "Advanced Ceramic Powders for Structural Components,
          Coatings and Electronic Applications," published March 1990.<P>
4. GB-110R, "Electronic Ceramics," published July, 1990.<P>
5. GB-121, "Ceramic Matrix Composites," published November 1990.<P>
6. DCD-90, "A Complete Guide to the U.S. Advanced Ceramics Industry,"
          published December 1990.<P>
7. GB-152, "Wear-Resistant Ceramic parts," published April 1992.<P>
8. GB-149A, "Permanent Magnets," published October 1992.<P>
9. GB-149B, "Soft Magnetic Materials," published December 1992.</UL><P>


