<HEAD><TITLE> GB-102R: ADVANCED CERAMIC POWDERS AND NANO-SIZED 
                        CERAMIC POWDERS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> GB-102R: ADVANCED CERAMIC POWDERS AND NANO-SIZED 
                        CERAMIC POWDERS </H2>
<HR><P>
<I>THOMAS ABRAHAM, Ph.D </I><BR>
SENIOR INDUSTRY ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>


<P>Advanced ceramic materials constitute an emerging technology with a very broad 
base of current and potential applications and an ever growing list of 
material compositions. Advanced ceramics are inorganic, nonmetallic materials 
with combinations of fine-scale microstructures, purity, complex compositions 
and crystal structures, and accurately controlled additives.  Such materials 
require a level of processing science and engineering far beyond that used in 
making conventional ceramics. These new generations of high-performance 
materials hold promise of markets in the billions of dollars by the end of the 
century. Collectively, they represent an enabling technology, the development 
of which is critical to advances in a host of high-technology applications, 
ranging from modern microelectronics to futuristic auto engines and 
superconductors.</P> 

<P>The outstanding properties possessed by advanced ceramics are achieved through 
special compositions and microstructures that require very careful control 
throughout the successive stages of ceramic processing. These stages are: 
powder synthesis, powder sizing, rheology control, consolidation and forming 
processes, sintering, final machining and inspection.</P> 

<P>Ceramic powder is a necessary ingredient for most of the structural ceramics, 
ceramic composites, electronic ceramics and ceramic coatings. For most 
advanced ceramic components, starting powder is a crucial factor. The 
performance characteristics of a ceramic component are greatly influenced by 
precursor powder characteristics. Among the most important are the powderœs 
chemical purity, particle size distribution and the manner in which the 
powders are packed in the green body before sintering.</P> 

<P>Powders of narrow size distribution can be compacted into ordered arrays and, 
when in the submicron region, these powders are sinter at reduced 
temperatures. Consequently, in the processing of advanced ceramics, there is a 
growing need to develop synthetic techniques capable of producing submicron, 
chemically pure powders with a narrow size distribution. However, the cost is 
again the factor since the new synthetic processing techniques are 
comparatively more expensive than the currently established powder 
manufacturing methods.</P> 


<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>

<P>Since BCC published of a report entitled "Advanced Ceramic Powders" in 1990, 
several new developments have taken place. One important development is the 
availability of nano-sized ceramic powders. BCC has updated this report since 
advanced ceramic powders still constitute the most important ingredient for 
making ceramic components for structural and electronic applications as well 
as for thermal spray ceramic coatings. These three application areas for 
advanced ceramics constitute a global market in the billions of dollars. Also, 
in the last few years, several new powder synthesis techniques have been 
developed as alternatives to established methods. All this has created a need 
for an analysis of the technological and business issues, new developments and 
the trends in ceramic powder production.</P> 

<P>This report has been prepared with the following objectives:</P>

<UL>
<LI>To provide an overview of the various advanced ceramic powders, their
  production technologies and applications.
<LI>To identify the technological and business issues related to the commercial
  production and use of  advanced ceramic powders.
<LI>To analyze the domestic and foreign competition among companies within
  each of the advanced ceramic powder segments.
<LI>To determine the current size and future growth of the markets for oxide,
  carbide, nitride and boride ceramic powders.
<LI>To determine the current size and future growth of the markets for nano-sized
  ceramic powders.
<LI>To identify and profile all U.S. producers of advanced ceramic powders.
<LI>To identify all users of advanced ceramic powders in the U.S.
<LI>To identify the U.S. companies that are currently conducting research and
  development in advanced ceramic powders as well as their areas of research.
<LI>To review important patents in the oxide, carbide, nitride, boride and
  nano-sized advanced ceramic powders.
</UL>

<B>CONTRIBUTION TO THE STUDY</B>

<P>BCCœs technical/economic study covers the markets, materials, synthesis 
techniques, current and emerging production methods, new developments in 
synthesis, current and emerging applications and a market analysis. Current 
size and future growth of the markets are estimated for the period 1993 to 
2000. The report analyzes the competitive environment within each of the 
markets for oxide, carbide, nitride, boride and nano-sized ceramic powders. 
The report profiles all U.S. companies involved in the production of advanced 
ceramic powders.</P> 

<P>Since our last study on advanced ceramic powder, we have included some of the 
smaller market segments such as beryllia, titanium diboride and boron nitride. 
Since nano-sized powder has become an important new development, we have 
carried an extensive technology and market analyses as well as the industry 
structure of this new material.</P> 


<B>FORMAT AND SCOPE</B>

<P>For each ceramic powder type, the report provides an analysis of material 
types in that category, processing technologies, properties, applications, new 
developments in the U.S., Europe and Japan, recent important patents worth 
looking into for commercialization, prices for each powder type and U.S. 
markets according to applications and powder types. A technology review has 
been conducted on the current and emerging ceramic powder production 
technologies such as carbothermal reduction, vapor-phase reaction, plasma 
processes, sol-gel techniques, chemical techniques such as precipitation, 
hydrothermal process, emulsion process, laser synthesis and self-propagating 
high temperature synthesis (SHS). Nano-sized powders have been treated in a 
separate chapter since many nano-sized powder synthesis technologies are 
common to different ceramic powders.</P> 

<P>The qualitative and quantitative judgments embodied in this report are a 
valuable contribution to the current knowledge of advanced ceramic powders and 
nano-sized ceramic powders, their processing techniques, applications and 
markets. Moreover, this study has been conducted at a vital stage in the 
development of this growing industry, where decisions need to be made by a 
number of companies as to their strategies of involvement and expansion as 
well as whether to enter new areas of business.</P> 


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>The findings of this report are based on information derived from interviews 
with almost all producers and potential producers of advanced ceramic powders 
and nano-sized ceramic powders, industry experts and those conducting research 
and development. In addition, many end users were contacted to evaluate the 
current and future demands for these materials. In all about 100 persons from 
60 companies and a dozen institutions were contacted for this study.</P> 

<P>Secondary data were obtained from trade publications, technical journals, 
government statistics, and NTIS and BCC databases.</P> 



<B>WHO SHOULD SUBSCRIBE?</B>

<P>This report is directed to the various strata of companies that are interested 
in the developments in this field such as:</P> 

<UL>

<LI>Companies involved in the development, manufacturing and supplying of
  advanced materials.
<LI>Manufacturers and suppliers of advanced ceramic raw materials.
<LI>Manufacturers and suppliers of advanced ceramic powders.
<LI>Companies involved in R&D and commercialization of nano-sized ceramic
  powders. 
<LI>Companies involved in the development and manufacture of advanced
  ceramic components.
<LI>Engine manufacturers.
<LI>Cutting tool insert manufacturers.
<LI>Manufacturers of integrated circuits, piezoelectric elements, capacitors and
  ceramic magnets.
<LI>Suppliers of thermal spray powders.
<LI>Manufacturers of wear parts and O.E.M. suppliers.
<LI>Chemical companies interested in diversification.
<LI>Venture capital companies and financial institutions interested in new,
  attractive investments and acquisitions. 
</UL>

