<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-110R  CERAMIC MATRIX COMPOSITES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-110R  CERAMIC MATRIX COMPOSITES</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS ABRAHAM, D. Eng. Sci.</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Advanced ceramic materials are an emerging technology with a very broad base
of current and potential applications, and an ever growing list of material
compositions. The promise of performance improvements is the main force
driving the development and commercialization of advanced ceramic materials.
The appeal of advanced ceramics in various applications is due to a
combination of excellent properties such as wear resistance, hardness,
stiffness, corrosion resistance and relatively low density. A major attraction
of ceramics is its relatively high mechanical strength at high temperatures.<P>

Among the family of advanced ceramic materials, ceramic composites will find
wider applications when increased toughness, due to fiber or whisker-
reinforcements, is combined with the inherent refractory properties of the
ceramic materials. Its development will allow the use of ceramics at
temperatures beyond the temperature limits for metals, but without the
familiar brittle fracture of conventional ceramics.<P>

Various types of new advanced ceramic matrix composites are now emerging from
the laboratories, and are undergoing field tests. Their manufacture is usually
based on new findings obtained in connection with the advances in various
fields of science and technology.<P>

A few of the particulate-toughened ceramics, such as the zirconia-toughened
ceramics, are filling applications such as bearings, bushings, precision
balls, valve seats and die inserts where their friction and wear
characteristics have improved both performance and cost. Similarly,
particulate-toughened as well as whisker-reinforced alumina have found use as
cutting tool inserts, replacing carbide and metal tool inserts. For space
shuttle tiles which require a good combination of strength, thermal stability
and low density, the material of choice is silica or a combination of silica
and other ceramic fiber-reinforced ceramic composites.<P>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

BCC had conducted a technical economic study on ceramic matrix composites in
1988. Since then several new developments have taken place. The various
ceramic matrix composite materials, along with their mechanical and high
temperature properties, are examined in this report from scientific and
applications points of view. There are, however, certain technical and
economic issues that remain to be solved. These include such problems as
stringent processing requirements, high cost and competition from some of the
new metal alloys and intermetallics which could withstand temperatures as high
as 1000(C. This report has been prepared with the following objectives:<P>


To provide an overview of materials for ceramic matrix composites, their
processing, new developments and recent patents.<P>

To review the current and potential uses for ceramic matrix composites,
including details of product applications in areas such as cutting tools, wear
resistant parts, engines, aerospace and defense-related, high temperature and
energy-related.<P>

To update major advances in ceramic composite technology.<P>

To determine the current size and future market growth for ceramic matrix
composites according to material types and applications.<P>

To review the U.S. ceramic matrix composite industry structure and foreign
competition.<P>

To identify and profile all U.S. producers and users of ceramic matrix
composites.<P>

To review the economic/market opportunities for current industry participants
and new entrants.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

The new BCC report provides an in-depth analysis of the technological
advancements in ceramic composite materials, and their processing, new
applications, economics, current markets and trends, domestic and foreign
competition and players. Forecasts for each material type and application
segment are provided to the year 2000. Profiles of all U.S. companies and
institutions involved in ceramic matrix composites as suppliers of raw
materials, processors, users and researchers are presented.<P>

<B>FORMAT AND SCOPE</B><P>

The dimensions of the current and future markets for advanced structural
ceramics have been explored by several market researchers, including BCC and a
few government agencies. However, this business opportunity report represents
the most complete technical, economic and marketing document on this subject,
and is designed to provide valuable information for manufacturers and end
users alike.<P>

Finally, the BCC study has been conducted with a global perspective in terms
of technology development and its applications. The market study has been
limited to the U.S. only. Since the Japanese and European companies are
positioning themselves to take niches of the U.S. advanced ceramics market, we
have included foreign players and the competition they pose to the U.S.
companies for each ceramic composite market segment. The report provides
business planners and managers with an improved understanding of the direction
and impact of ceramic composite materials technology, and how markets will be
affected and opportunities created.<P>

The qualitative and quantitative judgements embodied in this report are a
valuable contribution to the current knowledge of ceramic matrix composites.<P>

Moreover, this study has been conducted at a vital stage in the development of
this growing industry, where decisions are to be made by a number of companies
as to their strategies of involvement and expansion as well as whether to
enter new areas of business.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information for this report was collected through extensive industry contacts
with persons active in the development, production and use of ceramic fibers,
whiskers and ceramic matrix composites, from government and academic sources
active in research and development, and by reference to the technical
literature.<P>

Over 100 U.S. companies were contacted for this study to identify various
applications and to update the developments in ceramic matrix materials and
processing technologies. A thorough computer search was conducted in addition
to consulting several NTIS published searches. All the major technical and
trade publications and recent conference proceedings were reviewed for this
study.<P>

<B>WHO SHOULD SUBSCRIBE? </B><P>

This report is directed to the various strata of companies that are interested
in the developments in this field, such as:<P>

-Companies involved in the development, manufacturing and supplying of advanced
materials.<P>

-Suppliers of ceramic, quartz and silica fibers and ceramic whiskers.<P>

-Suppliers of advanced ceramic powders<P>

-Chemical companies supplying ceramic composite additives and processing aids.<P>

-Companies involved in the development and manufacture of advanced ceramic
components.<P>

-Engine manufacturers.<P>

-Wear parts and O.E.M. suppliers.<P>

-Cutting tool inserts manufacturers.<P>

-Suppliers of aerospace materials.<P>

-Companies involved in the development and use of aerospace and defense-related
materials.<P>

-Venture capital companies and financial institutions interested in new
attractive investments.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

 The following are related BCC studies:

1.GB-102, Advanced Ceramic Powders, published March 1990.
2.GB-107, "Advanced Structural Ceramics," published December 1987.
3.GB-108, "Metal Matrix Composites," published December 1988.
4.P-023N, "Advanced Polymer Composites," published August 1988.
5.GB-069R, "High Performance Fibers," published July 1987.<P>


