<HEAD><TITLE> GB-121R: ELECTRONICS CERAMICS: 
                        AN INDUSTRY AND MARKET ANALYSIS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> GB-121R: ELECTRONICS CERAMICS: 
                        AN INDUSTRY AND MARKET ANALYSIS </H2>
<HR><P>
<I>THOMAS ABRAHAM, Ph.D</I><BR>
SENIOR INDUSTRY ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>

<P>The electronic ceramics industry is a high technology industry characterized 
by rapid innovation and technological change. Composed of a wide variety of 
functionally different materials, the electronic ceramic industry is still in 
the midst of a strong expansion and redirection. It interfaces directly with 
the electronics industry through the widespread use of ceramic components as 
an integral part of electronic devices and packages. Several of the electronic 
ceramic market segments are mature but growing steadily. A few of the markets 
range from the concepts being tested in research and development laboratories 
to healthy emerging industries.</P> 

<P>Electronic ceramics provide basic components in the support of a variety of 
electronic products including computers, industrial controls, consumer 
automotive devices and digital switches. They can be used as active 
components, such as semiconductors to control voltage and electrical currents, 
in passive components, such as capacitors and resistors to moderate electrical 
current, or in mechanical applications, such as ferrite magnets or 
piezoelectric devices.</P> 


<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B> 

<P>Electronic ceramics have become a mature market among advanced ceramics and 
are still growing. BCC had published an earlier report on the same subject in 
1990. Since the publication of that report, many business reorganizations have 
occurred among producers of electronic ceramic components. Also, in the 1990s, 
the electronic ceramics industry has been doing quite well because of 
increased demand in electronic components and computers.</P> 

<P>This BCC report has been prepared to incorporate all these business changes 
and provide a detailed industry analysis for the benefit of producers and 
users of electronic ceramic components. Secondly, there have been new 
developments in materials, processing and applications in the areas of 
electronic ceramics. These have contributed to a need to make a proper 
analysis of the technological and business issues and trends in manufacturing 
as well as foreign competition.</P> 


<P>This report has been prepared with the following objectives:</P> 

<UL>

   <LI>To provide an overview of the various electronic ceramics, their 
     production technologies and applications.
   
   <LI>To identify the technological and business issues  related to the 
     commercial production of electronic ceramic components.
   <LI>To update the new developments in emerging technologies such as
     piezoelectric ceramics, ceramic packagings and high temperature
     superconductors.
   
   <LI>To analyze the domestic and foreign competition among companies within
     each of the electronic ceramic segments.
   
   <LI>To determine the current size and future growth of the markets for 
     electronic ceramic segments.
   
   <LI>To identify and profile all U.S. producers and suppliers of electronic 
     ceramic components.
   
   <LI>To identify the U.S. companies that are currently conducting research and
     development in electronic ceramics as well as their areas of research.
</UL>

<B>CONTRIBUTION TO THE STUDY</B> 

<P>BCCœs technical/economic study covers the markets, materials, fabrication 
techniques, current and emerging production methods, new developments in 
materials and processing techniques, current and emerging applications, and a 
market analysis. Current size and future growth of the markets are estimated 
for the period 1994 to the year 2000. The report analyzes the competitive 
environment within each of the markets for insulators, substrates, integrated 
circuits, capacitors, piezoelectric ceramics, ferrite magnets and 
superconductor ceramics. The report profiles all U.S.  producers and suppliers 
of electronic ceramic components.</P> 


<B>FORMAT AND SCOPE</B> 

<P>For each electronic ceramic application segment, the report provides an 
analysis of material types in that category, processing technologies, 
properties, applications, new developments, and the U.S. markets.</P> 

<P>The report provides a valuable contribution to the current knowledge of 
electronic ceramics including their processing techniques, applications and 
markets. The study also provides vital information on the growth of various 
market segments so as to help companies with their future strategies of 
involvement and expansion as well as deciding whether to enter new areas of 
the electronic ceramic business.</P> 

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B> 

<P>The findings of this report are based on information derived from interviews 
with almost all producers, potential producers and suppliers of electronic 
ceramic components, industry experts and those conducting research and 
development. In addition, many end users were contacted to evaluate the 
current and future demands for these materials. In all, about 200 persons from 
120 companies and a dozen institutions were contacted for this study.</P> 

<P>Secondary data was obtained from industry associations such as the Electronic 
Industry Association, the Magnetic Materials Producers Association; trade 
publications; technical journals; government statistics such as those from the 
Dept. of Commerce, International Trade Administration and Bureau of the 
Census; U.S. Patent Database and NTIS computer searches.</P> 


<B>WHO SHOULD SUBSCRIBE?</B> 

<P>This report is directed to the various strata of companies that are interested 
in the developments in this field such as:</P> 

<UL>

   <LI>Companies involved in the development, manufacturing and supplying of
     advanced materials.
   
   <LI>Manufacturers and suppliers of advanced ceramic raw materials.
   
   <LI>Manufacturers and suppliers of advanced ceramic powders.
   
   <LI>Companies involved in the development and manufacture of advanced
     ceramic components.
   
   <LI>Electronic insulator and substrate manufacturers.
   
   <LI>Manufacturers of integrated circuits, piezoelectric elements, capacitors 
     and ceramic magnets.
   
   <LI>Companies involved in the development of superconductor components.
   
   <LI>Suppliers of electronic ceramic components.
   
   <LI>Ceramic companies interested in diversification.
   
   <LI>Venture capital companies and financial institutions interested in new,
     attractive investments.
</UL>


