<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-152  WEAR-RESISTANT CERAMIC PARTS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-152  WEAR-RESISTANT CERAMIC PARTS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DR. THOMAS ABRAHAM</I><BR>
SENIOR INDUSTRY ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Following a long period of extensive research and development
efforts, advanced structural ceramics are now a reality, with
increasing usage in many load-bearing applications such as cutting
tools, automotive engine components, heat exchangers,
wear-resistant parts and aerospace components.<P>

Among the structural ceramics applications, wear-resistant ceramic
components constitute an important segment. Wear has plagued
equipment designers and plant operators since the beginning of
industrial development. Wear affects equipment and plant
efficiency, maintenance frequency, product quality, profitability,
to name but a few variables. As industry becomes more time and cost
conscious, increasing attention is being paid to the wear of
critical components and the components' intrinsic relationship to
output and efficiency. Although advanced ceramic wear parts are
sometimes more expensive, they could still become cost effective if
efficiency is improved by reducing downtime.<P>

Monolithic ceramic is the most commonly used wear-resistant ceramic
material. In certain applications, ceramic fiber or
whisker-reinforced ceramic matrix composites are found to be better
than monolithic ceramics. Ceramic-coated components, which are also
produced commercially now, have properties similar to monolithic
ceramic or ceramic matrix composites.<P>

Wear-resistant ceramic applications include bearings, mechanical
seals, liners for mineral and processing industries, grinding
media, ball mill liners, metal processing dies, thread and wire
guides, pulleys, sandblast nozzles, etc. The components are
produced using monolithic ceramics, ceramic matrix composites or
ceramic coatings.<P>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Although several applications have been established in the
wear-resistant ceramics area, proper technical economic analyses of
the various segments have not been done so far. As a growing area,
BCC felt that a detailed analysis should be carried for each
segment.<P>

This report has been prepared with the following objectives:<P>

<MENU><LI>To provide an overview of the various ceramic wear-resistant
components, their production technologies and applications<P>

<LI>To identify the technological developments and business issues
related to the commercial production of ceramic wear-resistant
components<P>

<LI>To understand the inter-material competition among the various
ceramic wear-resistant components<P>

<LI> To analyze the domestic and foreign competition among
companies within each of the ceramic wear-resistant market
segments.<P>

<LI>To determine the current size and future growth of the U.S.
markets for ceramic wear-resistant components.<P>

<LI> To identify and profile all U.S. producers and suppliers of
ceramic wear-resistant components.<P>

<LI> To identify the foreign companies which manufacture ceramic
wear-resistant components.</MENU><P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

The new BCC study provides an in-depth analysis of the
technological advancements, new applications, economics, current
markets and trends, and players. Forecasts for each segment are
provided to the year 1996.  Profiles of all U.S. companies and
institutions involved as suppliers, users, and researchers in the
advanced ceramic wear component industry are presented in Appendix
I. In Appendix II, we feature profiles of companies which supply
ceramic raw materials to the manufacturers of ceramic
wear-resistant parts.<P>

<B>FORMAT AND SCOPE</B><P>

The BCC study has been conducted with a global perspective in terms
of technology development and its applications. The market study
has been conducted for the U.S. only. However, Japanese and
European companies are positioning themselves to take niches of the
U.S. advanced ceramics market. Therefore, we have reviewed the
foreign competition for each wear-resistant ceramic market segment.<P>

The report provides business planners and managers with an improved
understanding of the direction and impact of wear-resistant
ceramics technology, and how markets will be affected and
opportunities created.<P>

The comprehensive report contains:<P>

<MENU><LI>    An overview of materials for wear-resistant ceramics,
processing, new developments, and recent patents.<P>

<LI>   Current and potential uses for wear-resistant ceramics,
including details of product applications.<P>

<LI>    An analysis of major advances in wear-resistant ceramics
technology.<P>

<LI>    Sales projections for wear-resistant ceramics in all the major
applications.<P>

<LI>   Detailed profiles of industry players as well as their product
lines and new product developments.<P>

<LI>    Review of the economic/market opportunities for current
industry participants and new entrants.</MENU><P>

We feel, therefore, that the qualitative and quantitative judgments
embodied in this report are a valuable contribution to the current
knowledge of wear-resistant ceramics. Moreover, we are making this
contribution at a vital stage in the development of this growing
industry, where decisions must soon be made by companies on their
strategies of involvement.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information for this report was collected through extensive
industry contact with people active in the development, production
and use of advanced ceramics and with those producers of
wear-resistant parts, from government and academic sources active
in research and development, and by reference to the technical
literature. Several industry experts were also interviewed for this
study. In addition, many end-users were contacted to evaluate the
current and future demands for these materials.<P>

Over 100 U.S. companies assisted BCC in identifying and updating
new material developments and their applications. A thorough
computer patent database search was conducted in addition to
consulting several NTIS published searches to evaluate new
developments. All the major technical and trade publications
together with conference proceedings were consulted.<P>

<B>WHO SHOULD READ THIS REPORT</B><P>

This study is directed to planners and decision-makers interested
in developments in this field. They will be in:<P>

<MENU><LI>    Companies involved in developing, manufacturing and supplying
advanced materials<P>

<LI>   Companies involved in the development and manufacture of
advanced ceramic components<P>

<LI>   Suppliers of advanced ceramic powders and components<P>

<LI>  Producers of ceramic bearings, mechanical seals, dies, guides,
pulleys, liners, grinding media and nozzles<P>

<LI>  Chemical companies supplying ceramic additives and processing
aids<P>

<LI>    Suppliers of advanced ceramic processing equipment<P>

<LI>    Wear parts and O.E.M. suppliers<P>

<LI>  Companies involved in the development and use of aerospace and
defense-related materials<P>

<LI>   Venture capital companies and financial institutions
interested in new attractive investments</MENU><P>

<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

The following are related technical and economic analysis reports
published by BCC:<P>

<MENU>GB-107,     "Advanced Structural Ceramics," published December
1987<P>
GB-111,     "Ceramic Coatings for High-Performance
Applications," published March 1988<P>
GB-102,     "Advanced Ceramic Powders for Structural Components,
Coatings and Electronic Applications," published March 1990<P>
GB-110R,    "Ceramic Matrix Composites," published November
1990<P>
GB-044,"    New Industrial Diamond and CBN Technologies and
Markets," published November 1991<P>
DCD-90,     "A Complete Guide to the U.S. Advanced Ceramics
Industry," published December 1990.</MENU><P>


