<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-153  TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER REPORT:
WHO'S DOING WHAT WITH WHAT
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-153  TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER REPORT:
WHO'S DOING WHAT WITH WHAT</H2>
<HR><P>

<I>SUSAN KAPLAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Although technology transfer and assistance programs offer companies
a way to get a larger bang for their research buck, the process is
quite complicated and confusing.  This BCC study is intended to help
eliminate some of the confusion and to provide a roadmap for those
interested in utilizing these resources as well for as those wishing
to make more effective use of them.<P>

The emphasis of most existing technology-transfer programs is on
transferring federally-funded research from national laboratories,
the military, universities, and other non-profit organizations to
the private sector and the States.  Hence, the focus of this BCC
report is primarily on these activities, which are addressed
quantitatively.<P>

However, there are other important aspects that are addressed
qualitatively.  Such aspects include technology assistance programs,
many of which are being established by the States with matching
funds from the Federal government; transfers from one private-sector
company to another; and international transfers.  Technology
assistance programs are being established to help small to mid-size
companies become more competitive through upgrading manufacturing
and computer capabilities (especially the use of online databases).
Private companies are involved in tech transfer through the
acquisition of new technologies and in shifting technologies that do
not fit their corporate structures to other firms.  International
transfers are experiencing more interest especially as a result of
the changes that are occurring in the former Soviet Union but also
because of the general trend of world market unification.<P>


<B>BACKGROUND INFORMATION</B><P>

It has been demonstrated that the aggressive refinement of existing
technology and the transforming of that technology into commercial
products works.  However, while U.S. companies seem to be reluctant
to do this, a number of foreign countries (Japan in particular) do
not have this reluctance.  The Japanese have quite successfully
taken U.S.-developed technologies (e.g., semiconductors, VCRs, LCDs,
certain types of optics and instrumentation, and flat-panel
displays) and turned them into commercial products.  However,
improved U.S. competitiveness through technology transfer will most
likely require the adoption by industry of a more long-range view
instead of the shortsighted quarterly- (or even monthly-) review.<P>

Tech transfer has received increasing attention and emphasis in
recent years as U.S. industrial competitiveness has eroded and as we
seek to make better use of our R&D dollars.  Federally-funded R&D is
being scrutinized for possible cuts because of the troubled economy
and our huge budget deficit.  The end of the Cold War has also
resulted in more emphasis on tech transfer.  As defense budgets
decline, it has become even more important for the Departments of
the Defense and Energy to demonstrate that their defense programs
can also be applied to peacetime applications.<P>

The purpose of the many federal and university tech transfer
programs is to effect better utilization of research and development
resources.  To quote Admiral James D. Watkins (Secretary of Energy),
"It is not enough to make it easier for industry to work with the
Federal government.  We have to make matches between what industry
wants and needs and what the Federal researchers can contribute."
However, it is not only a federal effort.  The above quote applies
not only to federal-laboratory researchers, but to university and
non-profit researchers that operate with funds from federal and
state programs.<P>

Organizations transfer technology through license agreements and, in
the case of government laboratories, Cooperative Research and
Development Agreements (CRADAs), reimbursable work-for-others
agreements, consulting, and user facilities.  Corporate technology
is also transferred through licensing as well as other arrangements
such as the sale of patents and business units or divisions, joint
ventures, and research consortias with other companies,
universities, and government agencies.<P>

The federally-funded laboratories (at least some of them) seem to be
very excited about being allowed to help American companies.
According to the Cooperative Technology RD&D Report, they feel that
"the real American technology genie is being let out of the bottle
with CRADAs, and that foreign companies are excluded from getting
their help."  However, note that there are some exceptions to the
no-foreign-company rule, especially for environmental, fossil-fuel,
and renewable-energy conservation technologies.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC feels that it is imperative to the U.S. that technology transfer
programs succeed and is, indeed, the wave of the future.  Although
Federal technology transfer is not a panacea for U.S. industry and
has many, many hurdles to overcome, it is a massive and extremely
important resource that American industry should not ignore.
Unfortunately, the difficulty in dealing with the bureaucracy
requires those interested in obtaining technologies to be persistent
and not give up when (not if) difficulties and frustrations are
encountered.  In addition, the programs and resources to facilitate
these activities seem to change almost daily!  Hopefully, one day
the bugs will be worked out and a system that works (for all
organizations and not just a select few) will be in place.  Until
then, BCC hopes to provide a link for those involved in these
activities and an important means of disseminating information.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This BCC report will prove invaluable for individuals and
organizations involved in technology transfer.  In particular, those
who will benefit from this study include:<P>

<UL><LI>Organizations interested in discovering how to obtain rights
        to new technologies and how to participate in cooperative
     research ventures<P>

 <LI>Those currently licensing technologies or participating in
     cooperative research ventures<P>

 <LI>Companies and other research organizations that have
     technology available for licensing or joint projects or
     are in the process of developing transferable technologies<P>

 <LI>Officials involved in setting up technology transfer
programs<P>

<LI>Organizations that facilitate the transfer process such as
     associations, consulting companies, brokers, etc.<P>

<LI>Those interested in learning what resources are available to
     assist in setting up international ventures.<P></UL>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The report discusses exactly what technology transfer is, the
process, programs, culture clashes, and the various mechanisms or
models that may be used in its implementation.  The study also
discusses the response to the call by "the powers that be" for
technology transfer and the special programs that have been
developed.  Information on the following is provided:<P>

<UL><LI>Barriers to technology transfer and the legal aspects;<P>
<LI>Government-sponsored-research transfer programs:
     Steps taken to promote technologies,
     Access to technologies, facilities, and people:<P>
<DD>Licensing intellectual property,<BR>
<DD>Cooperative R&D agreements (CRADAs),<BR>
<DD>Reimbursable work-for-others agreements,<BR>
<DD>Consultants,<BR>
<DD>User facilities;<P>
<LI>University and corporate programs;<P>
<LI>Research consortias;<P>
<LI>Programs and resources facilitating foreign exchanges;<P>
<LI>Participants, including licensors, licensees, and those
   organizations that help bridge the gap between the two;<P>
<LI>Specific technologies that are (or were) available for
   licensing;<P>
<LI>Conferences, newsletters, and other related publications;<P>
<LI>Comprehensive directory.<P></UL>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The bulk of the information for this report was obtained through
telephone contacts and information received from government
agencies, universities, and other organizations, particularly those
involved in promoting available technologies. Information was also
obtained from those involved in facilitating the transfer of
technology and from other published literature.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Related BCC works that may be of interest include our full range of
technology-based reports and newsletters, but particularly our
Industries in Transition Newsletter and Report GB-144,
"Opportunities for Transferring Defense-Related Advanced Optics."<P>


<B>REQUEST FOR INPUT</B><P>

BCC is considering making this an annual publication, depending on
reader response.  In order to better serve your needs, we request
that you submit technology transfer information to the author, in
care of BCC.  Comments and suggestions regarding content and
relevance are strongly encouraged.<P>


<B>DISCLAIMER</B><P>

The author assumes no liability for the information in this report
or for its use.  The material is intended to be as reliable as
possible and of a professional nature.  The author assumes no
liability for any loss or damage as a result of any reliance on any
materials or any information developed.  This is not a legal or
accounting document and much of the information is of a speculative
nature.<P>

