<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-165A  CARBON/GRAPHITE FIBERS: Highlighting New
Applications, U.S. and Global Markets, Players and Developments
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-165A  CARBON/GRAPHITE FIBERS: Highlighting New
Applications, U.S. and Global Markets, Players and Developments
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS ABRAHAM, Ph.D.
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Carbon fiber has been used as a fibrous reinforcement for composite materials
for the last 25 years. Even though high-performance carbon fibers were first
introduced in the 1960s, the physical properties of these reinforcing fibers
have improved dramatically over the past decade. This can be attributed to
three developments: significant improvements in both quality and performance
of the precursor fiber; a substantial increase in worldwide production
capacity and process improvements resulting from this gain in production
experience; and a strong push on the part of the United States and Western
European aerospace industries for high performance carbon-based reinforcing
fibers.<P>

Military aircrafts and aerospace applications provided a boost to the
commercial use of carbon fibers. However, the carbon companies have now
shifted their thrust from military aircraft to commercial aircraft, industrial
applications, and sporting goods.<P>


<b>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Before the cold war was over in the late 1980s, the prospects for carbon
fibers were very bright. The military establishment strongly promoted U.S. self reliance on carbon fibers for military applications. The markets were forecasted to double and triple by the mid 1990s by several industry experts.  In the late 1980s, the government also passed legislation that would make it mandatory for the military to buy domestically produced polyacrylonitrile. In turn, the producers started or added to their capacities for domestically produced polyacrylonitrile. However, because of major defense cuts, there was a slump in the market. Certain defense programs, including some of the new military aircraft, were shelved for the time being because of the massive cuts in the military.  This caused the carbon fiber industry to go through a turmoil in the early 1990s. Some companies exited from the business while others shut down their production facilities briefly to reduce the inventories.<P>

The recession in the last three years was also a factor in the downturn of the
carbon fiber industry. However, the economy is now showing signs of
improvement. Several nonmilitary segments, such as the industrial, sports and
recreation products, have been growing. The carbon fiber industry's thrust has
now shifted from military to commercial applications.<P>

The trends in acquisitions and joint ventures are continuing in the carbon
fiber industry. The Japanese companies have also entered the U.S. market by
setting up their own subsidiaries or through acquisition and joint ventures.<P>

Business Communications Company has tracked all of these industry
developments. Earlier it published a report, "High Performance Fibers - A
Technical Economic Study," in 1987 and another report, "Structural Carbon," in
1989. Both these reports had extensively covered carbon fibers.<P>

Since our last study in 1990, major changes have occurred in the U.S. and
global carbon fiber industry structure. Many companies have reorganized or
joined together. With all these changes, BCC felt that a detailed analysis
should be conducted on this important industry.<P>

This report has been prepared with the following objectives:<P>

<UL>-    To provide an industry overview of the U.S. and global carbon fiber
     industry<P>

-    To determine the current size and future growth of the U.S. and  global
     markets for carbon fibers<P>

-    To provide a technology overview, including material types, properties and
     applications for carbon fibers and carbon fiber products<P>

-    To review technological developments, including the U.S. and foreign
     developments as well as the recent patents in carbon fibers and carbon
     fiber products<P>

-    To analyze the domestic and foreign competition in the carbon fiber
     industry<P>

-    To identify and profile all U.S. companies and institutions involved in the
     carbon fiber industry<P>

-    To review the acquisitions, mergers, joint ventures and licensing
     agreements among carbon fiber companies on a global scale<P>

-    To determine the trends in the carbon fiber markets.<P></UL>


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This new BCC study provides an in-depth analysis of technological
advancements, new applications, economics, current markets and trends, and
players. Forecasts for each U.S. market segment are provided to the year 1998.
Profiles of all U.S. producer and user companies have been provided. In-depth
analyses are presented on the global carbon fiber industry structure,
providing detailed information on acquisitions, mergers, joint ventures and
licensing agreements.<P>

Through this report we hope to provide a better understanding of the U.S. and
global carbon fiber industry, including current markets, market potential and
players. Detailed profiles of all U.S. companies who are producers of carbon
fiber and carbon fiber products are provided in this report. This study
provides the most up to date information we have gathered on the carbon fiber
industry.<P>


<b>FORMAT AND SCOPE</B><P>

This study has been conducted with a global perspective in terms of technology
developments, applications and markets. The market projections reflect this
global focus. The Japanese companies have positioned themselves to take a
large percentage of the global market. Therefore, we have provided detailed
analyses of foreign acquisitions, mergers and licensing agreements which are
happening in the carbon fiber industry.<P>

The report provides business planners and managers with an improved
understanding of the direction of the carbon fiber industry and how markets
will be affected and new opportunities created.<P>

The comprehensive report contains:<P>

<UL><LI>   An overview of carbon fibers, their properties, new
         developments, and recent patents.<P>

<LI>   Current and potential uses for carbon fibers.<P>

<LI>   An analysis of major advances in carbon fiber technology.<P>

<LI>   Sales projections for carbon fibers in all the major market
         segments.<P>

<LI>   Detailed profiles of industry players as well as their product
         lines and new product developments.<P>

<LI>   Review of the economic/market opportunities for current
         industry participants and new entrants.<P></UL>

We feel, therefore, that the qualitative and quantitative judgments embodied
in this report are a valuable contribution to the current knowledge of the
carbon fiber industry. Moreover, we are making this contribution at a vital
stage when drastic changes are happening in the carbon fiber industry with the
emergence of several nonmilitary applications.<P>

<b>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information for this report was collected through extensive industry contacts
with people active in the research, development, production and use of
advanced ceramic components, from government and academic sources active in
research and development, and by reference to the technical literature.
Several industry experts were also interviewed for this study. In addition,
many end-users were contacted to evaluate the current and future demands for
these materials.<P>

Over 50 U.S. companies assisted BCC in identifying and updating new
developments, applications and markets. A thorough U.S. patent database search
was conducted for the period from the middle of 1991 to the middle of 1993, in
addition to consulting several NTIS published searches to evaluate new
developments. All the major technical and trade publications and conference
proceedings were used for this study.<P>


<b>WHO SHOULD READ THIS REPORT</B><P>

This study is directed to the various strata of companies and institutions
interested in markets and new developments in this growing field. They are:<P>

<UL>     -   Companies involved in developing, manufacturing and
         supplying advanced materials<P>

     -   Companies involved in the development and manufacture of
         advanced composites<P>

     -   Suppliers of carbon fiber precursors<P>

     -   Producers and suppliers of carbon fibers<P>

     -   Chemical companies supplying epoxies and other materials for
         composites<P>
     -   Suppliers of carbon fiber processing equipment<P>

     -   O.E.M. suppliers<P>

     -   Government agencies involved in advanced materials<P>

     -   Prepreg manufacturers<P>

     -   Aircraft and aerospace manufacturers<P>

     -   Automotive manufacturers<P>

     -   Producers of sports and recreational equipment<P>

     -   Companies involved in the development and use of aerospace
         and defense-related materials<P>

     -   Venture capital companies and financial institutions interested in new attractive investments<P></UL>


<b>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

The following are related technical and economic analysis reports published by
BCC:<P>

<UL>1. GB-121 "High Performance Fibers," published July 1987.<BR>
2. GB-120 "Structural Carbon," published July 1989.</UL><P>

