<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-173: DIAMOND, DIAMOND-LIKE CARBON AND
CBN FILMS AND COATED PRODUCTS 
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-173: DIAMOND, DIAMOND-LIKE CARBON AND
CBN FILMS AND COATED PRODUCTS 
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Thomas Abraham
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Diamond possesses the greatest hardness and greatest thermal
conductivity among all known materials. Combined with these
important properties, diamond has very low thermal expansion and
high electrical resistance. Because of its hardness, diamond is far
more effective and efficient than other competing materials used
for abrasive, cutting, shaping or finishing tools. Its very high
thermal conductivity makes it ideal for spreading and conducting
the heat out of compact, high power, high speed electronic
packages. However, synthetic diamond has been produced by high
pressure and high temperature techniques.<P> 

In recent years, a low pressure technique to produce diamond using
chemical vapor deposition (CVD) has drawn worldwide attention.
There has been an explosion of interest in CVD diamond, diamond-
like and CBN films and coatings. These films are expected to be
used in a variety of applications from cutting tools to wear-
resistant parts, and from electronics to optical applications. One
advantage of CVD diamond technology over the high-pressure
technology is its low cost and its ability to coat any shapes.<P> 

CVD diamond has advantages in being incorporated in electronic
packages due to its extremely high thermal conductivity, coupled
with its excellent dielectric properties. Also, large substrates
are now available and a variety of package designs are possible
with CVD diamond. Tool inserts with CVD diamond thick-film blanks
or thin-film coatings constitute the newest tool material. Diamond
and diamond-like coatings are also finding increasing applications
in optical applications such as sunglasses, ophthalmic lenses and
IR windows.<P>
  

<b>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This BCC report has been prepared because a lot of new developments
have been taking place in the CVD diamond, diamond-like and CBN
thin films, and coated products. Some of the market segments have
achieved production scale while others are still in the testing and
prototype quantities. Secondly, there are several new potential
applications such as semiconductors, protective coatings and
advanced flat panel displays, which would revolutionize electronic
and consumer products. These have warranted a need for a proper
analysis of the technological and business issues, trends in
research, development and manufacturing, as well as the worldwide 
competition in the diamond film and coated products industry.  
This report has been prepared with the following objectives:<P>

<LI> To provide an overview of the various industrial diamond,
     diamond-like and CBN thin films and coated products, their
     production technologies and applications.<P>
  
<LI> To identify the technological and business issues related to
     the development and commercial production of diamond, diamond-
     like and CBN films and coated products.<P> 
  
<LI> To analyze the domestic and foreign competition among
     companies within diamond, diamond-like and CBN films, and
     their product market segments.<P>
  
<LI> To determine the current size and future growth of the U.S.
     and worldwide markets for diamond, diamond-like and CBN thin
     films and products.<P>
  
<LI> To identify and profile all U.S. producers and those involved
     in the development of diamond, diamond-like and CBN films and
     products.<P>
  
<LI> To identify the U.S. universities and institutions involved in
     diamond film, diamond-like and CBN film research.<P>
  
<LI> To identify the foreign companies, universities and other
     institutions involved in the diamond, diamond-like and CBN
     films and coated products.<P>
  

<b>CONTRIBUTION TO THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC's technical/economic study covers the technical and industry
overviews, materials, current and emerging production methods, new
developments, CVD diamond and processing techniques, business and
development issues, current and emerging applications and an
extensive market analysis. Current size and future growth of the
U.S. and worldwide markets are estimated for 1993 and 1998.<P> 


<b>FORMAT AND SCOPE</B><P>

The report provides a detailed technology overview for CVD diamond,
diamond-like and CBN thin and thick films, including their
production techniques, properties and applications. New
developments in the U.S. and outside the U.S. have been described
in detail for each of the material categories. Detailed patent
analyses have been carried out for each material. Finally, market
analyses have been provided for each of the application segments. 
The qualitative and quantitative judgments embodied in this report
are a valuable contribution to the current knowledge of CVD
diamond, diamond-like and CBN thin films and coated products, their
manufacturing technologies, applications and markets. Moreover,
this study has been conducted at a vital stage when their
applications are growing at tremendous strides.  With these new
developments, decisions may be made by a number of companies as to
their future strategies of involvement.<P>


<b>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The findings of this report are based on information derived from
interviews with almost all producers, potential producers and
suppliers of CVD diamond, diamond-like and CBN thin film materials
and their products. Several industry experts were also contacted
for this study. In addition, many end users were contacted to
evaluate the current and future demands for these materials. In
all, about 150 persons from 80 companies, universities and other
institutions were contacted for this study.<P>

Secondary data were obtained from the Industrial Diamond
Association of America; trade publications; technical journals; and
the U.S. Patent Database, NTIS and Dialog computer searches.<P>


<b>WHO SHOULD SUBSCRIBE?</B><P>

This report is directed to the various strata of companies that are
interested in the developments in this field, such as:<P>

<LI>  Companies involved in the development, manufacturing and
     supplying of advanced materials.<P>
  
<LI>  Developers and producers of diamond, diamond-like and CBN
     films and coatings.<P>
  
<LI> Manufacturers and suppliers of industrial diamond and CBN
     materials.<P>
  
<LI> Manufacturers and suppliers of diamond and CBN products.<P>
  
<LI> Manufacturers and suppliers of advanced ceramic materials and
     components.<P>
  
<LI>  Producers and suppliers of advanced electronic and optical
     components.<P>
  
<LI>  Producers and suppliers of machine tool inserts.<P>
  
<LI>  Producers of sunglasses, ophthalmic lenses, IR windows and
     other optical materials.<P>
  
<LI> Electronic, automotive, computer, aerospace and
     telecommunication companies.<P>
  
<LI> Advanced material companies interested in diversification.<P>


<b>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

The following are related BCC studies:<P>

<UL> GB-044--New Industrial Diamond and CBN Technology and 
     Materials, published December 1991.<P>

GB-135--Abrasives: Materials, Processing, Applications,
     Economics and Markets, published March 1991.<P>

GB-130--Chemical Vapor Deposition, published January 1990.<P>

GB-133--Physical Vapor Deposition, published April 1990.<P>

WTAP-02--High-Performance Diamond, an Analysis of the U.S. 
     Patents, published March 1991.<P></UL>

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
<H3>TABLE OF CONTENTS</H3></CENTER>
