<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>C-002U SPECIALTY WATER TREATMENT CHEMICALS: WHAT'S
AHEAD?</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-002U SPECIALTY WATER TREATMENT CHEMICALS: WHAT'S
AHEAD?</H2>
<HR><P>
<I>NORMA CORBITT/ANNA CRULL</I><BR>
REPORT ANALYSTS
<P>
<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</H3></I>
</CENTER> 

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B>

<P>The goals and objectives of this technical/marketing study are to illustrate the
complexity and dynamic nature of the U.S. specialty water treatment chemicals
industry, within the context of the marketplace.  This study seeks to ascertain how
this industry relates to and is influenced by government regulations, technology and
economic factors.  It also aims to provide the facts, figures, and statistics necessary to
evaluate and to make projections regarding this industry. </P>  


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B>

<P>This revised BCC technical/marketing study provides an in-depth analysis that
forecasts and tracks significant changes in the mature, yet still dynamic, U.S.
specialty water treatment chemicals industry.  The risks and rewards involved in
these economic, environmental, governmental, and technological changes determine
the difference between success or failure in this industry.</P> 


<B>HISTORY OF THE MARKET</B>

<P>Plagued by impure water for centuries, mankind has employed a variety of primitive
purification means to produce clean, potable water.  These means range from Moses
throwing a tree and Elisha throwing a cruse of salt into impure water sources to an
ancient Hindu filtration recipe that involves boiling foul water in copper pots and
filtering it through charcoal.  As early as 1450 B.C., the Egyptians are reported to
have used siphons to draw clear water from settling tanks.  The Chinese are credited
with the discovery that the addition of aluminum sulfate to contaminated water
coagulates the turbidity and increases the settled water's potability.  An extensive
waterworks network employed by the Roman Empire is said to have included the
first reliable meters, the extensive use of settling tanks, and the separation of potable
water, heated process water, sewage, and storm runoff.</P>  

<P>The U.S. water treatment chemicals industry has its roots in the desire to produce a
clean, disease-free supply of potable water for municipal consumers.  Within 20 years
of the British Parliament requiring the City of London to use sand filters for
removing bacteria and other impurities from its water, Poughkeepsie, NY was
installing them.  By 1912, liquid chlorine was being applied to U.S. municipal water
systems to destroy disease-producing bacteria.</P>

<P>Since that time, the U.S. water treatment industry has now evolved into the design of
facilities for the conveyance, control and treatment of industrial waters.  This
evolvement comes in response to an altered federal environmental policy and a
shifting of national industrial priorities.  From that response comes the trend toward
waste minimization and water recycling/reuse.  This evolvement has also seen the
creation of the government water expert, who (in theory) balances the public's need
for a reliable supply of potable water with industry's need to operate in a safe,
ultimately profitable manner.</P>  

<P>Over the last 25 years, the U.S. water treatment chemicals industry has also
segmented into commodity and specialty chemicals, with the basis of the
segmentation being how the individual chemical or chemical formulation is sold. 
Specialty chemicals remains the most competitive and fastest growing segment, due
to the development of new polymer technologies that enhance water/solids separation
and higher-priced products that replace chlorine, chromates, and hydrazine. </P> 


<B>SCOPE OF THE REPORT</B>

<P>Water treatment touches nearly every individual or industry in one way or another,
as the water treatment industry seeks to bring impure water up to potable standards
or better.  As this extremely large industry continues to expand, the lines between
commodity and specialty chemicals and mechanical and other treatment methods
sometimes blurs.</P> 

<P>This report concentrates on the most competitive, high-growth segment of the water
treatment industry:  those chemicals sold by specialty suppliers.  Using information
gathered from diverse sources, this report has been organized into a cohesive unit
that includes an overview of the industry with relevant information on the
environmental and regulatory constraints and actions that greatly control this
industry.  This report addresses the structure of the industry and its competitive
aspects, as well as specialty water treatment chemicals by function and market
application.  Abstracted patents represent many of the research and development
trends in the industry.  Not all of these patents become commercialized; however,
they do illustrate areas of company activity and alternative technologies under
development.</P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>The methodologies employed in this study include extensive library research and
information from BCC internal files, as well as contact with representatives from the
leading water treatment chemicals companies.  This report also ilcludes an on-line
data search of databases that cover all existing literature and an evaluation of
government statistics, company activities, state-of-the-art technology, and patents. 
Since it revises, expands, and updates an older BCC report, the report contains some
historical and background information from the older report.  This information
conforms to the newer BCC format and the more focused objectives of this report.</P>

<P>Values reflect U.S. sales of specialty water treatment chemicals for the market
applications covered in this report.  Projections for the 1995-2000 time period are
given in 1995 constant dollars and represent real growth.  Where precise information
was not available, a consensus was made, using a formulation of reasonable
assumptions and estimates based on a baseline obtained from historical data.</P>

      
<B>VALUE OF THE REPORT</B>

<P>This report consolidates a range of legislative/industrial/technical information into a
comprehensive technical/marketing study.  This study should aid technical personnel
in the research and development of water treatment chemicals, as well as suppliers to
any of the application market applications and readers interested in discovering and
exploiting current or projected market sub-niches.  Senior marketing, venture
capitalists, executive planners, government officials, and environmentalists should
find this report of interest.  As for the novice reader who desires to understand how
regulation, market pressures, and technology interact in the water treatment
chemicals industry, this report should be a key source.</P>


