<I>ANNA CRULL
</I><BR>
PROJECT MANAGER
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>GOALS AND OBJECTIVES OF THE REPORT</B><P>


Flame Retardant Chemicals presents a detailed view of market size, growth, and
trends for this industry.  The major product lines and applications are
identified and the market size for each product line and application is
estimated for the next five years. Significant technological trends and
developments in materials and applications are identified and analyzed.
International aspects of the flame retardant chemical market are discussed,
and the structure of the industry is addressed, including profiles of the
major flame retardant chemicals suppliers.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE REPORT</B><P>

The flame retardant chemicals industry has historically been driven by
regulations and standards.  The normal fire-, smoke-, and toxicity-related
standards have been joined by environmental standards caused by the alleged
environmental impact of halogens and the alleged toxicity of antimony.
Although suitable replacements have not been found for these materials in all
cases, the environmental concern has served to depress their growth levels
from what it would otherwise have been and/or channel the growth into
alternative chemical products.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE REPORT AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

Flame Retardant Chemicals provides in-depth information and state-of-the art
technological evaluations for decision making by those involved in, or
considering becoming involved in, the supply of flame retardant chemicals to
the plastics, textiles, wood/paper paint, and paint/coatings industries.  The
study can assist clients in strategic planning, acquisition analysis,
technology analysis, commercial development of new products, and analysis of
competitors' strategies, strengths, weaknesses, pricing, market share, and
profitability.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT OF THE REPORT</B><P>

This report analyzes the products, applications, technology, international
aspects, industry structure, and profiles of key companies/organizations
involved in the supply of flame retardant chemicals to the plastics, textiles,
wood/paper paint, and paint/coatings industries.

The format of this report is to state all values, projections, and forecasts
in terms of constant dollars unless otherwise noted.  All numbers and
projections are substantiated or noted as to their origin.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The background research of Flame Retardant Chemicals consisted of a thorough
analysis of trade, government, and company literature, and the extensive
information in BCC's database.  An extensive series of personal and telephone
interviews with key executives and officials in the industries, trade
associations, and government followed the background work.  The expert and
reasoned comments of these people, combined with BCC experience and analysis,
provide the basis for the content of this report.<P>

This report summarizes the changes which have occurred in the flame retardant
chemicals industry since the March 1990 BCC report.  The consumption and
market size for phosphorus-based flame retardant chemicals contained in this
report are markedly different than those contained in the 1990 report.  The
difference is due to a change in the method of computing the consumption of
phosphorus used in the U.S., from which the amount of phosphorus used in flame
retardant chemicals was derived. This new BCC report reflects the consumption
of phosphorus (atomic weight 31).  The previous report considered the
consumption of phosphorus in its many molecular forms, including P2O5 and PO4.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Major sources of information are noted throughout the report and in Appendix A
(Works Cited).<P>


<B>BCC CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The author of this report has worked on many assignments dealing with the
supply of technologically advanced materials to industry, and has analytical
familiarity with many of the important issues influencing the supply of flame
retardant chemicals to the plastics, textiles, wood/paper paint, and
paint/coatings industries.<P>

Related BCC reports include:<P>


<UL>PatTap-03R, Patent Technology Review: Flame Retardant Chemicals and
     Compositions<P>


     P-031N, Fillers and Extenders for Plastics<P><P>

     C-0094, Structural and Specialty Adhesives<P>

     Z6P-064N, Plastics in Electronic Equipment Enclosures<P>

     QP-128, Tough Plastics</UL><P>

BCC also publishes a monthly newsletter, Flame Retardancy News.<P>

Each year BCC conducts an Annual Conference on Flame Retardancy: Recent
Advances in Flame Retardancy of Polymeric Materials.  Proceedings from each of
the previous four conferences are available.<P>

