<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-009X  STRUCTURAL AND SPECIALTY ADHESIVES:
ADHESIVES: MARKETS, TRENDS AND PROSPECTS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-009X  STRUCTURAL AND SPECIALTY ADHESIVES:
ADHESIVES: MARKETS, TRENDS AND PROSPECTS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Norma Corbitt</I><BR>
Project Analyst
<P>

<I>Anna Crull</I><BR>
Project Manager
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This technical/marketing study is an in-depth analysis which
forecasts and tracks significant changes in the
specialty/structural adhesives industry.  This highly fragmented
industry caters to dynamic end-use markets in which customer
demands quickly change.  Even when an end-use market levels off,
niche markets appear that aid adhesive growth.<P>

This report seeks to assess the current status and future
outlook for the specialty/structural adhesives industry.
Specifically of interest are the competitive aspects of the
industry.  Merger and acquisition activity has been brisk.
Companies are restructuring in order to maintain a competitive
edge in domestic as well as international markets.<P>

Sophisticated products and processes continue to affect
traditional means of fastening.  High-tech markets are demanding
new chemistries and high levels of consistency and performance
from specialty/structural adhesives.  With the advent of high
performance engineering plastics, adhesives are increasingly
required to perform well under extreme temperatures, while
maintaining bonding strength and physical and chemical
properties.<P>

The specialty/structural adhesives industry has not escaped the
myriad of environmental regulations written over the last
decade.  Like the chemical industry in general, the adhesives
sector is developing technology that meets or exceeds
governmental regulations.  New products are being developed that
anticipate any possible future hazards.  Methodology that allows
for any adjustments to meet future environmental demands is
being established at a product's inception.<P>

<B>HISTORY OF THE MARKET</B><P>

Great strides have been made in the specialty/structural
adhesives industry since primitive man first used natural resins
and pitch to affix spearheads to shafts.  Adhesive systems have
advanced since the first glue was developed by Elijah Upton in
1808.  The development of synthetic resins in the 1930s was to
bring changes in the specialty/structural adhesives industry
during World War II.<P>

These synthetic resins were necessary alternatives to the
natural rubber solutions that had been used for adhesion since
the 1700s.  Bonding technology advanced rapidly as the nation
switched to synthetic adhesives.  By 1943, the high frequency
heating of glue lines was commercialized.  Synthetic adhesives
were used to bond paper, ceramics, glass, textiles, rubbers and
plastics.  Adhesives were developed with higher strength and
greater durability than animal- and plant-derived glues.<P>

Later, space exploration, which required lightweight components
and airtight bonding, lent a boost to the bonding of metal
substrates.  Structural adhesives began in the early honeycomb
bonding programs associated with the first of the solid fuel
rockets developed at Redstone Arsenal.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This report quantifies and qualifies market information on
specialty and structural adhesives for the U.S. market.  Both
opportunities and pitfalls of the industry are explored, as are
the impact they may have on the industry.  Specific market
segments that are representative of the industry as a whole are
discussed.  This report targets only specialty/structural
adhesives.  Excluded are those used for packaging and common
consumer glues.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This study is divided into key chapters dealing with the
environmental impact on, the markets for and the resin systems
of specialty/structural adhesives.  This report is limited to an
analysis of the specialty/structural segment of adhesives only
and does not include the adhesives industry in general. Emphasis
is given to the latest market information on product
development.<P>

Much of the information for this technical/marketing report was
gathered through telephone conversations with industry,
government and academic experts in the field.  The balance of
the information was gathered from available government, trade
and technical publications.  An on-line data search was made of
data bases to retrieve information and cover all of the existing
literature.<P>

Projections are in terms of constant dollars.  Historical values
are for the year given.  The specific geographical area covered
is the U.S.  Predictions are for the 1990-1995 time period.<P>


<B>VALUE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This comprehensive technical/marketing study will be valuable to
senior marketing and planning executives.  Technical personnel
engaged in research and development, together with marketing and
business managers involved in the formulation of
specialty/structural adhesives will find this report of value.
Leading industry authorities will discover the latest
developments in products, competition and technology.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

BCC, Inc. has a number of related technical/marketing reports
that may be of interest to the specialty/structural adhesives
industry.  Below is a sampling of the many reports that are
available:<P>

<PRE>
    C-004U    Flame Retardant Chemicals
    C-020B    Antioxidants
