<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-012N  WATER SOLUBLE POLYMERS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-012N  WATER SOLUBLE POLYMERS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DONALD SAXMAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Depending on how they are defined, water soluble polymers (WSPs)
represent a 5.0 billion pound, $2.9 billion dollar market.  It is
a rare industry that does not rely on WSPs during some stage of the
production process.  WSPs have always been important (water-based
animal glues and food binders can be traced to prehistoric times).
During the Seventies, increased environmental concern and the
realization that inexpensive petroleum-based products were gone
forever sparked new interest in WSPs.  Processors have realized
that water-based formulations can measure up to petroleum-based
formulations in cost, performance, and especially environmental
acceptability.  Despite recessionary industrial activity levels,
and slowed construction activity, WSPs have consistently performed
better than many other commodities, specialty chemicals, polymers,
or agricultural derivatives.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Now, in the 1990s, natural, synthetic, and semi-synthetic WSPs are
continuing to compete with each other for market position in this
expanded market.  A better understanding of WSP chemical
structures, improved microbial fermentation technology, more
efficient production processes, and the development of formulations
approved for human consumption have helped maintain an active WSP
market.  Developments in degradable products, enhanced oil
recovery, processed foods, wastewater flocculants, cleaning
formulations, pulp and paper sizings, and water-based inks have the
potential for creating new WSP markets.  This BCC Business
Opportunity Report addresses the potential of these markets.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report should be a basic market reference and technology
summary for the farmers, miners, chemical processors, importers,
and manufacturers who deal in, or are considering dealing in the
water soluble chemical market.  Highly competitive chemical
suppliers should find the report particularly useful.  WSP
consumers, from whatever consuming or producing market sector, can
identify existing and developing chemical alternatives.  Designers
and process engineers can track the performance of the WSPs useful
for a specific application.  Finally, producers and suppliers of
competing materials are provided with a valuable outline of what
WSPs can and can't do.  The report author wishes to thank all of
the manufacturers and WSP consumers who cooperated in the
preparation of this report.<P>

<B>SCOPE & FORMAT</B><P>

This report divides the WSP industry in two ways: by consumer
(markets) and by producer (WSP chemicals).Water soluble polymers
represent a diverse and varied group of agricultural and industrial
chemicals.  Nearly every industrial sector uses WSPs during some
phase of its operation.  Unfortunately, this has discouraged a
unified, coherent set of nomenclature.  Indeed, substances
identified as water soluble polymers by one industrial sector may
not be considered water soluble polymers by a different sector.
WSPs can be classified by derivation, chemical structures, and
application.  They are derived from natural sources (gums,
proteins, celluloses, starches, etc.), from wholly synthetic
sources (polyvinyls, polyacrylates, polyimines, petroleum
sulfonates, etc.), and semi-synthetic sources formed by modifying
natural materials to produce forms with more desirable properties.
This report adopts a classification scheme based on marketing
considerations.  A material will be considered a water soluble
polymer if: 1) it contains at least 10 monomer units in the polymer
chain, 2) it forms an aqueous solution under commonly encountered
industrial conditions, and 3) it is recognized or marketed as a
water soluble polymer for a given application by a specific
consuming market sector.  The total WSP market has been further
divided into nine sectors: gums, biopolymers, proteins, starches,
celluloses, polyvinyls, polyacrylics, polyimines, and surface
active WSPs.<P>

This report divides the market for water soluble polymers into nine
consuming sectors: adhesives, pulp and paper, textiles, foods,
drugs and cosmetics, the oilfield, paints and coatings, water
treatment, degradable products, plus a miscellaneous category.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This Business Opportunity Report is intended to be the most
complete technical, economic and business document of this type on
this subject and is designed to provide information of a
professional nature.  The technical data are dependent on the
accuracy of the manufacturers and technical sources that helped
make up the BCC database.  This report is not intended to
constitute a legal or accounting document, nor is it an endorsement
of any given product or process.  The author, and BCC Inc., as the
publisher, assume no liability for loss or damage as a result of
reliance on this material.<P>

Historic growth, value, and price data are expressed in current
dollars.  All values represent wholesale level prices unless
otherwise mentioned.  All predictions are expressed in constant
1990 dollars.  Predictions for the periods 1990-1995 and 1995-2000
are based on a synthesis of the BCC database.  Growth rates are
average annual growth rates for those periods. Totals are rounded
to the nearest million.  When appropriate, information from
previously published sources is identified to allow a more detailed
examination by clients.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

This report is based on a literature review, patent examination,
discussions with commercial and government sources, and an analysis
of raw material sources and markets.  This BCC Business Opportunity
Report represents a complete revision, expansion, and update of our
1985 report, C-012R Water-Based Polymers: Markets, Technologies,
Developments.  Since then, the market has altered significantly.
An entirely new data base has been prepared, drawing from
correspondence and contact with WSP suppliers, consumers, trade
journals, technical articles, government statistics, and
industry-sponsored conferences.  The report project supervisor has
authored several related BCC Business Opportunity Reports,
including analyses of the oilfield chemicals, enhanced oil
recovery, water treatment chemicals, environmental management, and
corrosion inhibitor markets.  BCC's monthly technical newsletters
on enhanced oil recovery, applied genetics engineering, and
membrane separations also provide a unique source of important
background material.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The report's project analyst, Donald Saxman, writes and edits three
monthly BCC newsletters.  Mr. Saxman has twelve years' experience
in market analysis, technical writing and newsletter editing.<P>


