<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-020AR  CORROSION INHIBITORS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-020AR  CORROSION INHIBITORS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DONALD SAXMAN
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Depending on who compiles the figures, corrosion costs the
national economy between $10 and $30 billion per year.  Sixteen
billion is a good representative figure for the cost of
potentially preventable corrosion.  Corrosion can be reduced by
using inherently corrosion resistant materials (special alloys,
plastic resins, etc.), by coating corrodible materials (with
films, paints, mastics or coatings), or through cathodic
protection and sacrificial anodes.  In many cases, the most cost
effective way to control corrosion is through the use of
corrosion inhibitors.   Corrosion inhibitors are consumed by the
water treatment industry, the oilfield/petrochemical industry,
and the manufacturing industry.  This report analyses the
corrosion inhibitor market in terms of both producers and
consumers.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Despite level per capita water consumption, a collapse of the
oilfield chemical market, recessionary industrial activity
levels, and competition from inherently non-corrosive materials,
the corrosion inhibitor industry has survived.  The corrosion
inhibitor market consists of bulk commodity chemicals, specialty
chemicals, and highly proprietary formulations.  A variety of new
products are vying for a position in the competitive corrosion
inhibitor marketplace.  Several historically important inhibitors
are associated with environmental problems.  When these chemicals
will be replaced, by what, and at what cost, are questions being
asked by producer and consumer alike. This BCC Business
Opportunity Report, latest in a series, identifies the technology
involved, reviews the market, and forecasts future corrosion
inhibitor consumption.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This Business Opportunity Report should be a basic market
reference and technology summary for the miners, chemical
processors, and manufacturers who are involved in, or are
considering becoming involved in the corrosion inhibitor market.
Highly competitive chemical suppliers should find the report
particularly useful.  Corrosion inhibitor consumers, from
whatever consuming or producing market sector, can identify
existing and developing chemical alternatives.  Designers and
process engineers can track the performance of the corrosion
inhibitors useful for a specific application.  Finally, producers
and suppliers of competing materials are provided with a valuable
outline of what corrosion inhibitors can and can't do.  The
report author wishes to thank all of the corrosion inhibitor
producers and consumers who cooperated in the preparation of this
report.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This Business Opportunity Report organizes the corrosion
inhibitor industry in two ways: by consumer (markets) and by
producer (corrosion inhibitor chemicals).<P>

Corrosion inhibitor chemicals include bulk commodity inorganics
and organics, their byproducts and derivatives, specialty
inorganics and organics, and a variety of proprietary mixtures
and custom designed formulations.  For the purposes of this
report, corrosion inhibitors are organized according to chemical
structure.  Groups tracked include:<P>

<UL>Chromium-containing<BR>
Phosphorus-containing<BR>
Miscellaneous inorganic<BR>
Nitrogen-containing organic<BR>
Non-nitrogen-containing organic</UL><P>

Chemistry, applications, and sources and suppliers of specific
chemical compounds within these groups are provided.<P>

This report tracks the following corrosion inhibitor consuming
market sectors:<P>

<UL>Potable water<BR>
Steam generators and boilers<BR>
Recirculating water and cooling towers<BR>
The oilfield<BR>
Pipelines and storage tanks<BR>
Petrochemical refineries</UL><P>

A number of minor markets, including hydraulic fluids and
lubricants, metal preparation, cleaning, coolants, and machining
fluids, and concrete inhibiting markets are also discussed.<P>

A series of market sector case studies provide graphic examples of
specific corrosion inhibitor applications.  A series of formulation
examples, provided by corrosion inhibitor producers or consumers,
exemplify mixing techniques, application processes, and special
handling requirements.  This material is provided as an example,
for information purposes only.  Corrosion inhibitor company
profiles are also provided.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This Business Opportunity Report is intended to be the most
complete technical, economic and business document of this type on
this subject and is designed to provide information of a
professional nature.  The technical data are dependent on the
accuracy of the manufacturers and technical sources that helped
make up the BCC database.  This report is not intended to
constitute a legal or accounting document, nor is it an endorsement
of any given product or process.  The authors, and BCC Inc., as the
publisher, assume no liability for loss or damage as a result of
reliance on  this material.<P>

Historic growth, value, and price data are expressed in current
dollars.  All values represent wholesale level prices unless
otherwise mentioned.  All predictions are expressed in constant
1992 dollars.  Predictions for the period 1992-1997 are based on a
synthesis of the BCC database.  Growth rates are average annual
growth rates for those periods. Totals are rounded to the nearest
million.  When appropriate, information from previously published
sources is identified to allow a more detailed examination by
clients.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

This report is based on a literature review, patent examination,
discussions with commercial and government sources, and an analysis
of raw material sources and markets.  This BCC Business Opportunity
Report represents a complete revision, expansion, and update of the
company's 1984 report, C-020A Corrosion Inhibitors: A Technical-
Economic Market Analysis.  Since then, the market has altered
significantly.  An entirely new data base has been prepared,
drawing from correspondence and contact with corrosion inhibitor
suppliers, consumers, trade journals, technical articles,
government statistics, and industry-sponsored conferences.  The
report project supervisor has authored several related BCC Business
Opportunity Reports, including analyses of the oilfield chemical,
enhanced oil recovery, water treatment chemicals, environmental
management, and water soluble polymer markets.  BCC's monthly
technical newsletters on enhanced oil recovery and waste treatment
technology have also provided a unique source of background
material.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The report's project analyst is Donald Saxman, BCC newsletter
editor and technical market analyst.  Mr. Saxman has 13
years' experience in market analysis, technical writing and
newsletter editing.  Since 1983, he has operated as a full-time
technical market consultant and subcontractor to BCC.  During this
period, duties included editing Enhanced Energy Recovery News and
was a member of the founding team of Waste Treatment Technology
News which he edited.  He has prepared over twenty BCC Business
Opportunity Reports, including earlier corrosion inhibitor reports.
Other activities include confidential single-client
market/technical analyses, ad copy design, and single-client
monthly briefings.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC PUBLICATIONS</B><P>

<UL>C 014R: Enhanced Oil Recovery, by Donald Saxman<P>

C 048: Oil and Gas Field Chemicals, by Donald Saxman<P>

C 091: Industrial Fluids, by Kurt Miska<P>

 "Enhanced Energy Recovery News," monthly newsletter, edited by
Diana Mulloy, managing editor Anna Crull<P>

"Waste Treatment Technology News," monthly newsletter, edited by
Norma Corbitt, managing editor Anna Crull<P></UL>

