<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-020BR ANTIOXIDANTS: MARKETS, MATERIALS, TRENDS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-020BR ANTIOXIDANTS: MARKETS, MATERIALS, TRENDS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ERIKA SMITH</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>
<I>ANNA CRULL</I><BR>
PROJECT DIRECTOR
<P>
<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Antioxidants are compounds which reduce the rate of oxidation in
auto-oxidizable organic materials, thus preventing their
deterioration.  Antioxidants find applications in plastics, rubber
and elastomers, foods, fuels and other functional fluids,
agricultural feeds, and cosmetics.  The types of antioxidants used
in a particular market subsector are fairly well-established.
Restrictions in application are generally limited to cost,
effectiveness, stability within a given system, and the
minimization of undesirable effects such as discoloration in
plastics.  Additional regulations governing health and safety exist
within the food and agricultural markets and, to a lesser extent,
in cosmetics.<P>

Controversy exists.  Within the food antioxidant market, specific
chemicals such as BHT, BHA, sodium nitrate, and sodium nitrite have
been implicated as causes of cancer.  Sulfites have been
responsible for significant allergic reactions in some members of
the population.  These effects, prompting concern from government
and private agencies, provide areas of growth for new or
alternative antioxidants, or for other methods of preservation.
However, some of the alternatives, for instance food irradiation,
are as, or even more, controversial than the use of antioxidants.
Thus, despite some hesitancies, antioxidants will continue to play
a vital role in various industries, warranting an analysis of the
market.<P>

<B>OBJECTIVES OF THE REPORT</B><P>

The objectives of this report are to provide an overview of the
different classes of antioxidants, their relative importance and
share in the overall antioxidant market, and estimates of their
future potential growth.  Important to this evaluation is a
concomitant analysis of the trends in those industries in which
antioxidants are employed.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

The information in this report may be of interest to those
manufacturers, suppliers, and investors already involved in the
antioxidant business or those considering a venture into this area.
Any company marketing antioxidants to the food and agricultural
sectors will find the legislative and standards guidelines helpful.
This report hopes to emphasize the necessity of antioxidants in
vital market sectors and the important role that they play in
protecting and preserving plastics, food, rubber, functional
fluids, and related products.<P>



<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This report classifies antioxidants into six categories based upon
their chemical structure and/or functionality:  1) hindered
phenolics, 2) nitrogen compounds, 3) acids and their derivatives,
4) sulfur compounds, 5) phosphorous compounds, and 6) miscellaneous
compounds with unique modes of operation, such as chelating agents
and biological antioxidants.<P>

The antioxidants are then analyzed according to the market
subsectors in which they are used.  The areas treated in this
report are plastics, rubber and elastomers, food, functional
fluids, and "others" (agriculture, cosmetics, etc.).<P>

Values given refer to the manufacturers' sales in current dollars.
Projections are provided through the year 2001 and are given in
constant dollars.  Projections are a summation of market forces,
technology, and regulatory factors.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The information in this report was gathered from interviews with
antioxidant manufacturers, product literature, periodical reviews,
and government documents and publications.  A patent search was
conducted.  The full text of U.S. patents is available from the
U.S. Patent Office.  All estimates are made by BCC unless otherwise
specified.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

The following reports are of related interest to the study on
antioxidants:<BR>

<PRE>
    C-020PR  Corrosion Inhibitors
    GA-056   The Changing Sterilization Picture
