C-069R CHEMICALS FOR COSMETICS AND TOILETRIES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-069R CHEMICALS FOR COSMETICS AND TOILETRIES
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>NORMA CORBITT</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>
<I>ANNA CRULL
</I><BR>
PROJECT DIRECTOR
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This industry research\technical market study has been prepared as an in-depth
analysis to forecast and track significant changes in the chemicals for
finished cosmetic and toiletry products in the U.S.  While the basic types of
these finished products have remained largely the same, many of the chemicals
used as fillers, solvents and active ingredients have changed due to recent
developments in biochemical processing methods. Despite the maturity of the
cosmetic and toiletries market, a dynamic of change in chemical formulation
continues to evolve from advances made in specialty chemicals and the need of
chemical producers to accommodate the greater diversity found in all finished
cosmetic and toiletry products.<P>


<B>HISTORY OF THE MARKET</B><P>

Throughout the ages, people have used cosmetics and toiletries to enhance
their personal appeal.  The tombs of Egyptian kings dating as far back as 3500
B.C. contain evidence of perfumed hair oils and beautiful box chests in which
cosmetics were kept.  Both upper-class Egyptian men and women darkened their
eyelids with black and green pigments, while the women also rouged their lips
and cheeks and stained their hair with henna. Cold cream originated in Roman
times, reportedly circa 200 A.D.  Both ladies and gentlemen of 17th and 18th century Europe used cosmetics lavishly.<P>

Today, the ancient impulse to improve one's appearance with cosmetics is
getting help from modern specialty chemicals and science.  Cosmetics are
becoming a highly technical business, with the growth of products which are
supposed to act like pharmaceuticals revolutionizing the business and
enhancing the demand for certain natural chemicals, such as alpha hydroxy,
hyaluronic and amino acids, and proteins, such as collagen.  The high rate of
growth in sales of sunscreen products or cosmetics containing them also
continues to effect change.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This BCC study evaluates the contribution of specialty chemicals to the
finished cosmetic and toiletry products industry.  In turn, it offers a
comprehensive review of basic developments in the cosmetics industry and any
resulting effects on the markets for cosmetic chemicals.  Although the focus
of this report is U.S. manufacturers' sales of cosmetic chemical ingredients,
due to the global nature of both the finished cosmetic products and cosmetic
chemical ingredients markets, recent international patents that could affect
U.S. markets are mentioned.  Besides an overview, the report also includes an
in-depth evaluation of the structure of the cosmetic chemicals industry and
its competitive aspects.<P>

Significant space and discussion are given to the five major finished cosmetic
and toiletry product categories.  Current manufacturers' sales of these items
are discussed, with each category's respective growth rates, market values and
the value of the chemicals each uses given.  This section is intended to link
changes in the demand for finished cosmetic and toiletry products with
resulting changes in demand for the chemical ingredients from which they are
formulated.<P>

The final section reviews the major types of chemical ingredients.  The
present and likely future markets for these ingredients are analyzed, along
with their application to cosmetic formulations and trends affecting demand
for particular types of chemicals.  Estimates are given on significant usage
trends and growth rates.  These estimates take into account economics,
consumer preferences, demographic trends, product properties, competition and
government regulations.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Much of the information for this technical/marketing report has been gathered
through telephone interviews with industry partici- pants, including producers
of both cosmetic chemicals and finished cosmetic and toiletry products.  The
balance of the information comes from data obtained from available government,
trade and technical publications, as well as an evaluation of company
activities and patents.<P>

The value of U.S. manufacturers' sales for finished cosmetic and toiletry
products and for cosmetic ingredients are projected for the 1993-98 time
period.  The projections are given in 1993 constant dollars and cover the U.S.
geographic area.  The average annual growth rates conform to the convention
for significant figures.  Where precise information was not forthcoming, a
consensus was made, using a formulation of reasonable assumptions and
estimates based on a baseline obtained from historical data.<P>


<B>VALUE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This comprehensive technical/marketing report study will be of value to
technical personnel involved in the research and development of cosmetic
chemical ingredients, and manufacturers of finished cosmetic and toiletry
products.  Senior marketing, venture and planning executives, who must meet
federal standards on purity, will also benefit from this report.<P>




<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Current information can be found in the following related BCC reports:<P>

