<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-119 THE AGRICULTURAL CHEMICAL INDUSTRY: REGULATIONS,
TECHNOLOGY,ECONOMIC CHANGE AND NEW PROFIT OPPORTUNITIES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-119 THE AGRICULTURAL CHEMICAL INDUSTRY: REGULATIONS,
TECHNOLOGY,ECONOMIC CHANGE AND NEW PROFIT OPPORTUNITIES</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Heber Boulard</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The study is designed to inform those with a stake in the
agricultural chemical and related industries about:<P>

1.   Important trends in domestic consumption, production, and
     prices of fertilizers and pesticides;<P>

2.   Major shifts in worldwide fertilizers and pesticides trade;<P>

3.   How the industry is structured, and how it is  rapidly
     changing; and<P>

4.   Opportunities for profiting from these trends and
     changes.<P>

It also provides information on forces influencing market trends
and industry structural changes such as:<P>

a)   Technology -- including the movement toward Low Input
     Sustainable Agriculture (LISA) and the role of competing
     methods of controlling pests and adding plant nutrients, e.g.,
     biotechnology and physical methods such as bug vacuums and
     infrared weed control;<P>

b)   Regulations -- such as the 1990 Farm Bill, the 1990 Clean Air
     Act, and various state laws;<P>

     Economics -- including the impact of rising oil prices and
     diminishing returns to farmers for additional inputs.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR THE STUDY</B><P>

Firstly, there is a growing public concern about potential dangers
of agricultural chemicals.  Unless when preempted by other crisis
messages like these are frequently on the nightly TV news, radio
commentary shows and newspaper headlines:<P>

     Nitrate from fertilizer contaminating public drinking
     water;<P>

     Pesticides detected in the ground water of 26 states;<P>

     Farm workers exposed to herbicides have six times the risks of
     non-Hodgkin lymphomas;<P>

     Cancer-producing, allergy-causing, immune system-alterizng
     pesticide residues found in food supply.<P>

Even though voters turned down most environmental ballot
initiatives during the November 1990 election, governments -
federal, state, and local - will still be under pressure to
legislate more restrictions and controls over agricultural
chemicals.<P>

Secondly, there is an expanding development of new technology and
farming practices that have the potential of changing the demand
for agricultural chemicals.  For example, Low Input Sustainable
Agriculture (LISA), practices are designed to reduce the
application of chemicals.  To what extent will farmers implement
LISA and to what extent will other new competing technologies be
adopted?<P>

Thirdly, both fertilizer and pesticides are sensitive to energy
prices, and recent rising and fluctuating oil prices, along with
other economic forces, will impact on the industry.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report will be valuable to a wide variety of people interested
in or involved with the agricultural chemical industry.  The report
is designed to:<P>

     Help investors and lenders evaluate where the industry is
     going, and who the potential losers and winners may be;<P>

     Provide chemical producers with information useful in
     strategic planning and forecasting;<P>

     Help chemical brokers, distributors and farm cooperatives plan
     storage and distribution systems;<P>

     Assist industry trade associations evaluate the impact of
     environmental lobby groups;<P>

     Assist government policy makers design and evaluate chemical
     regulatory and price support programs;<P>

     Help farmers learn about new farming practices and trends.<P>

Overall, it should provide necessary facts and highlight issues to
help businesses and other people make better decisions.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

Primarily this study covers fertilizers and pesticides used in crop
production.  To a lesser degree, it covers plant growth regulators
and miscellaneous agricultural chemicals.  It does not cover post
harvest crop, livestock, or dairy chemicals.<P>

Following this introductory chapter is Chapter II, an executive
summary highlighting the findings followed by:<P>

     Chapter III    An overview of the fertilizer and pesticide
                    sectors;<P>

     Chapter IV     Forecasts of domestic consumption, production,
                    and prices of fertilizers and pesticides;<P>

     Chapter V      Details of the industry structure, the major
                    firms, and what they are doing;<P>

     Chapter VI     Description of the 1990 Farm Bill, the
                    California initiatives and many other federal
                    and state regulations impacting on the
                    industry.<P>

     Chapter VII    Discussion of alternative agricultural
                    practices and new research on biotechnology,
                    more benign chemicals and more efficient
                    equipment for applying agricultural chemicals.<P>

     Chapter VIII   Analysis of the economic forces that influence
                    the supply and demand for agricultural
                    chemicals.<P>

     Chapter IX     Trends in agricultural chemical exports and
                    imports, and what is happening on the
                    international front.<P>

     References     Lists of more than 150 references: books,
                    articles, reports, etc.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This research is based on a review of the literature, a survey of
knowledgeable people, and collection and analysis of statistics -
the various sources listed in the next section.  A survey was made
of experts in 12 major agricultural producing states that consume
more than 50 per cent of the agricultural chemicals in this
country.  The experts include more than 40 county agricultural
extension agents, 20 state agricultural economists or other
specialists, and 20 specialists at the national levels from such
organizations as USDA, TVA, various think tanks, trade
associations, congressional staff, and environmental groups.  In
addition, some time series and limited regression analysis were
used.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The following are the major published data sources:<P>

     DOMESTIC MARKET TRENDS<P>

          USDA's Agricultural Resources<P>

          TVA's various publications on fertilizers
          EPA's Pesticide Industry Sales and Usage
          NACA's Industry Profile Survey
          International Trade Commission Synthetic Organic
          Chemicals<P>

     WORLDWIDE TRADE<P>

          FAPRI, 1990 World Agricultural Outlook
          U.S. Department of Commerce's import and export data
          FAO publications on trade<P>

     INDUSTRY STRUCTURE<P>

          Annual reports of major firms
          Wards' Business Directory
          Dun's Business Directory<P>

In addition, more than a hundred articles or reports were reviewed.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK AND CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Since 1971 Business Communications Company, Inc., (BCC), has
provided important technical and economic studies that address
vital concerns in marketing and strategic planning.  BCC has
specialized in the areas of chemicals, foods, energy, and
materials.  Heber Bouland, the project analyst, has a Bachelors
Degree in Agricultural Engineering and a Masters Degree in
Engineering Administration.  He worked nine years at USDA in
agricultural marketing research, and thirteen years at the U.S.
General Accounting Office in evaluating agricultural and related
programs and policies.<P>

Related BCC studies include:<P>

     Biotechnology in Agriculture:  New Technologies, Product
     Development, Markets, GA-051R, Nov. '85.<P>

     Biotechnology in Plant And Animal Agriculture, (Conference
     report), Stamford, CT., April 12 & 13, 1985.<P>



