<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-125  MOLD RELEASE AGENTS </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> C-125  MOLD RELEASE AGENTS </H2>

<HR><P> 


<I>KEVIN SWIFT</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goal of this report is to provide what we believe to be the
first detailed and comprehensive "multi-client" study ever of mold
release agents and their commerical potential.  The objectives
include a thorough coverage of the underlying technological and
environmental issues of the evolving mold release business, as well
as assessments of new and potential products.  Another important
objective is to provide realistic market data and forecasts on mold
release products and the end-use markets in which they are used.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The main reason for doing the study is that during the past five
years there have been a large number of new mold release product
introductions, as well as the rapid diffusion of semi-permanent
mold release technology and systems in the marketplace.  The
diffusion of semi-permanent mold release systems, which offer
multiple release capabilities, excellent surface finish properties,
scale economies and a variety of other advantages, have caused some
observers to predict that they will supplant more traditional
topical coatings.  This will be premature but, nonetheless,
semi-permanents will adversely impact the growth potential for
metallic stearates, synthetic waxes, polymer, silicone and other
topical coatings.<P>

In addition, environmental issues involving solvent emissions and
CFC propellents have placed the industry in a state of turmoil and
are leading to the development and diffusion of CFC alternatives,
water-based emulsions, and alternative methods of mold release
delivery.These issues are also promoting a shift to lubricants,
which are more environmentally sound.  Finally, there has been an
increase in the number of industry participants and most industry
observers maintain that mold releases is one market in which small
companies can still effectively compete and find unique market
opportunities.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of the report is comprehensive, covering the present
status and future prospects for mold releases in the United States.<P>

It covers the many issues concerning the merits of and future
prospects of semi-permanent mold release technology in addition to
similar techno-economic issues dealing with topical coatings such
as parting agents, metallics stearates, soaps, waxes, and
silicones, among others.   In addition, the report covers the
applications and end-use markets in which these mold releases are
used.  It covers the environmental issues that so many regard as
critical to the industry's current state of change.  The report
provides an analysis of the market shares of suppliers along with
analysis of the structure of companies involved in producing
chemicals that are  formulated with other materials and packaged as
mold releases.  Lubricants, which are blended into polymer melts
and  are often the same chemical compounds (providing release
features) are  assessed for their impact on mold releases. The
competitive position of the main players in the market and the
strategic options they face are also discussed as well as such
competitive factors as marketing, technical services, distribution
and operations.  The roles of major multinational chemical
companies and vertical integration are considered as well.  The
report also looks at the varieties of basic research, product
development and commericalization that being conducted in the area
of mold releases.<P>

The study also covers slip agents and anti-blocking agents which
are related to mold releases.  Lubricants, another abherent
material related to mold releases, are not included, except in a
secondary sense.  Unless otherwise noted, all figures represent
consumption of these mold release products in million of pounds.
These figures include active ingredients only and exclude solvents,
oils, water and other materials that are blended with mold
releases.  As a result, the 54.3 million pounds of mold releases
consumed in 1989 were formulated with an additional 133 million
pounds of these other materials.  The value of consumption ($192
million in 1989) and sales, in million of dollars is at the level
of the final end-user.  At this level, a large portion of the cost
includes packaging, propellants and other materials.  As used in
this study, the term consumption is equivalent to, and used
interchangeably with the terms demand and sales.  During the
discussion of end-use markets, consumption is related to indicators
in the tables.  This does not imply that the indicator used
represents the sole end-use in that market (e.g., casting shipments
for metal processing markets).  Rather, it is used for comparative
purposes.  All growth rates mentioned in the tables and the text
are based on the average annual rate of growth from 1989 to 1994.
The compounding method is used.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY<B/><P>

This study provides the most complete accounting of the ongoing
developments in mold releases currently available in a
"multi-client" study format.  It provides a most thorough and
up-to-date assessment that can be found anywhere on the subject.
The study also provides extensive quantification of the many
important facets of the market developments for mold release
agents.  This, in turn, contributes to the determination of what
kind of strategic response that firms may adopt in order to compete
in this dynamic market.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Initially, a comprehensive and exhaustive search for the literature
on mold releases was conducted.  These secondary sources included
trade journals, technical journals, on-line databases, product data
sheets, other product/promotional literature, annual reports, and
other publications.  In addition, there were some 50 formal and
informal interviews and discussions with end-users, chemical
distributors, plastic compounders, lubricant and other plastic
additive producers, technical experts, government officials, trade
association officials, and responsible officers, sales and
technical personnel of the mold releases companies themselves.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Founded in 1971, Business Communications Co., Inc. (BCC) is known
throughout the world for its technical-economic reports and
services.  The company has studied major market, economic and
technological developments that have characterized industry during
the past two decades to produce reports, newsletters and
conferences.  In the process, BCC has focused on advanced
materials, high-technology systems and components, and novel
processing methods since the development and marketing of these
phenomena assert a profound influence on manufacturers and users on
a worldwide scale.  BCC clients include almost every major
corporation  in the United States, Canada, Western Europe, and
Japan.  Of related interest to the subject of mold releases (and
lubricants) are such BCC reports as Engineering Resins; Fluorine
Compounds; Molded Plastic Containers; Pipe Market; Plastic Film
Business; Plastic Sheet:  Formable and Stampable Industrial;
Plastics for Large Automotive Parts; Plastics in Gears, Bearings,
Fasteners and Seals; Plastics in Military Applications;  Plastics
in Valves and Pumps; Powder Metallurgy; Resins: Commodities Compete
with Engineered; RIM (Reaction Injection Molding); Thermoplastics:
einforced; Thermosets: Reinforced; and
Thermosets/Thermoplastics: High-Temperature.<P>

