<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C132B  SORBENT MATERIALS FOR NON-SPILL APPLICATIONS:
TECHNICAL REVIEW</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>SUSAN ARNOLD KAPLAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>CHAPTER 1.  INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Sorbent materials are used by many different industries for hundreds,
maybe even thousands, of diverse applications.  They are
currently being evaluated (or possibly reevaluated) for use in
applications such as reduction of air and water emissions, process
improvements, product purifications, and as catalysts.  As a result
of the growing use of sorbents in these as well as other areas,
improved materials and processes are rapidly being developed.  In
this two-volume study, BCC presents both new and well-established
technologies and materials that have been and are being developed.<P>



<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

There is an incredible amount of information available on this
topic, with new products being introduced, it seems, almost daily.
Because of this, BCC performed the study in order to provide a
comprehensive reference for those involved with or interested in
sorbent materials and technologies.  BCC sorted through and condensed
information from vast quantities of company literature,
published articles, and reference materials to compile this report.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report is intended to assist those involved in the design of
sorption systems and products, selection of materials, purchasing or
using these systems, as well as financial analysts responsible for
evaluating companies involved in this industry.  BCC feels that this
comprehensive report will be invaluable to technical personnel, as
well as marketing and business managers in the following areas:<P>

     -  Companies involved in the development, manufacturing,
mining,
        or distribution of sorbent products,<P>

  -  State and federal government personnel within the Environmental
 Protection Agency, Bureau of Mines, and Occupational
        Safety and Health Administration with responsibilities per
        taining to these materials,<P>

     -  Organizations involved in applied or basic research,<P>

     -  Financial institutions and venture capitalists interested in
     emerging technologies with large growth potential as well as
     identifying areas of potential trouble.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This two-volume report covers the technology, economic, and
environmental considerations of the sorbent industry.  This is
primarily a study of the U.S. market, but noteworthy international
activities are also included.  The forecasts are given in constant
U.S. dollars and the growth rates are compounded.<P>

Volume I includes:<P>

  -  General sorption applications<BR>
<MENU>-  U.S. markets with forecasts through 1995<BR>
     -  Industry structure and players<BR>
     -  Selected company profiles<BR>
     -  Economic and pricing information</MENU><BR>
  -  International issues<BR>
<MENU>-  Environmental, safety, and regulatory concerns<BR>
     -  Company directory by material and by application</MENU><BR>
-  Alphabetical directory of companies<P>


Volume II includes:<P>

-  Sorption mechanisms and terminology<BR>
-  Process technologies<BR>
-  Materials and their specific applications<BR>
-  Patent and literature reviews<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Online and manual searches were made of the literature, including
technical, trade, and government publications.  Product and market
information came directly from the companies involved whenever
possible.  Company profile information was obtained from published
directories, articles, and from the companies themselves.<P>


