<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-133 SORBENT MATERIAL FOR SPILLS AND OTHER LIQUID PICKUPS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-133 SORBENT MATERIAL FOR SPILLS AND OTHER LIQUID PICKUPS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Susan Kaplan</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>CHAPTER 1.  INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

In the U.S., there is a growing awareness of the impact of
chemicals, oils, hazardous materials, and infectious or toxic
materials on people and the environment.  Federal and state
regulations regarding spills and the disposal of sorbent materials
used to clean them up (also used in the disposal of liquid waste)
are becoming more restrictive.  Generators are responsible for the
proper handling of the chemicals they use and the wastes they
produce.  This makes it more important than ever for companies to be
well informed of the strengths and weaknesses of the different
sorbent technologies, and the products and services that are
available.  An important issue that should be considered when
selecting sorbents and stabilization agents is that all industries
are now required to actively pursue waste minimization, resource
recovery and recycling.  Careful selection of sorbents utilized
frequently for clean-up of various leaks and spills can potentially
reduce the quantity of waste that must be landfilled.  Selection of
the proper sorbent material is also important because of personnel
protection, fire, safety, and other hazards that may exist in
specific situations.  This report presents information regarding
sorbent and solidification materials used for industrial leaks,
spills, and other liquid waste.  It also covers materials used for
medical and consumer applications such as for water and body fluid
absorption.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is intended for those involved in the selection of
sorbent materials to help them make an informed decision regarding
the many different choices that are available.  BCC also feels that
this report is extremely important because end users, without a good
base knowledge of materials and their limitations, can purchase
products that are not the most efficient and economical choice for
their application.  Also, in some cases, fire and safety hazards
exist when these products are used on certain chemicals.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

BCC feels that this comprehensive, single-source report will be
invaluable to technical personnel, as well as marketing and business
managers in the following areas:<P>

<DD>- Companies involved in development, manufacturing, mining, or
       distribution of sorbent products and the materials that are
       used to produce them;</DD><BR>
<DD>-  State and federal government personnel within the
       Environmental Protection Agency, Department of
       Transportation, and Occupational Safety and Health
       Administration with responsibilities pertaining to these
       materials;</DD><BR>
<DD>-  Generators of hazardous waste, including laboratories, clean
        rooms, manufacturing sites, loading sites, transport trucks,
        hospitals, and public buildings;</DD><BR>
<DD>-  Organizations involved in applied or basic research;</DD><BR>
<DD>-  Financial institutions and venture capitalists interested in
        emerging technologies with large growth potential, as well as
        identifying areas of potential trouble.</DD><P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report covers the technology, economic, and environmental
considerations of the sorbent industry.  This is primarily a study
of the U.S. market, but noteworthy international activities are also
included.  The forecasts are given in constant U.S. dollars, and the
growth rates are compounded.<P>

This report includes descriptions of:<P>
     -  Sorption mechanisms<BR>
     -  Sorbent materials<BR>
     -  Material and product applications<BR>
     -  Product information arranged by tradename<BR>
     -  Industry test methods and result comparisons<BR>
     -  Industry structure and players<BR>
     -  U.S. markets presented by application and by material with
        forecasts through 1995<BR>
     -  Selected company profiles<BR>
     -  Patents and literature searches<BR>
     -  Economic and pricing information<BR>
     -  Environmental, safety, personnel protection, and regulatory
        concerns<BR>
     -  Company directory.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Online and manual searches were made of the literature, including
technical, trade, and government publications.  Product and market
information came directly from the companies involved when possible.
Information for company profiles was obtained from published
directories and from the companies themselves.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Other BCC reports and newsletters that may be of interest include:<P>

1.  Technologies for the Management of Hazardous Waste (C-059)<BR>
2.  The Huge Conventional Waste Management Business (C-038R)<BR>
3.  Environmental Management Through Biotechnology (C-110)<BR>
4.  The Solid Waste Recycling Business (GB-127)<BR>
5.  Waste Treatment Technology News (Monthly newsletter)<P>



