<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-134  CHLOROFLUOROCARBONS (CFCs):
Alternatives (In-Kind) and Substitutes (Not-In-Kind)
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-134  CHLOROFLUOROCARBONS (CFCs):
Alternatives (In-Kind) and Substitutes (Not-In-Kind)</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ANNA CRULL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>SCOPE</B><P>

This technical/marketing report examines the growth and changes
taking place in the market for replacements to chlorofluorocarbons
(CFCs). Replacements include recycling efforts, alternative
chemicals that contain halogen or "alternatives (in-kind)," and
substitutes (not-in-kind). This report concentrates on strategic
changes in the replacements for CFCs.  New developments are almost
a daily occurrence in portions of this industry.  Never before has
the market for CFCs faced such a challenge. Bans and reduced
consumption demands occur almost weekly, yet the suitable
replacements for these chemicals are not all in place.<P>

Certain sectors are under increasing government regulation and
public scrutiny. Hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFCs), the leading
alternative, could be phased out by 2015 and banned by 2030.  For
U.S. producers, a decline on CFC production is in effect. Many
foreign producers have met restrictions by simply eliminating
aerosol uses for CFCs.  The U.S. banned nearly all aerosol use of
CFCs in the 1970s. The latest version of the Montreal Protocol and
the Clean Air Act phase out CFCs, Halons, and carbon tetrachloride
by 2000 and methyl chloroform by 2005.<P>


<B>MATERIALS AND TECHNOLOGY</B><P>

This technical/marketing report is based on information from the
various companies involved and the numerous agencies, public and
private, that monitor the use of fluorochemicals. Mandated taxes on
the CFCs have doubled and tripled the prices and by the year 2000
will be part of a ten-fold increase in the selling price of the
remaining CFC production.<P>

It continues to be difficult to enter the materials end of the
fluorine compounds business because the technology involved is both
dangerous and expensive and the established major producers are
well integrated. The  force that  kept companies in the business of
fluorochemicals was the lucrative profit margins. Now billions may
be spent on R&D and testing to regain just a portion of the CFC
market. The properties of the fluorine compounds are in many cases
unique to certain applications: their stability, chemical and
thermal resistance, and inflammability.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The organization of the chemicals is to present the compounds in a
way that best reflects the marketplace and the dominant compounds.
Hydrogen fluoride (HF) is given a separate line-item listing to
reflect its unique status and is one of the few compounds beside
the CFCs that the U.S. government keeps statistics on.  Use was
made of the most recent government information on CFCs. Information
from both the International Trade Commission and the EPA.<P>

Information beyond government statistics is a result of producers
and suppliers sharing their perceptions with us. Interviewees also
tried to verify and augment our data. The selling prices which are
the key to the "value" figures for the various compounds represent
a scenario that comes fairly close to a consensus that it allows
the chemical companies a reasonable profit margin to recoup the
large R&D  and capital expenses of the new chemicals, and is still
at a level that the majority of users can afford.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This technical/marketing report will be of value to anyone in
government or industry who is involved in monitoring or producing
alternatives for CFCs, or recycling systems or CFCs, CFCs, or other
fluorine-containing chemicals. Companies engaged in the marketing
of other fluorine compounds for industrial or medical uses will
also find this a useful document, in terms of evaluating their own
market for expansion opportunities, and keeping abreast of new
products and technologies. The alternatives to CFCs must be put in
the total context of the continuing green movement and total
environmental safety.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC, INC. STUDIES</B><P>

Business Communications Co. regularly publishes in-depth studies on
specialty chemicals, plastics, and environmental concerns. Of
interest might be P113 titled "Plastics in Gears, Bearings,
Fasteners, and Seals" and Recycling Plastic Packaging [P084]. The
monthly newsletters "Membrane & Separation Technology News" and
"Waste Treatment Technology News" include information on fluorine
membranes and environmental information. Future developments
relating to CFCs and other potentially ozone-depleting chemicals
will be covered in the new monthly newsletter form BCC, Inc.,
"Atmospheric Monitoring and Abatement News."<P>


