<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-137R  ENVIRONMENTALLY ACCEPTABLE SOLDERING AND CLEANING
MATERIALS AND SYSTEMS IN ELECTRONICS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-137R  ENVIRONMENTALLY ACCEPTABLE SOLDERING AND CLEANING
MATERIALS AND SYSTEMS IN ELECTRONICS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DIRK MUYSKENS</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This new Business Communications Co. report provides an in-depth analysis of new cleaning and soldering materials for the
electronics industry as it pertains to the manufacture and cleaning
of electronic assemblies.  New chemicals analyzed are solder
pastes, fluxes, rosins, cleaners and solvents and environmentally
safe alternative chemicals.  The study features in-depth analyses
of the higher performance requirements of products, applications,
markets and marketers.<P>

Case studies of user concerns, as well as worldwide materials
market size, growth and usage trends through the year 1998, will
show suppliers to the industry the paths to business opportunity
while end-users will benefit from knowing about the new products
and their suppliers.<P>

Solder pastes and cleaners are a relatively small market in
themselves compared to the total value of materials for
electronics.  However, they are the "tail that wags the dog" for
surface joining and product reliability and appearance.
Cleaning in electronics is in a state of "flux" as the industry
seeks new solutions.  The electronics industry is approaching a
cleaning crisis in response to the toxicity issue of chlorinated
fluorocarbons (CFCs).  Concerns about atmospheric greenhouse
effects and ozone depletion have resulted in the banning of the
most common materials used to clean electronic assemblies.
Additionally, the reduced standoff clearances of new assembly
technology, such as SMT, have made cleaning more difficult.
Together, these factors are forcing the development of new
materials, processes and equipment for soldering and cleaning.<P>

Electronic chemicals and materials are the fundamental technology
at the heart of today's electronics products.  Electronic
components with very high functional density and component
performance requirements demand unique and innovative approaches
which address electrical, thermal and mechanical material concerns.
Current indicators show that advanced fine-line approaches will
drive electronic materials for the 1990s through the 21st century.<P>

This BCC electronic materials technology report analyzes the
current and future materials for soldering, cleaning and assembly
within the context of shifting geophysical forces which will
determine the future industry winners.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

The report provides a thorough analysis of the conventional
soldering and cleaning materials industry, and then provides a
comparison of advanced materials and substitute processes, to
accommodate new imaging technology, fine-line and high-speed
devices.  The study discusses the global electronic materials
industry structure, describing activities of the players in the
U.S., Europe, Asia and the rest of the world.  Worldwide material
consumption is tabulated and market forecasts are provided by type
of material through the year 1998.  Environmental issues, case
studies and winning strategies are presented with an eye to the
21st century.<P>


This report is directed to the following decision makers who need
strategic information on the electronic materials industry and its
markets:<P>

<UL><LI>  Suppliers of chemicals, materials and substrates
<LI>  Suppliers of printed circuit boards and components
<LI>  Circuit board assemblers
  <LI> Electronic and electrical equipment manufacturers
  <LI>  Electronic cleaning equipment manufacturers
  <LI>  Merger and acquisition and investment executives
  <LI>  Environmental compliance executives
  <LI>  Federal, state and local electronics and environmental
     organizations<P></UL>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This BCC analytical business tool covers the new technology in
terms of materials, processes and applications.  The report
chapters reveal the emerging technologies and then make analytical
market and industry forecasts that identify paths to new and
profitable business opportunities.  An extensive directory of
suppliers provides a one-stop source for all industry needs.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Data are based on a thorough review of and appraisal of electronic
materials technology based on a systematic review of developments
through telephone and in-person interviews, and an extensive data
base of technical and marketing sources.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC RESEARCH CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Since 1971, BCC has been a leader in market research and consulting
to the electronics and materials industries.  Over the past five
years, BCC has conducted in-depth analyses of technologies and
business opportunities in integrated circuit packaging, the printed
circuit board industry, tape automated bonding, surface mount
technology, fine pitch technology and thick and thin film in
microelectronics.  BCC continues its in-depth analysis with the
current volume.  The following reports are available from BCC:<P>

<UL>  C-134   CFCs, Alternatives and Substitutes<BR>
  G-067U  Printed Circuit Board Industry<BR>
  GB-138  Multichip Modules in Electronics<BR>
  G-118   Surface Mount Technology in Electronics<BR>
  G-122   Fine Pitch Technology<P></UL>

Also available from BCC are two monthly newsletters that cover
electronics materials and waste management developments:
Electronic Materials Technology News and Waste Treatment Technology
News.<P>

<B>ACKNOWLEDGEMENT</B><P>

Dr. Charles L. Hutchins of C. Hutchins and Associates, Raleigh, NC,
supplied many contributions and editorial comments during the
preparation of this report.<P>

