<CENTER><H2>C-145  NEW SURFACTANTS FOR NEW APPLICATIONS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>SUSAN KAPLAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This BCC report is an invaluable technical/economic review intended
for those involved in the surfactants industry.  It is a
comprehensive single-source document that provides a broad base of
technical information as well as an evaluation of the market,
players, and products.<P>

In this report, BCC attempts to provide an objective view of the
actual consumption patterns in this industry.  We analyze the market
data in three ways:  by charge, chemical, and application.  By
charge, we provide a detailed analysis of sales (volume and value)
and production (volume) data.  In addition, we provide information
on selected individual surfactants and a breakdown of the market by
application.<P>


<B>BACKGROUND INFORMATION</B><P>

Surfactants reduce the surface tension of water or other solvents.
They are produced from natural fats and oils; from silvichemicals
such as lignin, rosin, and tall oil; or from chemical intermediates
derived from coal tar and petroleum.  They function as dispersing
agents, emulsifiers, foaming agents, and wetting agents.<P>

Surfactants are widely used in both consumer and industrial
applications.  Consumer applications include soaps and cleaners,
laundry detergents, cosmetics, and toiletries.  Non-consumer
applications are found in almost every industry and, except for
cleaning uses, most consume minute quantities as processing aids.
Industries where they are used include rubber, plastics, textiles,
civil engineering and construction, petroleum drilling, ore-
processing, food processing, medicines and pharmaceuticals,
herbicides, paper and pulp, machinery, and metals.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

There is a major upheaval occurring in the surfactants industry.  It
appears that almost every product where they are used, especially in
the consumer market, has been recently reformulated. These
reformulations are a result of new demands that are being placed on
these chemicals, and the products that contain them, by users as
well as by federal, state, and local governments.<P>

There are several main driving forces behind the changes that are
occurring in the industry.  These forces include:  the economy;
demands for generally "green" products that are milder, safer, and
cheaper; high expenses due, in particular, to regulatory compliance,
insurance, and environmental-related expenses; technical
obsolescence; erosion of commodity/specialty segment
differentiation; and the public perception of the chemical industry
in general.<P>

Because about half of the surfactants produced in the U.S. are used
in the detergent (both consumer and industrial) and personal care
markets, the industry is heavily influenced by regulatory
requirements, and consumer demands and trends.  Growing public
concerns over the environment, or the "green" movement, are causing
surfactants to have a more critical role in laundry and cleaning
products.<P>

There is a growing demand from consumers for mild, biodegradable,
non-toxic products that are made from natural raw materials.
Changes are also being brought on by their desire to decrease energy
consumption by the reduction of washing and cleaning temperatures.
Consumers are demanding a reduced number of products, achieved
through multifunctionality, in an effort to save money and to lower
the quantity of chemicals added to the wastewater.<P>

More stringent regulatory requirements in the areas of ecology and
toxicology are also starting to affect industrial and consumer usage
as well.  Government regulations are having wide ranging effects.
Volatile organic compound (VOC) restrictions are affecting
formulations of widely varying products from cosmetics and
toiletries, which use alcohol, to paints and adhesives.  These
regulations are causing a shift to water-based systems, which need
different surfactants than solvent-based systems.  VOC regulations
impact product performance and characteristics such as "dry time"
and aesthetics.<P>

In addition, new products are being developed for new or changing
industrial applications.  Surfactants are beginning to attract
attention in energy and environmental protection applications.  They
are being tried in pollution-control systems, paper processing, and
ultra-thin films.  They are also being evaluated in sintering of
superconducting ceramics, and in medical applications such as blood
substitutes for transfusions.  Industrial cleaning products are
being reformulated to make them more environmentally friendly and
safer to use.  There also seems to be some emphasis on making them
easier for non-English-speaking personnel to use.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This BCC study is intended for those involved in the surfactants and
surfactant-containing product industry.  It will be especially
useful to those performing research and development, sales and
marketing, and surfactant selection and specification.  It will also
be useful to financial analysts who are responsible for evaluating
companies involved in the industry as well as government analysts
whose responsibility is to track these chemicals.<P>

BCC feels that this comprehensive two-part (market analysis and
technical review) report will be invaluable to technical personnel
as well as marketing and business managers of companies involved in
the following areas:<P>

<UL>
-  Companies involved in the development, manufacturing,
        and distribution of surfactants and surfactant-based
        products<P>
     -  Industrial surfactant users<P>
     -  Organizations involved in applied or basic research<P>
     -  Financial institutions and venture capitalists<P>
     -  Government analysts</UL><P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report covers the technical, environmental, and economic
considerations of the surfactant industry.  It is primarily a study
of the U.S. market, but noteworthy international activities are also
included.  The forecasts are given in constant U.S. dollars and the
growth rates are compounded.<P>

Part I includes:<P>

<UL>
-  Industry trends and new developments<BR>
-  Analysis of the U.S. market with forecasts through 1997<BR>
-  Industry structure, participants, and products<BR>
-  International issues<BR>
-  Economic and pricing information<BR>
-  Environmental, safety, and regulatory concerns</UL><P>

Part II includes:<P>

<UL>
-  Discussion of surfactant chemicals including chemistry,
   performance, and properties<P>
-  Role of surfactants in dispersion systems (suspensions,
   emulsions, and foams), in solubilization, wetting and
   dewetting, thickening, gel formation, and controlled
   dissolution<P>
-  Applications by chemical and function and by market segment<P>
-  Patent and literature review<P>
-  Appendices<BR>
<UL>List of abbreviations and definition of terms<BR>
Company directory (alphabetical and by function)<BR>
Additional market data and player information</UL><P></UL>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

On-line and manual searches were made of the literature, including
technical, trade, and government publications.  Information was also
obtained from published directories and from the companies
themselves.<P>

