<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-149  PAPER AND PAPER CHEMICALS: HIGHLIGHTING
ENVIRONMENTAL CONSIDERATIONS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-149  PAPER AND PAPER CHEMICALS: HIGHLIGHTING
ENVIRONMENTAL CONSIDERATIONS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS KEVIN SWIFT</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goal of this report is to provide a detailed and comprehensive
multi-client study of pulp and paper chemicals and their commercial
potential.  The objectives include a thorough coverage of the
underlying technological and environmental issues of the pulp and
paper chemicals business, as well as assessments of new and
potential products and systems.  Another important objective is to
provide realistic market data and forecasts for pulp and paper
chemicals.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The main reason for doing this study is that during the past five
years there has been a large number of  changes in which chemicals
are used in manufacturing pulp, paper, and paperboard, as well as
changes in the pulp and paper industry itself.  In large part,
these changes revolve around issues concerning the environment.
The growth of recycling has promoted the increased use of
lower-cost secondary fibers at the expense of virgin fibers.  In
many ways this will aid the competitiveness of domestic pulp and
paper producers.  On the other hand, concern over dioxin discharges
and trace amounts in paper products have promoted the use of sodium
chlorate, hydrogen peroxide, oxygen, and other bleaching agents and
systems at the expense of chlorine.   Recent directions in the
legislative and regulatory arena indicate that environmental
pressures on dioxin and other issues--including clean water and
solid wastes--will intensify in the years to come, engendering
further changes in the pulp and paper chemical business.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of this report is comprehensive, covering the present
status of and future prospects for pulp and paper chemicals in the
United States.  It covers the many issues concerning the merits and
future prospects of pulping and bleaching chemicals, as well as
pigments, fillers, strengthening agents, sizing agents, defoamers,
biocides, and other paper additives.  In addition, the report
covers pulp, paper, and paperboard markets and products in which
these chemicals are used.  It also covers in detail the
environmental issues that so many regard as critical to the
industry's current state of change.  The report provides an
analysis of the market shares, along with an analysis of the
structure of companies involved in producing pulp and paper
chemicals.  The competitive position of the main players in the
market and the strategic options they face are also discussed, as
well as such competitive factors as marketing, technical services,
distribution, and operations.  The roles of major multinational
chemical companies and vertical integration by forest product
companies are considered as well.  The report also looks at the
varieties of basic research, product development, and
commercialization that are being conducted in the area of pulp and
paper chemicals.<P>

Unless noted otherwise, all figures represent consumption of these
pulp and paper chemicals in either thousands of short tons (of
2,000 pounds each) or less frequently, in millions of pounds.  The
value of consumption ($3.6 billion) of pulp and paper chemicals by
the pulp and paper industry, in millions of dollars,  represents
the price of product shipped from the manufacturer's plant site.
These prices exclude the cost of freight and insurance.  Thus,
prices do not reflect list prices, but actual transaction prices
between a chemical producer and the pulp or paper mill.  As used in
this study, the term consumption is equivalent to, and used
interchangeably with, the terms demand and sales.  During the
discussion of individual chemical products, consumption is related
to indicators in the table.  This does not imply that the indicator
used represents the sole application of that chemical in the pulp
and paper industry.  Rather, it is used for comparative purposes,
and often rather broad indicators (i.e., wood pulp production) are
used.  For example, lime (or calcium oxide) is used predominantly
during pulping (for the recovery of caustic soda from soda ash in
green liquor), but has also been used in bleaching (in the
preparation of calcium hypochlorite).   All growth rates mentioned
in the tables and in the text are based on the average annual rate
of growth from 1991 through 1996.  The compounding method is used.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study provides the most complete accounting of ongoing
developments in pulp and paper chemicals  currently available in a
multi-client format.  It provides the most thorough and up-to-date
assessment that can be found anywhere on the subject.  The study
also provides extensive quantification of the many important facets
of the market developments for pulp and paper chemicals.  This, in
turn, contributes to the determination of what kind of strategic
response companies may adopt in order to compete in this dynamic
market.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Initially, a comprehensive and exhaustive search of the literature
on pulp and paper chemicals was conducted.  These secondary sources
included technical journals, technical books, product material
safety data sheets, other product/promotional literature, annual
reports, 10-K reports, and other publications.  In addition, there
were some 50 formal and informal interviews with pulp and paper
producers, technical experts, government officials, trade
association officials, and the sales and technical personnel of the
pulp and paper chemical companies themselves.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Founded in 1971, Business Communications Co., Inc. (BCC) is known
throughout the world for its technical-economic reports and
services.  The company has studied major market, economic,
environmental, and technological developments that have
characterized the chemical industry during the past two decades to
produce reports, newsletters, and conferences.  In the process, BCC
has focused on advanced materials, high-technology systems and
components, and novel processing methods since the development and
marketing of these phenomena assert a profound influence on
manufacturers and users on a worldwide scale.  BCC clients include
almost every major corporation in the U.S., Canada,
Western Europe, and Japan.<P>

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
<H3>TABLE OF CONTENTS</H3></CENTER>
<PRE>
