<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-151  CATALYSTS FOR ORGANIC SYNTHESIS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-151  CATALYSTS FOR ORGANIC SYNTHESIS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS</B><P>

The objectives of this report are to: (a) Identify the catalysts
for organic synthesis, the suppliers and users; (b) Estimate and
forecast the quantities and dollar values of U.S. catalyst
consumption for organic synthesis, by catalyst type and by
application; (c) Elucidate the forces for market and technological
change with respect to catalysts for organic synthesis, and assess
their impact.<P>

The goals of this report are to shed light on a topic of major
importance and to provide executive management with a basis for
further consideration in making business plans.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTION</B><P>

The catalyst supply industry and users of catalysts for organic
synthesis now face both market and technological challenges, as
well as opportunities. The next several years will prove to be
dynamic for the catalyst industry, with new and shifting demands
for synthesized organic chemicals, cost containment issues,
environmental concerns, stereoselectivity, chiral technology and
biotechnology playing significant roles.<P>

This report presents a timely examination of the changing role
catalysts play in the manufacture of organic chemicals. The study
also details the ways in which catalysts address some of the most
important problems facing the chemical industry as it confronts a
new world order of business competition.<P>

The major objective of this BCC report is to illuminate a topic
which is poorly documented in business literature.. While most
studies discussing catalysts focus mainly on petroleum refining and
pollution control applications, this BCC study focuses exclusively
on catalysts for organic synthesis, encompassing primary and
intermediate petrochemicals, polymers and the many performance and
specialty organic chemicals. BCC also contributes by integrating
perspectives in chemical catalysis and biocatalysis.<P>

<B>AUDIENCE</B><P>

This report is written specifically for a business audience of
executives, business managers, marketing managers, product managers
and business-minded scientists. It is not a science text. Expected
readers of this report include catalyst suppliers, catalyst users,
catalyst support materials suppliers, and those who may be
considering entrance into the catalyst industry.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT</B><P>

This report concerns catalysts for organic chemical synthesis,
(i.e., organic "chemical processing") and excludes catalysts for
petroleum refining, pollution control, inorganic chemicals
synthesis and non-synthesis applications of catalysts.<P>

The OVERVIEW of Chapter I provides a concise, broad view of
catalysts and the catalyst business. Chapter II discusses the MAJOR
ISSUES facing the catalyst business today, particularly as regards
organic synthesis, and its major directions in the future. Chapter
III details the CATALYST INDUSTRY STRUCTURE AND DYNAMICS, and
identifies key players. Chapter IV on CATALYST PRODUCTS provides
details, quantified estimates and forecasts of U.S. consumption and
value, on all the major categories, including: acid catalysts, base
catalysts, metal catalysts, metallocenes, nonmetal catalysts,
zeolite catalysts, free-radical initiators, phase-transfer
catalysts, biocatalysts and the new biomimetics. Chapter V on
CATALYST APPLICATIONS covers primary petrochemicals and
petrochemical intermediates, polymers, fats and oils, surfactants
and plasticizers, fuel additives, pharmaceuticals, pesticides,
flavor and aroma chemicals, rubber-processing chemicals,
lubricating oil and grease additives, color chemicals, photographic
chemicals, textile and tanning chemicals, carbohydrates, amino
acids, peptides, oligonucleotides, and other organic chemicals.
Chapter VI provides an overview of CATALYST SCIENCE and the latest
technological developments. Chapter VII PROFILES COMPANIES in
catalyst supply. Four APPENDIXES complete this study.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This study results from three months of focused and extensive
research into the subject. Primary sources of information were
telephone interviews with a wide range of catalyst suppliers and
users (both domestic and foreign), and foreign correspondences,
with over fifty primary contacts. Extensive secondary sources of
information were also utilized, including company reports, product
literature, trade literature, computerized in-house patent searches
and readings of the scientific and technical literature.<P>

All analyses are made independently and objectively, without the
bias of vested interests. Mentions of products are not
endorsements, and omissions, if any, are unintentional. Estimates
of quantities and values of catalysts consumed refer to the U.S.
marketplace. Unless otherwise noted, all estimates and forecasts
refer to the United States. Rationales for estimates are provided,
and assumptions clearly stated. Given the proprietary nature of
some information, we expect knowledgeable readers to supplement our
analyses with their special insights.<P>

Quantities are expressed in pounds (lbs.), where 1 lb. = 453.59
grams, 1000 grams = 1 kilogram, 2000 lbs. = 1 ton, 1 metric ton =
1000 kilograms = 2205 lbs., and 14.58 troy ounces = 1 lb.  Sales
and value are expressed in U.S. 1991 dollars, where $1 = 100c, $1
MM = $1 million = $1 x 106, and foreign currencies have been
converted to U.S. dollars at prevailing exchange rates. Forecasts
are expressed in constant 1991 dollars to reflect real changes
without inflation, and assume constant prices. Valuations of
catalysts refer to ready-to-use products. The average annual growth
rate (AAGR) is derived by the compounding method.<P>

<B>CREDENTIALS AND RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

The analyst for this study is a chemist with additional technical
background in biotechnology. He also has an M.B.A. in marketing and
years of experience in technical and business management. Reports
written by this study's author include the subjects of chiral
technology, enzymes and numerous end-use markets. Published BCC
studies relating to the present topic include:<P>

<MENU>C-023R: Automotive And Petrochemical Catalysts<BR>
C-079 Chiral Technology<BR>
C-118 Markets For Zeolites<BR>
C-147 Comprehensive Outlook of the Enzyme Industry<BR>
C-066 Immobilized Biocatalysts<BR>
C-132 Adsorbents For Nonspill Applications<BR>
GB-118 Rare Earths</MENU><P>

+ Specific reports on applications, such as polymers, polymer
additives, fuel additives, drugs, pesticides, cosmetics, flavors
and aromas, surfactants, biotechnology, and others.<P>

