<CENTER><H2>C-107N ADVANCED NOVEL SEPARATIONS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>CRAIQ CAMPBELL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>
<I>ANNA CRULL</I><BR>
PROJECT MANAGER
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The market for separations, in general, is quite large and has the potential to become even larger.
Any 
industry using pure water or chemicals is a possible market, as are those industries which produce
waste 
materials or purify and concentrate various liquids and gases. Market opportunities are expanding
due to 
improved technology and greater energy savings. Increased enforcement of waste cleanup
legislation, 
along with the skyrocketing cost of traditional technologies, has provided an opportunity for the 
separations industry.<P>

The field of separation science continues to grow and evolve. Researchers in university and
industrial 
laboratories continue to explore, develop and improve processes and technologies. The goal of
this report 
is to examine novel techniques for separations and to analyze the market for these techniques. A
few of 
the processes described in this report are already available commercially, and have become well
known. 
Others are still in the research phase and are somewhat obscure.<P>


This report serves as in introduction to state-of-the-art separations techniques. A process
description is 
given for each technique, along with historical background, applications, and patent information
when 
available. The report will be of interest to those who wish  to keep up with the breakthroughs and 
improvements going on in separation science, and provide market projections for those interested
in exploring commercialization opportunities. <P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report analyzes the markets, technologies and companies involved in various novel
separations such 
as exsorption, supercritical fluids, field flow fractionation, and magnetic separations. The
technologies are 
each in a different phase of development, from strictly research to full commercialization. Specific
product 
information will be covered when available.<P>

Each of the processes introduced in this report offers the opportunity to expand the potential of
separation 
science. Values given for markets are generally based on the best estimates of those involved in
the 
commercialization of the techniques. There are many factors to consider when launching new
technology, 
not the least being the characteristics of the targeted industry application. Some fields welcome
new 
technology with open arms, while others are more conservative in nature. Competition from other 
processes, both novel and established, also play a part in the success or failure of a technique.<P>

Values of the markets in this report are for the year given, represent sales by companies selling
into the 
marketplace, and are for the United States only. Projections are in terms of constant dollars and
represent 
real influence on the U.S. market sector. For the technologies discussed in this
technical/marketing report, 
the United Sates is the leader in both commercial application and R&D.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Research for this report began with a review of current reported data. Manufacturers' product
literature 
was included when available, and interviews with company representatives and industry experts
were 
conducted. By compiling and evaluating this information, BCC, Inc. has made an assessment of
the 
outlook for various novel separation processes. The resulting report will be of value to current 
manufacturers, companies entering or expanding their involvement in the separations industry, and
to 
those companies interested in utilizing the processes for their own applications.<P>


<B>DISCLAIMER</B><P>

The author assumes no liability for the reported information or for its use. The developed
information is 
intended to be as reliable as possible and of a professional nature. The author can assume no
liability for 
any loss or damage as a result of reliance on any materials or information developed herein. This
is not a 
legal or accounting document, and much of the information is of a speculative nature.<P>


