<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-153  REPROGRAPHIC CHEMICALS: THE CHANGING ENVIRONMENT
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-153  REPROGRAPHIC CHEMICALS: THE CHANGING ENVIRONMENT</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ROBERT H. MORAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

BCC's goal in conducting this study was to determine the current
worldwide status of the market for reprographics materials, and
assess the growth potential over a five-year period from 1991 to
1996.  We were particularly interested in the changing structure of
materials brought about by environmental regulations and the
growing use of electronic composition and publishing systems.<P>

Our major objective was to present a comprehensive analysis of the
current reprographic materials industry and plot its future course.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

Over the past decade, legislation to improve the environment
through decreased emissions of volatile organic compounds (VOCs)
and restriction of substances in waste water streams, has caused
many industries, including reprographics, to change some of the
materials used in their products.  The increased utilization of
electronics has also changed materials requirements, especially in
the prepress area of the business.<P>

BCC decided to examine the current position of the materials used
in reprographics technology.  We were interested to find out what
kinds of inks, solvents, films and plates are being used to meet
the demands of a changing environment.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

We assembled a study of four major categories of materials used in
reprographics: printing and packaging inks, toners, prepress
materials, and press cleaners and washes.  We present a worldwide
industry structure, examine the competitive aspects of the
industry, analyze the current markets, and project shipments for
each of the material categories to 1996.  This study will be of
interest to those who manufacture printing inks and the various
chemicals used in their composition, prepress equipment and
materials, electronic composition and publishing systems, toners
and duplicating equipment, and cleaning and maintenance materials
for printing presses.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of our study encompasses the four major components of
inks: pigments, vehicles, solvents and additives.  We also examine
the major kinds of prepress materials: photocomposition paper, film
and developers; and printing plates.  Two other
materials are explored: toners and pressroom cleaners.  We also
analyze the growth potential of the five major kinds of printing
technologies used for printing and packaging: letterpress,
lithography, flexography, gravure and screen printing; and present
forecasts for growth to 1996.  Technological issues are reviewed.
Other influential factors, such as past growth and the effects of
a slower economic climate, are also discussed.<P>

Because this is a worldwide industry, BCC analyzes the domestic and
international environmental regulatory situations and their impact
on the business.  We also assess economic indicators and their
possible effects on the industry.  BCC presents an analysis of the
driving forces within the printing and packaging market segments
using these reprographic materials and looks at the impact of these
forces for the future.<P>

We also review the size and status of in-house publishing
organizations within the domestic environment and the kinds of ink
and toner they use in their printing operations.  Future
consumption of these materials by in-house publishers is also
estimated.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

BCC presents an analysis of the value of reprographic material
shipments by each major category.  Domestic material consumption is
detailed; worldwide consumption is added for each category.
Our estimated value is what manufacturers and materials providers
have paid in current dollars.  Then, based on our surveys, we
analyze applications of these materials, calculate an estimate for
growth, and forecast shipments for 1996.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC surveyed approximately 75 companies to obtain the data for this
report.  Included were manufacturers of chemicals, inks and toners,
prepress systems and materials, and electronic systems; commercial
printers, corporate publishing departments and distributors of
printed materials.  We also included several trade associations,
the U.S. Department of Commerce, and data from financial and
industry sources.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Several other reports are related to this topic.  They are:<P>

C-026N Radiant Energy Cure Systems for Coatings, Adhesives and Inks<BR>
C-137 Environmentally Acceptable Soldering and Cleaning
Materials<BR>
C-025 Inks/Printing Chemicals<P>


