<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-161  MATERIALS FOR ENVIRONMENTALLY ACCEPTABLE COATINGS,
INKS, AND ADHESIVES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-161  MATERIALS FOR ENVIRONMENTALLY ACCEPTABLE COATINGS,
INKS, AND ADHESIVES
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>GEORGE INNES
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

This report presents the findings of an analysis of the U. S.
market for selected raw materials used in environmentally
acceptable coatings, inks, and adhesives. Because of increasingly
restrictive government regulations on emissions of volatile
organic compounds (VOCs), and consequent changes in formulations
to reduce or eliminate the use of organic solvents, the materials
used have been undergoing profound changes.<P>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report seeks to describe and to quantify the changes in
materials used by these industries in a detailed analysis. The
emphasis will be on future trends, changing technology, and
opportunities.<P>

The major objectives of the study are as follows:<P>

<UL><LI> To make available the most current and reliable
       information on the consumption of selected raw materials
       by coatings, inks, and adhesives.<P>

<LI> To forecast the market for these materials, broken down
       insofar as possible by industry, specific raw material,
       and type of environmentally acceptable formulation.<P>

<LI> To identify the most rapidly changing applications and
       the reasons for their growth or decline.<P>

<LI> To describe the major trends in the end uses.<P>

<LI> To provide profiles of the most important suppliers of
       raw materials.</UL><P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

There have been few studies of the critical raw materials
employed in the environmentally acceptable versions of coatings,
inks, and adhesives. There is a need to update existing
information.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>
This study should be useful to companies interested in supplying
chemical raw materials to this field, and to manufacturers of
coatings, inks, and adhesives, who may wish to keep abreast of
current developments and economics.<P>

<B>SCOPE</B><P>

This report will be limited to products that are most affected by
regulations that are gradually eliminating the use of organic
solvents: latex emulsions, water-dispersible synthetic resins,
monomers, oligomers, and photoinitiators. Such materials as
additives, pigments, solvents, and drying oils will not be
covered. Hot-melt adhesives are also excluded.<P>
<B>
METHODOLOGY AND SOURCES OF INFORMATION</B><P>

Information on market size, growth rates, technological trends,
and the impact of government regulations was obtained from
interviews with suppliers of the materials in question.
Interviews were also conducted with trade associations.<P>

Secondary sources include reviews of published data from the
Government and other sources, and of pertinent trade journals,
such as "American Paint and Coatings Journal," "Adhesives Age,"
"American Inkmake," "Chemical Marketing Reporter," and "Chemical
Week."<P>

Product literature from selected major suppliers was also
reviewed.<P>

<B>UNITS</B><P>

The forecast growth rates were based, to some extent, on BCC
studies listed below:<P>

Related BCC Studies:<P>

<UL>C-026N Radiant Energy Cure Systems<BR>
C-136       Environmentally Acceptable Coatings<BR>
C-137       Environmentally Acceptable Soldering and Cleaning
Materials<BR>
GB-131 Conformal Coatings<BR>
GB-143 Coatings and Liners for Pipes and Tools<P></UL>

All forecasts are given in constant 1991 dollars. No attempt has
been made to adjust for the changing value of the dollar. All
growth rates are compounded annually. Trade names are shown in
upper case letters.<P>


<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
