<CENTER><H2>C-173  CHELATES AND CLATHRATES: MARKETS AND OPPORTUNITIES</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DIRK MUYSKENS</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING STUDY</B><P>

This technical/marketing study was prepared as an in-depth analysis
to forecast and track significant changes in the chelate and
clathrate business and technology.  A wide spectrum of applications
is generating high interest in these compounds.<P>

Short definitions of chelates and clathrates are provided below in
order to clarify the contents of this study.<P>

A chelate is a chemical that will perform chelation, defined as the
reaction between a metal ion and the complexing agent, resulting in
formation of ring structures in corporating the ion.<P>

A Clathrate is a cage structure capable of including another
compound within its own structure.<P>

Chelates are used in a myriad of products to control adverse
effects of trace metal contamination, ranging from hairspray to
industrial boilers.  There are four types of chelates utilized--the
family of ethylenediamine tetraacetic acid products, phosphonates,
gluconates and citric acid.  This study also includes the use of
phosphates as sequestering agents (a process closely allied to
chelation).<P>

Although use of chelates is a technology developed over a period of
60 years, new applications are continually being found, as
evidenced by the large number of patents being issued.  This study
also points out that there is a high degree of competition between
chelant types.  A new class of materials, polyelectrolytes, are
also starting to be used in place of the traditional chelants.  In
the United States, Europe and Japan the banning of phosphates in
some areas for use in household detergents has caused an increase
in sales of other sequesterants/chelants.<P>

The markets for all of the chelants are well established and will
continue to grow, except that phosphate sales are declining.<P>

There have been a wide variety of clathrates discovered in research
laboratories worldwide over the past 50 years.  The purpose of this
study is to fathom out actual commercial use of clathrates, as well
as report research activity in this area.  There are 5 clathrates
used in commercial quantities--zeolites, cyclodextron, urea,
thiourea and crown ethers.  Markets for these are reported in this
study.<P>


<B>HISTORY OF THE MARKET</B><P>

The related subjects of sequestration/molecular complexing/chelation goes back to the origins of chemistry, when chemists inquired
if a compound was a true chemical compound or simply two compounds
joined by an electrostatic force.  These questions have not been
completely answered yet, and more research is being done, but most
of the answers have been obtained.  The whole purpose of chelation
is to immobilize unwanted chemicals, and the same thing is true of
clathration.  Thus, the two sciences are related, although the
mechanism of action is not the same.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF THE REPORT</B><P>

To quantify and qualify market data on chelates and clathrates for
the United States, with developments from Europe included, where
pertinent.  Included are specific market areas such as:  cleaning
compounds, detergent builders, water treatment and food use.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This study is divided into certain key chapters dealing with
mechanisms of action of chelates and clathrates, producers of these
materials, as well as applications:  Emphasis is given to areas
currently under research, and future trends.  Focus is on the
United States and environmental concerns.<P>


<B>VALUE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This comprehensive technical/marketing study will be valuable to
technical personnel, those in research and development, as well as
marketing and business managers and executives in the areas of
detergents, water treatment, pulp and paper, textiles, foods,
toiletries, cosmetics and metal finishing, and to government
agencies, legislative and governmental.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The information sources include an on-line search, NTIS search,
patent literature, available journals and magazines, producers'
literature and the world's technical journals.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Related BCC publications include:  C-145, New Surfactants for New
Applications; C-132A, Sorbent Materials for Spill Applications; C-
133, Sorbent Materials for Spills and Others for Spill
Applications; C-118R, Zeolites:  Markets and Opportunities.  BCC
also publishes a monthly newsletter entitled Microporous Materials
Technology News.<P>


<B>DISCLAIMER</B><P>

The authors assume no liability for the reported information or for
its use.  The development information is intended to be as reliable
as possible and of a professional nature.  The author assumes no
liability for any loss or damage as a result of any reliance on any
materials or any information developed.  This is not a legal or
accounting document and much of the information is of a speculative
nature.<P>

