<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-174  CLEANING COMPOUNDS:
HIGHLIGHTING ADDITICES TO SURFACTANTS IN THESE COMPOUNDS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-174  CLEANING COMPOUNDS:
HIGHLIGHTING ADDITICES TO SURFACTANTS IN THESE COMPOUNDS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DIRK MUYSKENS
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This technical/marketing study was prepared as an in-depth analysis to
forecast and track significant changes in detergent additive business and
technology.  The study describes the structure of the U.S. cleaning product
industry for both household, industrial, and institutional cleaners.  Sales
and composition of individual cleaner types are described.<P>

The consumption of cleaner additives is also described in this report and is
correlated with the cleaner type.  Thus the report has double value -- sales
of both formulated cleaners and detergent additives are discussed in the same
report.  This comprehensive report has value to sellers of cleaners and to
suppliers to cleaning formulating companies.  The format of the report
provides a context to examine, on a microscale, consumption of additives by
type of cleaner.<P>

The report describes the markets for cleaner additives.  These include
detergent builders, enzymes, brighteners, bleaching agents, chelates,
suspending agents, and diluents.  Surfactants used in individual cleaning
products are described.<P>


<CENTER><B>HISTORY OF THE MARKET</CENTER></B><P>

<B>FORMULATED CLEANERS</B><P>

Starting with soap, the original cleaning compound, the types of cleaning
products offered for sale have increased into the thousands.  Cleaners are
formulated to clean all types of substances -- metal, ceramics, wood, fabric,
and plastic -- in all types of environments -- home, factories, and
institutions.  They are designed to remove all types of stains and dirt --
food, rust, dust, and oil -- both by hand and by machine. This has led to the
need for cleaners with many different properties.  To name a few, variables to
be considered in the development of the formulation are alkalinity or acidity,
temperature of cleaning, expected water hardness, type of washing machine, and
cost of ingredients.<P>

These considerations have led to the development of hundreds of ingredients
available for the formulation of cleaners.  The cleaning formulation business
long ago became a partnership between chemical manufacturers and the
formulators.  The chemical companies would develop the additives.  There are
many steps in the development of an additive.  First, a manufacturing method
must be devised to make the product. Then, in order to sell the additive to
the cleaner companies, application data are needed.  Originally, suggested
formulas to utilize the ingredient and test methods for measuring efficacy
were sufficient.  Now toxicity data, biodegradability, and fish toxicity are
needed, in addition to cleaning performance data.  The price of ingredient is
also becoming more and more important.<P>

The formulator, armed with information on ingredient utilization, will adopt the
product only when environmental and cost/performance criteria have been met.<P>

At this time, introduction of new molecular moieties into the cleaner industry
has dropped to almost zero due to the very large testing costs.  Now the
formulators use the ingredients already available to formulate their products.
Due to the availability of literally thousands of approved ingredients, there
is still plenty of latitude to develop a detergent product to meet a need.<P>

Of course, packaging and advertising, in addition to cleaning performance, has
always played an important part in selling cleaners.  This is particularly
true in household cleaners.  Also important to formulators is recognizing a
new need for a cleaner, and then developing a cleaner to meet the need.  The
cleaner business has had a good track record in this.  The industry is one of
the leaders in product innovation. Introduction of liquid hand soaps, fabric
softeners, aerosols, automatic dishwash detergents, brushless spray-applied
car washes, and all-in-one laundry combination detergent/bleach are examples
of products to meet particular needs not previously recognized.  There will be
more of these.<P>

Of recent concern to household cleaning formulators is a lessening of brand
loyalty by customers to all consumer products, and buying primarily on price.
This had led to intense price competition and has coerced the large "soapers"
to alter merchandising procedures, such as reducing temporary price promotion
to supermarkets and reducing large-scale distribution of coupons.  The savings
from reduction of these promotions is applied to reduction of product price.
Other moves to save costs are the selling of concentrated cleaning products
that result in lowered packaging and transportation costs.<P>

In the I + I market the cleaning is done by employees and labor-saving
cleaning procedures have top priority.  Development of machines to quickly and
efficiently clean with the aid of cleaning compounds is important in all I + I
segments --janitorial, dishwashing, metal treating, laundry, sanitizing, and
vehicle washing.<P>


<B>CLEANING INGREDIENTS</B><P>

The turning point in detergent formulation came in the mid-1940's with the development of synthetic detergent-phosphate combination laundry products, led
by the Monsanto Co.  After this, no longer was laundry soap which left
harsh residues on clothes the laundry cleaner of choice.  Other important
milestones were the development of fabric softeners, detergent enzymes,
optical brighteners, dry chlorinated bleaches which supplied a solid form of
chlorine, suspending agents to prevent soil redisposition on clothing during
washing, and last but not least, the development of numerous synthetic
surfactants that met many requirements.  There are foaming and non-foaming
surfactants; ones that will remove particulate soils; ones that will remove
oily soils; and non-ionic, ionic amphoteric, and cationic detergents suitable
for formulating alkaline, neutral, and acidic detergents.<P>

<B>SCOPE OF THE REPORT</B><P>

This report (1) quantifies and qualifies technical and marketing data on
household and I + I cleaners and (2) quantifies and qualifies technical and
marketing data on additives to cleaners.<P>



<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This study is divided into certain key chapters dealing with the market for
household and I + I cleaners by type of cleaner, and a separate section
describing the use of 13 important detergent additives in cleaner compounds.
Emphasis is given to areas currently under research, and future trends.  Focus
is on the United States and environmental concerns.<P>

<B>VALUE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This comprehensive technical/marketing study will be valuable to technical
personnel, those in research and development, as well as marketing and
business managers and executives in the areas of detergents formulation and
marketing (both household and I + I).  Technical and marketing personnel in
chemical companies that sell products for cleaning applications, Government
agencies, and legislative groups will also find value in this report.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The information sources used in compiling this report included an on-line
search, an NTIS search, and a search of patent literature, journals and
magazines, and producers' literature available.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Related BCC publications include:  

<UL>C-145 - New Surfactants for New
Applications<BR> C-132A - Sorbent Materials for Non-Spill Applications<BR>
C-133 - Sorbent Materials for Spills and Other Liquid Pickups<BR>
C-173 - Chelates and
Clathrates<BR>
