<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-175: ELECTRONS ARE GREEN: OPPORTUNITIES
IN ELECTROCHEMICAL SYNTHESIS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-175: ELECTRONS ARE GREEN: OPPORTUNITIES
IN ELECTROCHEMICAL SYNTHESIS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Mark M. Morrison</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>
<I>Anna Crull
</I><BR>
PROJECT MANAGER
<P>
<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Applications of electrosynthesis in a variety of specialty organic and 
inorganic chemicals, chlor-alkali, and specialty products continue to show 
significant growth potential. Despite certain drawbacks in the area of chlor-
alkali chemicals, and certain risks associated with predicting specific use 
for the methods, and specific growth among developing chemical requirements, 
the use of these methods can be projected to experience significant change and 
growth over the next 5-10 years.<P>  

Although electrochemical methods have been used to produce more than two 
hundred chemical compounds, gases and metals, except for several notable 
exceptions, electrochemical methods are not employed as widely as might be 
expected.  This study shows that electrochemical methods have often been 
ignored or sidestepped when considering potential synthetic routes, ignoring 
potentially significant benefits and often failing to recognize unique 
opportunities at cost reduction for reagents, improvements in environmental 
impact, and improved product characteristics.  

For firms with the proper experience, insight, and people mix, there is 
significant upside growth potential.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

The present state for the use of electrochemical technology for synthesis has 
the potential for relatively rapid change.  There are important areas for 
growth in the use of the technology, and there are areas of some significant 
turmoil for marketing concerns, difficulty in evaluating technology, and lack 
of experience.  Because of the changes in the industry and the potential 
upside for use of electrosynthetic methods, a technology/marketing report 
update is needed.<P> 

This technology/marketing report emphasizes areas where electrochemical 
methodologies are presently used, and those areas where electrochemical 
methodologies should be considered for the first time or reconsidered.  This 
report puts emphasis on the growth areas of specialty organic chemicals and 
pharmaceuticals and inorganic chemicals, and the area of the associated 
instrumentation for electrosynthesis.  The traditional electrosynthetic 
stronghold of the chlor-alkali industry is reviewed and its troubled growth is 
forecast.  No evaluation is provided for electrorefined metals or other 
electrochemically generated gases, because of what are considered overall poor 
business opportunities.<P> 

This report describes the market growth, the developing technology trends, 
industry leaders, and industry needs.  This report is a complete description 
and review of the complex electrochemical industry.  To our knowledge, this 
study is unique in bringing essential features of developing technology 
together with present markets into a coherent evaluation of the entire 
electrochemical synthesis industry.<P> 


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report will be valuable to those involved in chemical synthesis in 
industry, to those involved in supplying instrumentation to the 
electrochemical industries, and to those evaluating competing technologies.  
Further it may provide valuable insight in experiences in "selling" the 
approach internally within an organization, to help to support and overcome 
internal opposition to unfamiliar technology with examples of success and 
failures.  The report should prove useful to those engineering firms which 
look into new business opportunities which may be amenable to electrosynthetic 
methodologies.  Producers and suppliers of competing production processes are 
provided with a valuable outline of what electrosynthesis can, and cannot, do.  
BCC and the analysts wish to thank those companies, agencies, and university 
researchers who have made information available and provided verbal 
information for this report.<P> 

<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report includes a section which covers some of the background material on 
electrosynthesis.  Specific areas of electrosynthesis are then divided into 
four general areas:<P>  

<UL><LI> Specialty organic chemicals, including polymers and pharmaceuticals<P> 

<LI> Inorganic chemicals other than chlor-alkali chemicals<P> 

<LI> Chlor-alkali chemicals; and<P>

<LI> Electrosynthesis equipment<P></UL> 

Evaluations of the mature, conventional technology electrorefined metals and
electrogenerated gases industries are specifically not included in this report.<P> 

The area of electrochemical synthesis is large and is a diverse business with 
many aspects which are clearly not interrelated except for the fact that 
electrochemical methodologies are used to make a reaction proceed. 
Conversations with experts the general area of electrosynthesis indicate that 
electrosynthesis deserves renewed interest and consideration.  While several 
firms in Europe have extensive histories in using and developing 
electrosynthetic methods for commercial projects, the enthusiasm among 
electrochemists has not been converted into extensive use in industry in North 
America, with a few notable exceptions.  And in fact, in some cases, there has 
been some movement away from electrosynthetic methods.<P>  

This study is aimed at assessing as completely and as fairly as possible the 
present and potential areas where electrochemical synthesis methods and 
equipment markets are used.  Information for this report was collected by 
extensive industry contact with people long active in the use of 
electrochemical methodologies for synthesis, by review of the technical 
literature, patent literature, computer-retrieved information, and the 
author's experience with electrosynthetic methods, especially in the area of 
organic synthesis.  Key portions of patents are abstracted and cited as 
appropriate to demonstrate trends and versatility.<P> 

This comprehensive technical/marketing report provides forecasts for 
electrochemically generated chemicals and the associated equipment market for 
the near-term (to 1998), and defines the key technical and industrial 
developments and changes in market activities and attitudes.  This document is 
intended to be as accurate in technical, economic, and business areas as 
possible.  The quoted technical data are dependent on the accuracy of the 
manufacturers.  This report is not intended to constitute a legal document, a 
specific business plan for any product, or an endorsement of any given product 
or process.<P>

Neither the author, nor BCC Inc., as the publisher, assumes any 
liability for loss or damage as a result of reliance on this material.  The 
author and project manager wish to thank all of the manufacturers, engineering 
companies, end-users, marketers, professors, chemists and engineers who have 
demonstrated such a high degree of cooperation.<P> 

This report is a publication of BCC Inc.  BCC also produces a number of 
industry newsletters and a variety of market and technology surveys.  Users of 
this marketing and technology report may find newsletters entitled "Separation 
Technology News" and "Battery and Electric Vehicle News," produced by BCC Inc. 
particularly significant in updating specific market and technology areas 
related to this study. Among other things these newsletters offer information 
related to membranes used in electrochemical synthesis and to the use of 
electrolytic manganese dioxide and other electrochemically synthesized 
materials in batteries.  The BCC Inc. study entitled "Advanced Batteries, GB-
086N" also should prove useful in understanding the interplay between the 
electrosynthesized material and the battery application.<P>

