<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>C-178  SURFACE DISINFECTANTS</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-178  SURFACE DISINFECTANTS</H2>

<HR><P>
<I>PHILIP ROTHIEM</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REPORT OBJECTIVES AND GOALS</B>

<P>The objectives of this report are twofold:</P>

 <P>a) To delineate the surface disinfectant industry in terms of
    products, suppliers, sales, and markets for the benefit of those
    unfamiliar with the industry or of those looking for a simple
    strategic overview;</P>

 <P>b) To provide significant value addition for those already in the
    surface disinfectant industry by assessing major issues shaping
    the industry's future and by making an independent,
    quantitative forecast.</P>

<P>The goals are to provide valuable data, analysis and insights of the highest caliber for business planning. </P>

<B>REASONS FOR STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTIO</B>

<P>Disinfectants have important roles in the control of infectious diseases, 
microbial food spoilage, and unwanted microbes generally. Today,
antimicrobial effectiveness and antimicrobial spectrum are no longer the sole 
criteria for judging surface disinfectants, and suppliers who ignore the new 
factors will be left behind.</P>

<P>Most analyses on sanitation and disinfection rely only on readily available data from the Census Bureau.  Most published studies do not segregate disinfectants from ordinary cleaners.  Most studies mix surface disinfectants with other types of antimicrobials.</P> 

<P>The industry itself often blurs the distinction between surface disinfectants and other types of products, partly due to misconceptions and partly due to the difficulty in making a proper distinction.  One of the contributions of this particular study is its use of a strict, microbiological definition of disinfectants and thus a restrictive analysis of the relevant product sales.</P>
  
<P>Thus, this study goes beyond the readily available data.</P>

<B>AUDIENCE FOR REPORT</B>

<P>This study is intended to serve the interests of senior executive management. Suppliers of formulated disinfectants, suppliers of bulk disinfecting chemicals, and others who are concerned about the quality of microbe control in the United States will find this report of value.</P> 

<B>STUDY'S SCOPE AND CONTENT</B>

<P>This study covers disinfectants for the surface treatment of inanimate 
objects. Included are disinfectants based on halogen compounds, quaternary 
amines, oxygen compounds, terpenes, and miscellaneous others.  We include 
sanitizers, janitorials, hospital disinfectants and cold sterilants.  We cover the consumer and the I&I markets and we cover the food, health, building maintenance and other sectors.</P> 

<P>Excluded from this study is any discussion or quantitation of antiseptics for skin, germicides for water treatment, antimicrobial preservatives, 
agricultural fungicides, and therapeutic antibiotics.  The virtue of this 
study is precisely its coverage of surface disinfectants without the confusion of mixing them with other antimicrobics.</P> 


<B>STUDY'S METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>This study is based on scientific literature about germicidal chemicals, 
company product literature, business literature on disinfectants, Commerce 
Department Census Bureau data on cleaners and sanitizers, and telephone 
interviews with individuals in companies in positions of sales, product 
management, and market management.  We independently analyzed available data 
and information, in order to focus specifically on surface disinfectants.</P> 

<P>Brand names are indicated in capital letters and, wherever possible, we 
indicate the disinfecting active agents.</P> 
  
<P>Average annual growth rates (AAGR) are derived by the compounding method using standard tables of present value.</P> 

<P>Our analyses, observations and assessments are made independently, without the bias of vested interests.  Mentions of products are not endorsements, and 
omissions, if any, are not intentional.</P> 


<B>PERSONNEL FOR STUDY</B>

<P>The writer is an experienced microbiologist with an additional formal 
background in chemistry.  His experience is mainly in industry rather than 
academia, and therefore he provides an emphasis on product sales and business 
growth.</P> 

<P>Besides the formal education in the sciences, the writer also has an MBA 
degree in marketing.  He is the writer of a related BCC report on microbial 
sterilization (heat, EtO, radiation, UV, filter sterilization), BCC's study on medical anti-infectives, and many other published studies in the medical, 
biotechnological, and chemical areas.</P> 


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B>

<P>Published BCC reports relating to this study's subject (written by the same author or by others) include the following:</P> 

<UL>
      <LI>C-002U:   Specialty Water-Treatment Chemicals
      <LI>C-084:    Microorganism Testing
      <LI>C-090:    Chemicals for the Detergent Industry
      <LI>C-092:    Medical Anti-Infectives and Biotechnology's Role
      <LI>GA-056R:  New Directions in Sterilization

</UL>


