C-179  SYNTHETIC FUNCTIONAL FLUIDS AND LUBRICANTS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-179  SYNTHETIC FUNCTIONAL FLUIDS AND LUBRICANTS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>JOHN BRUCE</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goal of this study is to provide an understanding of the synthetic
functional fluids and lubricants (synlubes) industry.  To do this, we must
focus on several objectives. These are to:<P>

<UL> <LI>  Clarify the structure of this specialty industry<P>
<LI>   Highlight forces causing changes in the synlube industry<P>
   <LI> Ascertain the importance of governmental regulations<P>
<LI>   Estimate products and applications markets for synlubes<P>
 <LI>  Assess synlube marketing strategy and tactics<P>
<LI>   Describe synlube manufacturing and applications technology<P>
<LI>   Evaluate the global significance of the synlube industry, and<P>
<LI>   Profile synlube manufacturers and users.</UL><P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Significant changes are occurring in major applications areas for synthetic
functional fluids and lubricants.  These changes are significantly altering
product acceptance criteria, which means:<P>

<LI>   Synlubes will be required in many applications which were
formerly satisfied  by petroleum oils, and<P>

<LI>   Higher-performance, more-expensive synlubes will be favored in many important
   applications.<P>

This report will detail these changes and assess their relative importance, thus
providing vital guidance to the host of participants in the synlube industry
who must deal with these trends.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study will enable:<P>

<LI>   Directors of Planning to appreciate the strategic significance of synlube
   operations and develop plans that are appropriate to the situation,
   to either augment, acquire, or divest these business segments,<P>

<LI>   Directors of Development to select candidates for potential joint ventures,
   mergers, or acquisitions,<P>

<LI>   Directors of Marketing to develop successful marketing strategies
  and tactics,
   Directors of Sales to organize sales territories and set the criteria
   for selecting
   synlube sales representatives,<P>

<LI>   Directors of Research & Development to select worthwhile targets for R&D
   projects,<P>
<LI>
   Directors of Engineering to become familiar with the broad spectrum
   of available synlubes and their applications, and<P>

<LI>   Directors of Purchasing to know all of the potential suppliers of
    synlube products.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study covers only synthetic functional fluids, hydraulic fluids and
lubricants, including:<P>

<UL> -  Organic esters, including vegetable oils<BR>
  - Synthetic hydrocarbons, including polyalphaolefins and polybutenes<BR>
 -  Phosphate esters<BR>
 -  Silicones and silicates<BR>
  - Polyalkylene glycols, and<BR>
  - Fluoropolymers and other specialized materials.</UL><P>

Both fully- and partially-synthetic functional fluids and lubricants are
covered in this report.  Consumption and projected demand quantities stated
include the mineral oil present in the partially-synthetic products as well as
minor quantities found in the fully-synthetic products.<P>

The study does not cover functional fluids and lubricants that are based on:<P>

<UL> -  Ordinary refined petroleum oil fractions<BR>
  - Super-refined petroleum oils<BR>
  - Oil-in-water or water-in-oil emulsions of petroleum oils<BR>
  - High-water-base hydraulic fluids and<BR>
  - Conventional transport-vehicle brake fluids and water-glycol hydraulic<BR>
  - Fluids, except the thickener portion of these formulations which
   is included with other polyalkylene glycols.</UL><P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

To gain cogent, correct, and current information for this study, our first
step was to obtain and read appropriate scientific and trade literature as
well as relevant product literature from synthetic functional fluids and
lubricants producers.  Next, we interviewed by telephone selected authors of
synlube articles, marketing or product managers for these materials, and
applications engineers.<P>

At that point, we organized the information we obtained from these sources,
formed preliminary conclusions, and verified our understanding of the details
of the synlubes industry with a  representative group of the marketing or
product managers and applications engineers previously contacted.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information sources in addition to the interview data referred to above for
this study include:<P>

1. The Government of the United States<BR>
<UL>     Department of Commerce<BR>
     Department of Defense<BR>
     Department of Energy<BR>
     Department of Labor<BR>
     Department of Transportation<BR>
     Environmental Protection Agency</UL><P>

2.  Trade Associations<BR>
<UL>     American Society for Testing and Materials (ASTM)<BR>
     Factory Mutual (FM)<BR>
     National Fire Protection Association (NFPA)<BR>
     National Fluid Power Association (NFPA)<BR>
     Society of Tribologists & Lubrication Engineers (STLE)<BR>
     Underwriters Laboratories (UL)<BR>
     International Standards Organization (ISO)</UL><P>

3.  Trade & Scientific Journals<BR>
<UL>     ASHRAE Journal<BR>
     ASTM Standards News<BR>
     Automotive Engineering<BR>
     Automotive Industry<BR>
     Chemical Engineering<BR>
     Chemtech<BR>
     Compressed Air<BR>
     Design News<BR>
     Engineering<BR>
     Heating/Piping/Air Conditioning<BR>
     Hydraulics & Pneumatics<BR>
     Hydrocarbon Processing<BR>
     Lubrication Engineering<BR>
     Machine Design<BR>
     Manufacturing Engineering</UL><P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The Project Leader, who is managing this study, has about 40 years of
experience in the chemical and chemical process industries.  About half of
that time was devoted to product development and technical service of
synthetic functional fluids, hydraulic fluids, and lubricants.<P>

The Project Leader's background includes the following areas of expertise:<P>

<UL>   Automatic transmission fluids<BR>
   Automotive crankcase lubricants<BR>
   Automotive brake fluids<BR>
   Fire-retardant hydraulic fluids<BR>
   Phosphate ester hydraulic fluids & lubricants<BR>
   Polyalkylene glycol hydraulic fluids and lubricants<BR>
   Steam turbine lubricants<BR>
   Steam turbine electrohydraulic control fluids<BR>
   Synthetic fiber lubricants, and<BR>
   Water-glycol hydraulic fluids.</UL><P>

The Project Leader is also a fully-qualified senior market researcher with
almost two decades of experience in this professional specialty.<P>

