<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-183: SUPERCRITICAL FLUIDS THEIR TIME HAS COME
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-183: SUPERCRITICAL FLUIDS - THEIR TIME HAS COME
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Gerian Park
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Using supercritical fluids to perform separations is a relatively
new technology with a large potential for growth.  Behind the
recent expansion in use are environmental concerns, such as the
need to eliminate organic solvents and the push to find
alternatives for incineration.  Another factor in its growing
popularity is the increase in demand for lowfat, low cholesterol
food products.  For these reasons, market opportunities are
improving in analytical laboratories and the food processing
industry.<P>  

The report provides an analysis of the supercritical fluid
industry.  Market forecasts will be provided for supercritical
fluid extraction, supercritical fluid chromatography, and
supercritical water oxidation.  The report will provide process
descriptions; discuss both commercial and developmental
applications; describe the major players in academia, government,
and industry; and suggest where research and development is headed.<P>

<b>PURPOSE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This report will provide the reader with insight into the direction
of the supercritical fluid industry.  From this report, the reader
should be equipped to identify business opportunities, be familiar
with the major players, and be knowledgeable about the improvements
in this aspect of separation science.<P>

This BCC study is intended for those who wish to review the state-
of-the-art in this area of separations technology.  The report is
for those who desire to learn the new and developing applications
and those who are interested in exploring opportunities for
commercialization.  The report will be of value to manufacturers,
companies interested in entering or expanding their involvement in
the supercritical fluid industry, and companies or laboratories
considering employing the processes for their own applications.<P>  

<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

In addition to providing the technologies and their markets,
companies, government agencies, and universities involved in
supercritical fluid extraction, chromatography, or water oxidation
are described.  Certain company profiles feature specific product
information.<P>  

In the case of supercritical fluid extraction, the services of
companies who have developed and commercialized specific processes
that rely on the technology, such as precision parts cleaning and
microcellular foams, will be highlighted.<P>  

Values of the market in this report are for the year given,
represent sales by companies in the marketplace, and are for the
United States only.  Projections are in terms of real dollars and
represent real growth.  Competition from other processes plays a
role in the success or failure of these novel techniques.  The
values are generally based on the best estimates of those involved
in the commercialization of the techniques.<P>  

<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Research for this report began with an in-depth analysis of
technical and business literature, as well as a review of the
history of the technology.  Interviews with industry experts,
company representatives, federal government researchers, and
university scientists provided the basis for an assessment of the
outlook for supercritical fluids.<P>

This report is of a professional nature and has every intent at
accuracy.  It is not to be considered an endorsement of any product
described.  Nor is it intended to constitute a legal or accounting
document.  Neither the author nor the publisher assumes any
liability for loss or damage as a result of reliance on this
material.<P>  

<b>RELATED BCC PUBLICATIONS</B><P>

Other BCC, Inc. reports of potential interest to the reader include:

<UL>C-107R Advanced Novel Separations<BR> 
C-114 U.S. Chromatography
Supply Business<BR>
GB-168 Market for Spectrometric Equipment<BR>
GA-
075 Membrane Technologies for Food Processing<BR>
C-11R
Electrically Driven Separations/Systems and<BR> 
GB-112R Inorganic Membranes<P></UL>
  Subscriptions to monthly BCC newsletters concerning
separation technology, such as "High-Tech Separation News";
"Membrane & Separation Technology News"; "Energy Conservation
News"; "Food Ingredient News"; and "Waste Treatment Technology
News" are available.<P>

