<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-184A: MARINE BIOPOLYMERS    
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-184A: MARINE BIOPOLYMERS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>John Dullea
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>
 
Most market studies of marine-derived biomaterials have been conducted as 
segments of much larger studies of subjects such as aquaculture, commercial 
opportunities from the oceans, hydrocolloids, gums, thickeners, water soluble 
polymers, biotechnology, etc.  Such studies, while useful, have taken a "broad 
brush" approach and have not provided in-depth analysis of the large, 
important and growing marine biopolymer and marine biotechnology sectors.  It 
is the intention of this report to address this shortcoming by focusing on 
each of these important and growing industries.  In Part 1, we provide a 
detailed analysis of the important commercial, marine-derived, biopolymers and 
in Part 2, we provide an in-depth analysis of products derived from marine 
biotechnology which have, or someday will have, significant commercial 
potential.<P>  

Other than the marine biopolymers, surprisingly few commercially significant 
biomaterials have been derived from marine sources.  This dearth of 
commercially successful marine materials is especially unusual when we 
consider that the oceans, which cover nearly three quarters of the earth's 
surface, are home to an incredible multitude of biologically diverse life 
forms.  Science has identified close to 200,000 species of marine algae, 
animal bacteria, fungi and viruses.  It is thought that as many as four times 
this number have yet to be identified.  The marine environment under which 
these organisms live and propagate has endowed them with genetic and 
biochemical properties which are quite distinctive when compared to their 
terrestrial counterparts.  We have scarcely begun to explore this huge 
Thus, this report endeavors to give the reader an accurate bearing on the 
overall reservoir of biodiversity,  the commercial and scientific value of 
which is potentially enormous. commercial potential which exists in our marine 
environment.  The primary objectives are:<P> 

<b>Marine Biopolymers</B><P>  

 <UL><LI>   To describe the marine biopolymer industry, its importance and 
          its future prospects.<P>

<LI>    To analyze the current and historical volume and value of  shipments of each commercially viable marine biopolymer in the major world market areas, i.e. Europe, North America, Japan and the rest of the    world.<P> 

<LI>    To analyze the past and present markets for each type of biopolymer           and forecast the volume and value in each key geographic market 
          through 1998.<P> 

<LI>   To analyze the changes impacting this industry and assess the outcome.<P>
     
<LI>    To describe manufacturing methods and economics for each biopolymer.<P>

<LI>    To describe recent technological developments in marine biopolymers 
          and the potential market consequences.<P>

<LI>   To discuss the driving forces influencing demand.<P>

<LI>    To analyze the end-use markets for each material and determine 
          the past, present and future share that each use represents.  
          To report on major competitive factors influencing change.<P> 


<LI>    To review exports, imports and apparent consumption for each material           in key  geographic markets.<P>
         
<LI>    To discuss regulatory and environmental issues and concerns.<P> 

<LI>   To search patent and literature files to uncover and report 
          on significant new developments in the field.<P> 

<LI>    To identify the key international manufacturers of each material 
          and to profile the most influential of these.<P> </UL>




<b>Products of Marine Biotechnology</B><P>

<UL><LI>    To thoroughly investigate, on a worldwide basis,  research activities
          and commercial developments in the field.<P>

<LI>    To identify and describe, through extensive patent and literature
          searches and through discussions with recognized experts in the
          field, novel marine products and  technologies which hold
          commercial promise.<P> 

<LI>    To report on the current and potential market for those marine
          biomaterials which are now commercially available and to assess the
          market potential for promising products which have been identified
          and described but which are not yet being commercially pursued.<P>  

<LI>   To identify those companies that are currently working or
          considering working on specific biomaterials or areas and their
          objectives.<P>

 <LI>    To discuss regulatory and environmental issues and concerns which
          impact the research, development and commercialization of
          promising products from marine biotechnology.<P></UL> 


<b>REASONS FOR THIS STUDY</B><P>


<b>Marine Biopolymers</B><P>

Among marine biopolymer producers, cost containment, modernized or new 
facilities and improved quality control measures have led to productivity 
gains and quality improvements across much of the industry; however, in all 
products but agarose, excess capacity has prevented the industry from seeing 
such efficiencies settle to the bottom line as improved profitability.  
Overcapacity is a vexing problem for the industry and only time and restraint 
on the part of producers and prospective producers will correct it.  

The participants in this industry need to be acutely aware of these 
developments to intelligently plan for the future.  This report brings these 
factors into focus and provides manufacturers, distributors, users, and raw 
material suppliers with the knowledge needed to make informed decisions 
relating to investment, procurement or material selection.<P> 


<b>Products of Marine Biotechnology</B><P>

Extensive work has been undertaken in recent years to investigate the largely 
untapped source of useful chemical substances present in the marine 
environment. The breadth of the work underway is vast as are the numbers of 
actual and potential commercial products.  By thoroughly researching 
literature, patent and other secondary sources and through discussions with 
major organizations, research institutions and universities, we have compiled 
an up-to-date listing and description of marine biomaterials that are either 
currently on the market or exhibit a clear potential for commercial 
development.  From this analysis we have made projections of volume and value, 
and have identified companies and organizations currently working on specific 
marine biochemical products or product categories.<P>

This compilation and 
description will provide a valuable service to those wishing to capitalize on 
the extensive research and development work that has been conducted in this 
area.  The pharmaceutical, biotechnology and research communities in 
particular will benefit greatly from this up-to-date compilation and 
appraisal.<P> 


<b>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THIS STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report is intended to provide up-to-date international market information 
concerning the production, distribution, regulation, use and competitive 
environment surrounding the marine biopolymers agar, agarose, carrageenan, 
alginate and chitin/chitosan.  It is further intended to inform those 
companies and organizations interested in obtaining a current assessment of 
the status and potential of novel products from marine biotechnology.<P>  

This report is an analysis and summation of interviews with hundreds of key 
industry officials, trade association representatives, consultants, users, and 
governmental personnel, as well as searches of patent and literature sources.<P> 

<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of this report is worldwide.  In the biopolymer sector, North 
America, Europe, Japan and the "rest of the world" are analyzed and reported 
upon separately. Because of its emerging status, we break out products of 
marine biotechnology into two categories, North America and the "rest of the 
world."<P>    

With a changing world order and the emergence of major economic powers in the 
Far East, we believe it is important to make a brief statement about the 
geographic areas used in our analysis of marine biopolymer volume and value.  
In prior studies on the subject, the delineation of Western Europe has been 
straightforward.  With the coming apart of the Soviet Union the situation is 
not nearly so clear.  Germany, for example, has essentially doubled in 
population with the incorporation of the former East Germany.  This change 
obviously must be considered when assessing the use and growth projections for 
marine biopolymers in Western Europe.<P>   

Many of the former East European countries, Poland, Hungary and Slovakia for 
example, are beginning to move out of their third world status.  In fact, the 
other former East Block countries represent a huge population and industrial 
base which is a growing consumer of certain marine biopolymers, most notably 
agar and alginates. Also, Russia, The Ukraine, Georgia and the other now 
autonomous states of the former Soviet Union must ultimately be considered as  
geographically significant markets in studies such as this.  Quite frankly, 
the situation is too muddy and the data too difficult to uncover for us to 
take on this challenge.  Thus, we have included usage of marine biopolymers by 
all states of the former Soviet Union under the "rest of the world" heading 
for purposes of this report.<P> 

Similarly, while we consider Japan to be an identifiable and quantifiable 
geographic market for this study, the huge and technologically sophisticated 
geographic market of the Western Pacific Rim is also considered to fall under 
the "rest of the world" category, as are Africa, South America, the countries 
of the Middle East and the Indian subcontinent.<P>  


Interestingly, in spite of their size,  these regions do not as yet contribute 
significantly to the consumption of marine biopolymers.<P> 

The report begins with an introductory chapter which is followed by separate 
sections covering Parts 1 and 2.  Each part includes a summary chapter 
followed by Industry Overview, Regulatory Issues, Shipment Trends, 
Technological Issues, International Issues, Industry Structure and Profiles of 
Key Manufacturers.<P>  


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The extensive research capabilities of the BCC staff were accessed to analyze 
markets, consumption trends and supply and demand.  New technologies, market 
developments and present and future trends were identified through patent and 
literature searches and discussions with key industry sources.  Current 
regulatory and environmental issues were ascertained through discussion with 
industry sources, relevant regulatory agencies and literature searches.  
Manufacturing methods, process economics, international trade statistics and 
major influences on the industry were derived from discussions with a wide 
range of industry and government sources.<P> 


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The substance of this report is based on interviews with principal 
participants in the industry.  Over 200 sources were contacted, including raw 
material suppliers, manufacturers of marine colloids and biomaterials, agents 
and distributors, consumers, and governmental agencies.<P>


