<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-186 Polysaccharides
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-186 Polysaccharides</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>George Innes</I><BR>
Project Analyst
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

This report presents the findings of an analysis of the U.S. market for
polysaccharides.<P>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report is intended to bring to the reader a detailed analysis of 
industrial and consumer applications of polysaccharides, with emphasis on 
future trends, changing technology, and opportunities.<P> 

The major objectives of this study are as follows:<P>
<UL>     -  To make available the most current and reliable information on
        consumption of polysaccharides.<P>
     -  To forecast the market for these applications, broken down
        insofar as possible by end use and by individual product or
        product group.<P>
     -  To identify the most rapidly changing applications and the reasons for
        their growth or decline.<P>
     -  To describe the major trends in the end uses.<P>
     -  To provide a description of the most important companies
        supplying polysaccharides.<P></UL>

<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Although there have been previous studies of polysaccharides, most have 
focused on specific products or markets.  Few have attempted to cover the 
entire field, to show the broad scope of their end uses and the variety of 
their structures.  Since these products represent a renewable source of raw 
materials, they should have an interesting future.<P> 


<b>SCOPE</B><P>

This report will cover all important polysaccharides and their major 
derivatives. However, it will not include plastics made from cellulose esters.<P> 

<b>METHODOLOGY AND SOURCES OF INFORMATION</B><P>
Information on market size, growth rates, technological trends, and regulatory
influences was obtained from interviews with key marketing personnel with 
suppliers of polysaccharides.  Selected end users were also interviewed. 

Secondary sources include published government data, and reviews of trade 
journals such as "Chemical & Engineering News," "Chemical Marketing Reporter," 
and "Food Technology."<P> 

Product literature from selected major suppliers was also reviewed.<P>

<b>UNITS</B><P>
All forecasts are given in constant 1993 dollars.  Growth rates are compounded
annually.<P>

Trade names are shown in upper case letters.<P>


</PRE>

