C-204 THE NEW BIOPESTICIDE MARKET
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODU>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-204 THE NEW BIOPESTICIDE MARKET
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ERIKA SMITH</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<I>ANNA CRULL</I><BR>
PROJECT MANAGER
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>
                              
                                                            
<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This technical/marketing study was prepared as an analysis
to forecast and trace the significant changes in the
pesticide and agricultural chemical business, as well as
document the emerging trend toward integrated and low-input
agriculture.  Changes in the concepts of hard and soft
pesticides are coming about as new "biorational" control
measures become available.  This report identifies these
expanding technological innovations and evaluates the impact
of governmental regulations and legislative actions.  It
then projects what these developments mean for
manufacturers, suppliers and users of pesticides and crop
protection chemicals in terms of alternative agriculture.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Rapid changes are coming about in the conventional crop
protection business as well as in what chemicals are allowed
for use.  This study identifies the emergence of biocontrol
products against a framework of alternative agriculture and
integrated pest management concepts.  This
technical/marketing report examines the viable alternatives
to traditional hard (chemical) pesticides in the form of
biologically based, or soft, pesticides.  These are
presumably safer to the environment and less likely to cause
resistance in pest populations.  Pesticides, by type,
include fungicides, insecticides and herbicides.  These
compounds have continued to come under close government
scrutiny and public attack.<P>

The crop protection chemical business remains a market
sector that the world cannot adequately live without, and,
on the other hand, one that the world is very uncomfortable
living with. While a boon to farmers and the world's food
supply, many chemical-based pesticides persist in the
environment long after they have served their purpose.
These toxic chemical residues may show up in the food we
eat, the air we breathe and the water we drink, posing
serious health threats.  Increasing public awareness of
these dangers has prompted stricter government curbs on the
chemcial pesticides in both the U.S. and abroad.  Many
insect and weed populations have developed resistance to
chemical pesticides after years of use.  Still, effective
pest control is crucial to maintaining our food supply and
the financial stability of the agricultural market.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF REPORT</B><P>

This technical/marketing report will quantify and qualify
the market information for biorational pesticides for the
United States.  Included are specific market sectors such as
botanicals, pheromones, insect growth regulators, microbials
and genetically engineered products.  This report identifies
the state-of-the-art and market value for biological
pesticides in the U.S. and examines how this is impacting
agriculture in terms of low-input sustainable agriculture
and integrated pest management.  This is put into context by
looking at the total value of the U.S. pesticide market
including both the chemical pesticides and the newer concept
soft pesticides.<P>




<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The information for this study is drawn from interviews with
individuals in the companies involved with bringing the new
biological pesticides to the marketplace, literature
searches, the patent literature and government files and
records for the more traditional crop protection chemicals.
Historical figures are for the year given.  In so far as
possible, projections are based on reasonable price
assumptions for the use of the products.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

Once it is realized that agricultural pests and diseases are
not going to just go away, then there can be some ordered
program for coming to grips with the problem without
environmental or economic hysteria.  The crop protection
business continues to change because pests themselves elicit
different responses that must be made.  As there is a
general decline in the use and profitability of the chemical
pesticides, there is a rise in the new and more profitable
technology associated with biological controls.  New markets
are opening up in more effective control of agricultural
pests.<P>

This comprehensive technical/marketing study will be
valuable to technical personnel, those in research and
development, as well as marketing and business managers in
the areas of crop protection chemicals.<P>


