<CENTER><H2>DSC95 STEREOCHEMICAL INDUSTRY REVIEW
</H2>

<HR><P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

The implications of the revolution in stereochemistry may be
more profound than biotechnology.<P>

A  hidden  but  surging  new industry  is  transforming  the
chemical,   pharmaceutical,  and  biotechnology  industries.
Chiral,  cis/trans, regiospecific, syn/anti and other  forms
of  stereochemical  isomerism will  have  enormous  economic
impact.<P>

Chemists  have long known that an organic molecule can  vary
in  special arrangements. And they have long been aware that
these isomers of the same chemical can vary significantly in
biological activity and chemical activity. But now they have
learned to synthesize pure forms of isomers. This technology
has  now  become  one  of  the  hottest  areas  of  chemical
research.  Key patents are flowing from the labs;  sales  of
new  products  are growing in excess of 10% a year  and  are
rapidly approaching the billion dollar mark.<P>

Analysts  are  not  just making blue  sky  predictions.  The
promise  of  stereochemistry is very real-and  it  is  being
realized.    More   effective  drugs,   higher   specificity
pesticides, purer colors and dyes, and advanced flavors  and
aromas    are    already   being   produced.   Biochemicals,
petrochemicals,  surfactants,  liquid  crystals,  and   even
polymers  are  benefiting. Suppliers,  from  instrument  and
intermediate  producers to manufacturers and  developers  of
separation technologies, are also poised for profits.<P>



This publication includes:<P>

<UL>
     <LI>Stereoselective Synthesis, eparations, Analysis
     <LI>Catalysts and Transformation Agents
     <LI>Technology, including Patents, Tech Transfer
     <LI>Raw Materials and Intermediates
     <LI>Reaction Strategies
     <LI>Regulations: Latest Developments
     <LI>Markets, Trends, Analysis
     <LI>Applications: Drugs, Pesticides, Aroma and Flavor
       Compounds, Biochemicals, Liquid Crystals, Polymers, Others
     <LI>Industry News: Who, What, Why
     <LI>Research Developments
</UL>

It  keeps  you up to date in this fast changing  technology.
Key licenses and technology transfer offerings are featured;
supply  and demand for new materials, products and processes
are covered; new instruments and separation technologies are
described.<P>




