<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>G-112R AUTOMATIC IDENTIFICATION SYSTEMS:
               GROWTH MARKETS- A Major Enabling Technology for the 90s</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-112R AUTOMATIC IDENTIFICATION SYSTEMS:
               GROWTH MARKETS- A Major Enabling Technology for the 90s</H2>
<HR><P>
<I>ROBERT MORAN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST<P>
                             
                           
<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>

<P>BCC's goal in conducting this study was to determine the current
status of the  market for automatic identification systems and
assess their growth potential  over a six year period from 1994 to
2000.  We were particularly interested in  the types of technology
and kinds of applications being used by leading  industries to
identify products and people.<P> 

Our major objective was to present a comprehensive analysis of the
current  automatic ID industry and project its future course.</P>  

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B>

<P>Since BCC's 1988 study of this market entitled "Automatic
Product/People  Identification: Systems, Hardware," improvments in
technology have been made.   A variety of new and improved
products has been introduced and the industry  has expanded beyond
the identification and data collection stage.  At the same  time,
pressures for increased productivity and cost-efficiency have
heightened  the demand for more complete systems.</P> 

<P>BCC decided to examine the current position of automatic ID
systems  used in  key industries.  We were interested in what
technologies were being used to  meet the demands for
competitiveness.</P> 


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B>

<P>We assembled a study of the seven leading types of automatic ID
technologies  used.  For each technology, we discuss its
operation, examine the  applications, discuss its advantages,
weigh the competitive aspects, identify  factors that will drive
demand, and assess the potential for growth.  We then  project
sales and revenue for all seven technologies by type and by
industry.   This study will be of interest to those in the
business of making automatic  identification equipment and media,
general manufacturers, retailers,  transportation equipment
makers, the medical industry, government  administrators, and
those in financial services.  It will also be of interest  to
computer makers, software companies and system integrators.</P> 


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>The scope of this study encompasses bar coding, biometrics,
magnetic striped  and smart cards, radio frequency, optical
character recognition, machine  vision, and voice recognition.  We
define these various automatic  identification technologies and
explain how they work.  The applications are  described and
quantified for each industry segment.  The limitations and 
proposed solutions for each automatic ID technology are discussed.</P> 

<P>We analyze the competitiveness of each technology in relation to 
standardization, economic considerations, and the potential for
application  expansion.  The advantages of each technology are
also explored.  Growth  factors for each industry segment are
identified and their impact on the  future is discussed.  Sales of
each type of Automatic ID technology are  estimated and also
allocated by industry segment.  The value of these sales is  also
projected.  The impact of software is presented and its relative
cost is  analyzed. Technological issues and trends are reviewed
and other influential  factors such as the economic climate are
discussed.</P> 

<P>BCC also presents an industry overview, profiles of major
Automatic ID  manufacturers and industry associations, an appendix
of vendors by technology,  and a glossary of terms.</P>      
  

<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>BCC presents an analysis of the unit sales and their value by type
of  Automatic ID technology.  Our estimated value is what
customers have paid in  current dollars.  Then, based on our
surveys, we analyze the market factors by  technology and industry
segment, calculate estimates for growth, and forecast sales for
1994 and 2000.</P>   


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>BCC surveyed approximately 100 companies to obtain the data for
this report.   Included were manufacturers of Automatic ID
equipment, software vendors,  computer manufacturers, and
companies in various industries who use the  technology. 
Additional data for this report were obtained from government 
information, trade associations, industry and financial sources,
and an  exhaustive review of technical papers.</P>  


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B>

<P>Several other BCC reports are related to this topic.  They are:
G-132 "Credit  and Debit Cards," G-143 "U.S. Security and
Surveillance Markets," G-179  "Electronic Banking Systems: Present
Status, Future Prospects," and G-131  "Wireless
Communications-Update." </P>


