<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-133  TELECOMMUNICATIONS RETAIL OPPORTUNITIES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-133  TELECOMMUNICATIONS RETAIL OPPORTUNITIES</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS RUSH</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>
<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

There has been a boom in business use of telecommunications for the
last two decades that is beginning to foster lower equipment and
services costs that will allow many of the uses to find a niche in the
residential market. Our goal in this report is to show how the
declining prices for all elements are fostering a new market for
telecommunications--the home.<P>

We hope to provide the reader with some of the background, technology,
and services development that will foster "The Coming Retail
Communications Explosion." We provide a comprehensive assessment of
all factors of market development, including both equipment and
services.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

We believe there are certain trends underway that will blur the
distinction between residential and business telecommunications that
has existed for many years. Sales of cellular services, facsimile
units, personal computers, and similar new technology, have made
marketeers realize that the home of tomorrow may well be an extension
of the office of today. It is our outlook that telecommunications will
play a vital role in blurring the line between residential (what we
choose to call retail) and business use of new technology.<P>

Businesses have had the advantage in recent years of (l) the breakup
of the Bell System as we knew it in 1984; (2) the subsequent rise of
competitive carriers in the long-distance market; and (3) the rapid
implementation of microelectronic technology in all forms of computing
and communications applications. As a result, volumes for all forms
of technology and service have risen, with a related drop in pricing.<P>

This technology and pricing trend must have some spillover for the
non-business sector, which we choose to call retail. We chose five
application areas out of many potential areas for analysis and study.
These five should provide the reader with sufficient trends and
forecasts to allow related projections of similar telecommunications
applications for the retail sector.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report is intended to show how implementation of retail services
may evolve, especially for the five application areas studied. It
covers these five applications with a broad overview: noting issues,
technology, background, similar services, examples of today's users,
and l0-year projections of revenue for all parties -- equipment
suppliers, information providers, local and long-distance telephone
companies --with breakdowns of both units and sales dollars, where
applicable.<P>

It is intended as a planning tool for equipment manufacturers,
carriers, and information providers, and should be useful for
investors, analysts, regulatory bodies, and trade associations that
are involved in any way with the telecommunications industry.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of this report is retail telecommunications in the United
States. There are examples of similar retail implementations springing
up around the world that support our outlook, although not covered.
The report covers in-depth analyses of (l) payphones, (2) electronic
directory services, (3) voice mail, or messaging as provided by
telephone companies, (4) 900 and 976-type services, and (5) home video
communications.<P>

The format includes a review of the background of telecommunications
growth that leads in some manner to either the implementation of
technology and/or the lowering of prices, a thorough discussion of
each application area, lO-year forecasts of all aspects of growth, and
some of the issues or drivers that may either deter or accelerate
growth. All dollar figures are in current United States dollars.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Our approach in determining the forecasts embodied in this report is
to assess the total potential market, recognize that evolution (not
revolution) is most appropriate for the retail or residential sector,
and to derive forecasts accordingly. We attempt as fine a breakdown
of related factors as is feasible, and also note many of the positive
and negative issues that confront such evolution. Our assumptions are
noted so that the analyst can change to other assumptions and alter
our forecasts, if appropriate.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC has compiled this report from interviews of industry executives,
current literature, attendance at seminars and tradeshows, and
interviews of industry executives. In addition, BCC has authored many
similar reports on the telecommunications industry, and has extensive
in-house expertise in all of the aspects of this report.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

BCC has not previously focused on the retail sector of
telecommunications directly. We see this as a new and unique
contribution, as this market is in its infancy. Our prior reports on
Wireless Communications, Local Area Networks, and Private Networks
gave us some of the background presented in this report. BCC continues
to provide its customers with leading-edge information.</B><P>

