<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-134  VASTs: A RESURGING OPPORTUNITY FOR THE FADING
SATELLITE INDUSTRY</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-134  VASTs: A RESURGING OPPORTUNITY FOR THE FADING
SATELLITE INDUSTRY</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS RUSH</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

VSATs (very small aperture terminals) are not an industry by
themselves--they tie-in and complement the satellite industry.
VSATs also do not just form two-way data networks, but come in
receive-only data and video versions. Many other reports have
treated this subject as an isolated phenomenon, apart from the
satellite industry, and as exclusively a two-way data event. In
this report we wish to show all the inter-relationships. Therefore,
we present a complete assessment of the satellite industry along
with a thorough review of all types and markets for VSATs.<P>

In so doing, we have compiled a comprehensive assessment of the
market factors for both satellites and VSATs, a review of
justification for all types of VSATs, a separation of the key
players from those that have limited capabilities, market sizings
in all aspects of both equipment and services, and one of the most
complete and up-to-date research of VSAT users ever presented.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

We believe that VSATs are the predecessors of many new applications
afforded to users having direct links to satellites. Today, VSATs
are being increasingly used by governmental and commercial entities
to both save money over terrestrial alternatives and to accomplish
forms of communication not feasible on terrestrial transmission
facilities.<P>

We see a trend in VSAT equipment of decreasing prices; a trend
toward digitization of television signals; and a potential for
mobile and low-earth-orbit satellites -- all of which should assist
the satellite owners and operators to turn to one of the key
revenue producers they have for the future: VSATs.
In another respect, without VSATs satellite operators are facing at
best a slow growth industry, and more likely, a no growth industry.
We cover not only the VSAT outlook, but also the total satellite
industry outlook in this report.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

The study of VSATs includes all technical aspects pertinent to the
market, a review of the satellite industry and an assessment of
capacity based on transponder usage, history of all -aspects of
VSATs, a full discussion of key players along with market share,
future and international trends, and realistic ten-year forecasts
of each segment of the VSAT market with installed networks by
customer name as a base.<P>

This report is primarily oriented to those directly involved with
the satellite industry, satellite operators, service providers, and
earth station suppliers. However, we have a complete listing of
VSAT users and a discussion of VSAT economics which should be of
interest to anyone considering the implementation of any type o f
a VSAT network. Our discussion of the impact of VSATs on the
terrestrial carriers should interest all carriers in understanding
the potential for lost revenue. All suppliers of electronic and
radio frequency components used in VSATs should find the realistic
market projections in this report helpful in their planning. Those
involved with installation and maintenance of VSATs will find in
this report a complete outlook of this segment of the business.<P>

Investors, regulators, market analysts, and trade associations
should find this report a comprehensive review of the topic and an
aid to their endeavors.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

Our particular focus in this report is all three types of VSAT
networks--receive-only data, receive-only television, and two-way
data--for the United States. We also cover the international
market issues and potential in summary form.<P>

The format includes consistent forecasts of market-generated demand
for the years 1991 to 2001, along with a calculation of the
resulting average annual growth rate, called AAGR. All dollar
figures are shown as current (1991) United States dollars. We
include all of the assumptions behind our forecasts.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Our approach to determining the forecasts embodied in this report
is to assess the pricing trends, the total potential market, and
the vendors' and service providers' abilities to implement
networks, and to derive our numerical analysis accordingly. We do
not use any form of direct compound growth--rather our
calculation of AAGR is taken after our forecasts are complete. In
researching the information for this report, we were diligent to
uncover every installed VSAT network and the quantity of terminals
in each. This installed base formed the foundation for our
forecasts. In addition we not only discuss the potential for each
market segment, but also note the probable issues or risks that
might affect such an outlook negatively.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

In accomplishing the research for this report we found useful
information in trade press articles, other reports, press releases,
vendor and supplier brochures, and related documents. In addition
we interviewed a key executive in many of the leading VSAT supplier
companies. Interviews of speakers and exhibitors at seminars and
trade shows were also used for sources.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Prior reports by BCC on Wireless Communications, Satellites, and
Private Networks were all used in some fashion to form the
background material for this report. The author's extensive
background in the satellite industry in general, and VSATs in
particular, were a key asset in pin-pointing key factors of the
VSAT market. BCC continues to publish strategic reoirts on all
sectors of the telecommunications markets.<P>



