<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-137 LONG DISTANCE MARKETS, 2001
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-137 LONG DISTANCE MARKETS, 2001
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS RUSH</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The long distance market has undergone considerable change in the
last 10 years. It has matured to the point that three carriers
share over 95% of the net revenue. The long distance
business is poised for growth into the 21st century, and our goal
in this report is to assess both the total and the underlying
factors that will accelerate that growth. We also note issues that
may cause growth of particular areas, or carriers, to be different
from the total market.<P>

There is also a need for common language when addressing the many
different services and opportunities, and we include necessary
background and explanation of applications and services to
establish a basis for comparison.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The year 2001 has been somewhat an intriguing year, with many
futuristic scenarios of what not only telecommunications but the
entire environment will be in that year. We felt a comprehensive
study on a part of that environment--the long distance industry in
the United States--would add to our understanding of the future. We
also wished to take many of the future scenarios and assess them
with realistic analyses as to how do we get from here to there.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report deals only with the long distance business, but
recognizes the many factors that affect that business, particularly
the emerging international services opportunities for the countries
on the European and Asian continents. In assessing applications
that will drive this market we include background of each
application along with requisite equipment, so that all aspects of
potential growth are covered.<P>

This report is complete in its approach to the potential of the
long distance market. It is written for both local and long
distance carriers, equipment suppliers, regulators, and analysts
that desire a comprehensive view of all the factors that will
influence the long distance market.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

Our emphasis in this report is the United States long distance
market, recognizing that (1) international service is a significant
growth area for domestic carriers, and (2) local telephone
companies provide the gateway to long distance service.<P>

The report includes consistent forecasts of market-generated demand
for the years 1991 to 2001, along with the resulting calculation of
average annual growth rate, AAGR. All dollar figures are shown in
current United States dollars. We include all assumptions behind
our forecasts.<P>

<B>METHODLOGY</B><P>

Our approach to determining the forecasts embodied in this report
is to assess the pricing trends, past history, and potential
drivers and issues, along with availability and price of requisite
equipment, in order to derive our numerical analysis. We do not use
any form of direct compound growth--rather our calculation of AAGR
is taken after the forecasts are complete. In researching the
information for this report we used reported information where
available and our estimates where necessary. We break down the
total market into service segments, showing forecasts, issues, and
drivers for each.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

In accomplishing the research for this report we found useful
information in trade press articles, annual reports, FCC reports
and filings, vendor and supplier literature, and related documents.
In addition, we interviewed key executives in the industry,
attended seminars, discussed applications at trade shows, and used
our background in this industry to assure completeness.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Prior reports by this author for BCC on Satellites, VSATs, and
Private Networks were all used in some fashion to form the
background material for this report. The author's extensive
background in the long distance market was the key factor in
assessing the key issues and drivers for a comprehensive outlook.
BCC continues to publish strategic reports on all aspects of the
telecommunications market.<P>

