<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-138  VIDEO COMMUNICATIONS INTO THE 21ST CENTURY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-138  VIDEO COMMUNICATIONS INTO THE 21ST CENTURY
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>THOMAS RUSH</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Recognizing that volumes of sales will drive down equipment costs for video
communications, and also recognizing that communications costs are coming down
dramatically, the area of video communications should flourish as the key
telecommunications application of the 1990s, and continue into the 21st century.<P>

Our objective is to give the reader both the background, market sizing,
pricing forecasts, and related factors to make a comprehensive assessment of
the future for video communications. We offer a 10-year outlook of this
subject, together with reviews of vendors, technology, and the background
related to video communications.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

For some time analysts have referred to the five generations of computers--generations that spoke to the technology of computer components: tubes, integrated circuits, chips, large scale integration of circuits, and very
large scale integration. The favorite comparison is to note that a computer of
the 1960s can be contained on a single VSLI chip of today.<P>

This same evolution has spurred the development of video communications. The
"generations" of video communications can better be classified in their use,
although technology has played an important part in the cost and convenience
of use. This report is oriented more toward use, with the four generations of
video communications evolving from the (1) permanent room with controllable
audio/video systems, to the (2) rollabout or temporary cabinet for quick
upgrade of any room into a video communications setup, to the (3) desktop
personal computer where some of the processing and display are combined with
the computer, to the (4) standalone unit where the video is built-in with the
handset (this latter group is referenced in this report as "residential,"
although we see both desktop and standalone units being bought by either
commercial or residential customers).<P>

The first two generations have occurred and were designed primarily with the
business or national organization in mind, while the latter two are still
emerging and apply to residential customers, as well.<P>

In like manner, the world of communications is evolving. The analog carriage
of the past is being replaced with digital  transmission capabilities. This
report's forecast is based on the coincidence of digital transmission with
video compression in digital form. We cover the background of both, and note
that the years 1994 through 1996 will be key to video communications--years
in which all the video development will be mature, and in which a significant percentage of local carriers will convert to an ISDN (Integrated Services Digital Network) interface.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

We include all aspects of video communications--business television,
conference room systems, desktop systems, and standalone (residential) units--and offer separate discussions and forecasts for each. It is intended as a source of background and forecast for vendors of video compression devices and audio/video support systems, computer manufacturers, long distance carriers, local telephone companies, and similar organizations involved with the future of video communications.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report covers only the growth of video communications in the United
States, briefly noting the international impact. All figures are based on 1992 U.S. dollars.<P>

Following a comprehensive section on the background of both video transmission and telecommunications trends, the report addresses the four sections of the market individually: business television, conference room systems, desktop systems, and residential (standalone) units. Vendors, technology trends and user requirements, users and applications, and forecasts are discussed for each of these four groups.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

We note all our assumptions in the discussion of forecasts. These assumptions include pricing, unit sales, installed inventories, and, where applicable, trends or dependencies on related factors, such as the conversion to digital by local telephone companies.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC has compiled this report from research of available literature, interviews of leading industry experts and vendor representatives, attendance at seminars and tradeshows, and combined that input with the experience of the author, who has been personally involved with the video communications evolution.<P>

<B>OTHER BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Although this is the first BCC report on video communications, that subject has been covered as key to both satellite and long distance revenues, as discussed in the BCC reports: G-134, VSATs; G-109, ISDN; and G-136, Long Distance.<P>

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
<H3>TABLE OF CONTENTS</H3></CENTER>
